<HEADLINE>
LACKLUSTER DEVILS HAPPY WITH A TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Who could blame Devils' supporters for
being inspired as the Atlantic Division leaders came home after
notching four victories in a five-game road trip? And who could
blame those fans for being disappointed Friday night by the team's
uninspiring performance against the Montreal Canadiens, who are in
last place in the Northeast Division?
</P>
<P>
   Playing down to Montreal's level until the latter stages of the
third period, when they finally raised their intensity, the Devils
salvaged a 1-1 tie before a crowd of 16,268 at Continental Arena,
and said afterward that they considered themselves lucky to escape
with the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Andreychuk scored the tying goal for the Devils with 1
minute 53 seconds left in regulation, when his shot from the top of
the right circle found its way behind Montreal goaltender Jeff
Hackett, who faced 38 shots, including four in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' letdown came after a trip in which they registered
victories at Carolina, Dallas, Colorado and Washington, and lost at
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all mental,'' said Andreychuk, who scored his
seventh goal of the season. ``You come home and you think it's
going to be easy. You got your fans behind you and you sleep in
your own bed, but it doesn't work. I wish I had an answer for it.
All I know is we got away with a tie and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rolston was also happy with the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well,'' he said. ``We weren't on top of our
game. We played well only late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Malakhov scored for the Canadiens (9-13-2) against
Martin Brodeur, who faced 22 shots, including one in overtime,
while keeping the Devils (14-8-1) in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Pandolfo appeared to have scored a goal with 1:47 left in
overtime for the Devils, but the goal was disallowed as the video
replay showed that the puck was kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played with little intensity around each other's net
in the scoreless first period. Each goaltender faced nine shots,
none too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was making his sixth start in the seven games since he
and Eric Weinrich joined the Canadiens from Chicago in exchange for
Jocelyn Thibault. Hackett looked sharp in the first two periods
with 21 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Making his ninth consecutive start, Brodeur looked sharp, too.
His only blemish was Malakhov's goal with 4:55 left in the second
period on a shot in which Brodeur was screened by two Devils and
never saw the puck.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils played the last two periods with five defensemen
after Kevin Dean, who came off the injured reserve list after
missing three games, reaggravated his groin injury. With Dean out,
the other New Jersey defensemen saw plenty of ice time, with Scott
Stevens leading the way. Stevens was the best defenseman for the
Devils on the five-game trip, especially in the victory at Denver,
where he broke up several rushes by the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   The Devils will visit the Islanders Saturday night for the
second time this season. The game will be the 934th in the National
Hockey League for KEN DANEYKO, tying JOHN MACLEAN's Devils record. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
