<HEADLINE>
UCLA POISED FOR OKLAHOMA ST.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's no longer considered much of a classic and no
longer nationally televised, but it still carries John Wooden's
name and includes UCLA, so there remains some level of prestige for
today's Wooden Classic at the Pond in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th-ranked Bruins might be the local draw, but even their
highly anticipated matchup with 11th-ranked Oklahoma State took a
hit this week when the Cowboys lost their first game of the season
to lowly Florida Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a recruit call us the other night and say, `Florida
Atlantic beat you? That sounds like an airline,' '' Oklahoma State
coach Eddie Sutton said. ``Our team is really overrated. If we were
playing in a 6-6-and-under league, we would have a really good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The 83-81 loss to Florida Atlantic in Stillwater, Okla., broke
the Cowboys' 80-game home winning streak, which had been the
longest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised, but when you look across the country at
scores, that's a real example of the parity that exists,'' UCLA
coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   But once Lavin began discussing Oklahoma State, one had to
wonder how much parity exists between the Bruins (3-2) and Cowboys
(4-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie Sutton is one of the top five coaches in the country. We
have the youngest coaching staff in America,'' Lavin said. ``It's
going to be a grinder game. Like the Green Bay Packers, three yards
and cloud-of-dust type of game. If it gets to an up-tempo game,
maybe our athletes can keep us in it.''
</P>
<P>
   That last remark prompted an unsolicited remark from John
Wooden, who was sitting next to Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a coach talks about the opposing team, they sound so
good, it's like you shouldn't even be playing the other team,''
Wooden said. ``When they talk about their own teams, you only hear
the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin did please Wooden, at least for one day, when he said the
Bruins would not wear their controversial new black uniforms
against Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like them at all,'' Wooden said. ``But it doesn't make
any difference what I think.''
</P>
<P>
   If today's game is significant, it marks another progress point
for UCLA point guard Baron Davis. He will play 20-22 minutes today,
in his second game back after being sidelined with a torn anterior
cruciate ligament. Davis said his left knee feels about 90 percent
recovered after being injured last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in the rehab process,'' Davis said. ``I feel real
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the knee bothered him following Friday's practice at
the Pond, Davis said, ``Not at all. Not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin said Davis will probably be allowed to play in five-minute
intervals.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first meeting between UCLA and Oklahoma State since
the 1995 Final Four, when the Bruins won 74-61 in a semifinal game
en route to the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Note: About 2,000 tickets remain for today's games, mostly for
the terrace level, at a cost of between $30-$50 apiece. Some $75
seats on the floor level are also available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
