<HEADLINE>
7-ELEVEN: CHILI DOGS, NACHOS, SLURPEES ... FINE WINES?
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: Stresses stores sold wine before in 2nd
graph.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ White goes with chicken and red with beef. But
what's a gourmand to serve with nacho cheese and a microwave
burrito? The answer lies no further than the corner 7-Eleven.
</P>
<P>
   To grab a slice of the nation's multibillion-dollar retail wine
market, America's biggest convenience store chain recently started
expanding its selection, and will stock its shops with up to 30
different wines.
</P>
<P>
   The company is quick to note that these are not the bottles of
Thunderbird and Night Train Express favored by low-budget imbibers.
With price tags ranging from $6 to $15 a bottle, and labels from
the likes of Beringer and Ecco Domani, the 7-Eleven wines are aimed
squarely at the dinner crowd. Racks include educational information
on wine and menu suggestions for different bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for people on their way home from work or on their way
to a special dinner who want to stop by and grab a bottle of
wine,'' said 7-Eleven spokeswoman Dana Manley. ``They can park
right in front of the door and run in.''
</P>
<P>
   From a financial standpoint, analysts say, it's a natural
pairing for 7-Eleven and its parent company, Dallas-based Southland
Corp. U.S. wine sales last year topped $16 billion and wine is the
second-fastest growing beverage category behind soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes a lot of sense,'' said analyst David Maura at First
Union Capital Markets in Charlotte, N.C. 7-Eleven is already the
nation's largest beer retailer. If its roughly 3,200 stores
licensed to carry alcohol sell just a few bottles of wine a week,
it would mean tens of millions more dollars on the company's top
line.
</P>
<P>
   And though its wine sales are never expected to approach that of
beer, by virtue of the chain's size 7-Eleven could quickly become a
major force in the retail wine market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows that wine is becoming more mainstream,'' said
Gladys Horiuchi, a spokeswoman for the San Francisco-based Wine
Institute, a public policy advocacy group for California wineries.
``It's always good to have it in more outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   7-Eleven officials say the rollout of their campaign is under
way and should be complete by early 1999. And for the record,
7-Eleven's Manley said, microwave burritos go best with a chilled
chardonay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
