<HEADLINE>
MUHAMMED FLIES TO U.S. MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Sabir Muhammad, 22, set an American
short-course record of 52.42 seconds in the 100-meter butterfly
last night at the U.S. Open Swimming Championships.
</P>
<P>
   In the four days of the FINA World Cup and U.S. Open, Muhammad
has set two American records and one meet record, but he's not
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   He won't be for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've learned is that this is all really
insignificant,'' Muhammad said. ``My main goal right now is the
Olympic Trials and representing the United States in Sydney. If I'm
able to do that, I've accomplished my greatest goal.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Muhammad became only the fourth African-American to
make the U.S. National Team, but a disastrous Olympic Trials
prevented him from representing the United States at the Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad now trains with USA Swimming's resident training team
in Colorado. He finished second to Australian Geoff Huegill (23.73
seconds) in the 50-meter butterfly at the World Cup earlier in the
week, but still set an American record with his time of 23.75.
</P>
<P>
   His goal yesterday was another record in the 100 fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I dove into that final, the first thing that hit my mind
was, `Wow, I'm really tired,' '' said Muhammad who has been
competing for four days. ``I said, `Keep going, you're not as tired
as you think.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A total of six American records have fallen during two days of
U.S. Open action. Last night, a U.S. Open mark and two American
records fell.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Davis, 26, picked up his third American record in three
days when he won the 200-meter freestyle in 1:45.24, breaking the
record of 1:45.54 set 10 years ago by Troy Dalbey.
</P>
<P>
   It was Davis' 21st race in four days, and the exhausted Austin
resident was happy to be heading home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than I could hope for,'' Davis said. ``I've been
on the National team for eight years,and these are my first
American records. Tonight I thought ... I could command the
race,and I went out a little slower so I'd have more coming back.
It paid off. Those were the three-tenths I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Coughlin, 16, won the 100-meter backstroke in 58.59,
setting a U.S. Open record, but it was her dramatic .14-second
victory over Olympian Cristina Teuscher, 20, in the 400-individual
medley that grabbed attention.
</P>
<P>
   On the butterfly and backstroke, Coughlin, a Kansas City
resident, was a body-length ahead of Teuscher, but the Olympian
made an attack on the breast stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the breast and freestyle, I was just trying to hold her
off as much as possible and spin my arms and make it to that wall
before her,'' said Couglin who won in 4:36.24. She also won the
200-meter backstroke in U.S. Open record time the night before. ``I
was really excited because she's such a good swimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open concludes today at the Texas A&AMP;M University
Student Recreation Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
