<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REELING KINGS TO FACE BIG TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings have lost 10 of their past
11 games, have scored three goals in their past four games, have
scored one goal in their past nine first periods, and on and on the
litany of misery goes. And tonight at the Forum, the Kings (6-16-3)
will try to shake themselves awake enough to face the NHL's best
and deepest team since Wayne Gretzky's Edmonton Oilers a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do about it but start preparing for
it,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson said of tonight's meeting with the
two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings. ``We'll
be ready for them at home. That's all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the Kings suffered a 3-1 setback to the Ottawa
Senators in Kanata, Ontario. They outshot Ottawa 32-18, and if not
for an outstanding performance by Senators goalie Ron Tugnutt, the
Kings might have sealed a victory in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first game in 15 or 16 games where we gave
ourselves a good chance to win,'' defenseman Mattias Norstrom said.
``I don't think we did that earlier. Instead of going after teams,
we were waiting for things to happen and things went downhill.
(Against Ottawa) we showed a different attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When things are going bad and you're playing without
confidence, that's typical,'' said Norstrom, who teamed with Sean
O'Donnell on the blunder that resulted in Ottawa's first goal, by
Andreas Johansson. ``We played strong, didn't have a lot of
turnovers, and we had one there and boom, it's in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   But playing well in defeat will not get the Kings into the
postseason. In fact, it is reaching a point where it almost is
imperative that the Kings begin their turnaround if they are to
qualify for the playoffs for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the eighth and final playoff spot in the Western
Conference went to the San Jose Sharks, who finished the season
with 34 victories and 78 points. For the Kings to match those
modest totals, they would have to go 28-22-7 (a .553 winning
percentage) in their final 57 games. Including the final 25 games
last season, four playoff losses and the first 25 games this
season, the Kings are an abominable 17-33-4 (.352) in their last 54
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like playoff time,'' left wing Luc Robitaille said,
referring to the final four-plus months of the regular season. ``If
we want to make the playoffs, we've got to win this month. We've
got to fight every game like it's the last game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
