<SLUG> BC-CENTRALPARK-SLAYING-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGER CONVICTED OF MANSLAUGHTER IN PARK SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A teen-ager was found guilty of first-degree
manslaughter Friday in the grisly slaying of a 44-year-old Upper
East Side man who was stabbed, eviscerated and left floating in a
lake in Central Park in May 1997. The teen-ager, Christopher
Vasquez, was acquitted of a more serious charge, second-degree
murder, and faces a sentence of 3-and-one-third years to 10 years
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict meant that neither of the two teen-agers accused in
the killing _ Vasquez and Daphne Abdela, both 16 _ was found guilty
of intentionally murdering Michael McMorrow, even though he was
stabbed 34 times during the attack and suffered six stab wounds to
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, who showed little emotion when the verdict was read,
will be sentenced in January.
</P>
<P>
   The question of which teen-ager delivered the fatal blows
dominated Vasquez's trial. Arnold Kriss, Vasquez's lawyer, accused
Ms. Abdela of carrying out the murder and using Vasquez as a
scapegoat. But in deciding to try Vasquez, prosecutors made clear
that they accepted Ms. Abdela's statements that Vasquez inflicted
the fatal stab wounds and that she played only a minor role in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   In a plea bargain that was criticized by jurors, prosecutors
allowed Ms. Abdela to plead guilty last March to first-degree
manslaughter but did not require her to testify against Vasquez at
his trial.
</P>
<P>
   A juror, speaking Friday night on the condition of anonymity,
said the failure of Ms. Abdela to testify complicated their efforts
to decide whether Vasquez had committed the murder..
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest problems was that Daphne Abdela was not
available and there was nothing to guide us through it,'' the juror
said. ``We just felt that we couldn't be sure what happened and
were not 100 percent positive that he committed a murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Another juror, who spoke Friday night on the condition of
anonymity, said some of the jurors felt that Ms. Abdela was the
murderer. The juror said that an outright acquittal of Vasquez was
debated during ``extremely emotional, extremely painful''
deliberations over three days. Four jurors wept as the verdict was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The juror, who said the panel felt great sympathy for McMorrow's
family, called the decision to allow Ms. Abdela to enter a plea
without testifying at a trial wrong and offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone walked away without being convicted'' of murder, the
juror said. ``The jury had the opportunity to try Christopher
Vasquez and acquitted him. The jury did not have the opportunity to
try Daphne Abdela.''
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was announced, relatives of McMorrow said they
believed that Vasquez had escaped justice. Matthew McMorrow, the
victim's 19-year-old nephew, said: ``There is no doubt in our minds
that Christopher Vasquez killed Michael in cold blood. All the
evidence points to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vasquez's relatives, while expressing sympathy for the
McMorrow family, praised the verdict. Michael Tantillo, Vasquez's
uncle, said that Vasquez did not carry out the killings and thanked
the jury. ``They did the right thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Who is responsible for delivering the fatal blows may never be
known.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez and Ms. Abdela met only three weeks before the killing
while watching a fight in Central Park, friends said. The two
teen-agers, now forever linked by the killing, could not be more
different.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez spent most of his childhood at home in his family's
walk-up apartment on the Upper East Side after agoraphobia _ a fear
of public places _ was diagnosed when he was 9. Ms. Abdela, by
contrast, grew up in a wealthy family on Central Park West and was
brash and aggressive, according to friends of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Recriminations over who was responsible for the killing
continued after the verdict was announced, focusing on a series of
statements Vasquez reportedly made to psychiatrists and
psychologists after the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez's statements in those evaluations were sealed, and would
have been made public only if his lawyer, Kriss, chose to adopt a
psychiatric defense.
</P>
<P>
   But two law enforcement officials, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that in those interviews with the psychiatrists and
psychologists, Vasquez confessed to the killing, giving an account
that matched Ms. Abdela's. The officials said the fact that
Vasquez's account, as well as evidence from the scene, corroborated
Ms. Abdela's account led to the plea bargain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kriss said that the psychiatric reports were sealed material and
that he would not disclose their contents. He angrily criticized
law enforcement officials for commenting on Vasquez's statements
after the trial concluded. And he warned that Vasquez's state of
mind at the time should be taken in context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people say things at one point in time when they are
under a lot of different stresses,'' he said, adding that police
reports and the evidence at the scene did not match Vasquez's
statements.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence produced at the trial included a cut finger and
facial bruises that Vasquez suffered on the night of the murder.
Vasquez's blood was found at the scene and a knife was found in his
bedroom that had his DNA and McMorrow's DNA on the blade.
</P>
<P>
   The defense suggested that Vasquez may have injured himself in
ways other than an assault. Investigators failed to test the handle
of the knife, which created some doubts on the panel, a juror said.
``There were a lot pieces that did not point conclusively to him,''
the juror said of Vasquez.
</P>
<P>
   The cut on Vasquez's hand, the juror said, pointed to at least
some involvement by him in the attack and led them to conclude that
manslaughter was the proper verdict.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Kriss hammered away at the fact that an abrupt
attack did not fit the actions of Vasquez, who witnesses described
as shy and passive. Witnesses said Ms. Abdela tried to pick fights
with several adults on the night of the murder before the two
bumped into McMorrow. Kriss also repeatedly pointed out that Ms.
Abdela had McMorrow's blood on her Rollerblades and Vasquez did
not, as evidence that she carried out the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that according to Ms. Abdela, the
fatal confrontation erupted on the night of May 22, 1997, when she
kissed McMorrow in the gazebo on the lake in Central Park as
Vasquez looked on. Law enforcement officials said they believe that
Vasquez was romantically interested in Ms. Abdela and that the
evidence backs her account.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Abdela, Vasquez flew into a rage and began
attacking the older man with a knife. Ms. Abdela said she joined
the attack and twice kicked McMorrow's feet out from under him.
</P>
<P>
   Kriss said he wished he had had the opportunity to cross-examine
Ms. Abdela on the stand and prove that the account of the killing
she and law enforcement officials are putting forward is incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors appeared to shift their position on the issue of Ms.
Abdela's testimony. In March, an assistant district attorney, Sarah
Hines, agreed to the plea agreement that did not require Ms.
Abdela's testimony. But another assistant district attorney,
Matthew Bogdanos, who prosecuted the case against Vasquez, met with
Ms. Abdela in prison this summer to try to talk her into testifying
voluntarily at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Brafman, the prominent defense lawyer who negotiated
Ms. Abdela's plea agreement, said she would not testify in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Michael Corriero ruled that prosecutors could introduce as
evidence portions of Ms. Abdela's statement blaming Vasquez. But he
also allowed Kriss to introduce other material that called into
question Ms. Abdela's credibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
