<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-UCSB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BEATS UCSB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ A couple nights back, maybe last week, this
wouldn't have been the situation Elias Ayuso wanted to find himself
in _ his USC team struggling, the Trojans needing him to hit clutch
shots with a game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   But Ayuso shed his shooting slump and found his shot at just the
right moment Friday, and his barrage of second-half 3-pointers
helped the Trojans hold off scrappy UC Santa Barbara, 79-73 before
4,563 at the Thunderdome.
</P>
<P>
   The winless, but clearly inspired Gauchos had the undefeated
Trojans off-kilter, and had tied the game at 60 with 6:43 left. But
Ayuso hit a quick pair of 3s and scored 10 of his 21 points in the
last 5 minutes to help the Trojans (5-0) avert catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just gives you a lot of confidence, when down the stretch
you come in and knock shots down,'' Ayuso said. ``I've been
struggling. Go and look at my stats.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance at the stats showed Ayuso wasn't exaggerating.
Coming in, he had shot 37.5 percent from the field, and 5 of 20
from 3-point range. His struggles continued Friday, as he hit just
2 of 7 in the first half. He stepped up his game just in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to step it up from the beginning. Like coach said, they
can't wait for me to get warmed up at the end of the game,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Ayuso could shoulder the blame for a surprisingly close
contest. The Trojans were outrebounded 48-38 and shot just 41.3
percent as a team. Their failures didn't result in a loss only
because the Gauchos shot 38.6 percent from the field and 66.7
percent from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what kind of game we would be in,'' USC coach Henry
Bibby said. ``This team that we played tonight is better than their
record indicates. They gave us everything they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Barbara's B.J. Bunton had his way in the paint all night,
scoring 22 points to go along with 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trojans eventually overwhelmed the Gauchos (0-6) with a
superior perimeter game, as Ayuso and Brandon Granville combined to
hit 10 of 19 3-point attempts. Granville finished with a
career-high 22 points, and Jeff Trepagnier also hit a career best
with 19.
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier scored 15 in the first half. ``Unbelievable,'' Bibby
said. ``One of the best first halves I've seen in college
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans needed it. They played without starting forward
Jarvis Turner and reserve guard Quincy Wilder, both suspended one
game for missing classes this week.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Turner, averaging 9.2 points and one of only two
senior starters, was certainly evident in the first half, when the
Trojans squandered a double-digit lead and settled for a 43-40,
margin.
</P>
<P>
   So eager was Bibby to leave the floor after the first half, he
took his team into the locker room before the half even ended.
Brian Scalabrine had fouled Bunton at the buzzer, and rather than
watch, Bibby ushered the Trojans off the floor before Bunton made
both foul shots to cut the lead to 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   The game hadn't been that close since the opening five minutes.
USC held a creaky two-point lead early on before mounting an 11-2
run to make it 22-11. The Trojans would push the margin to 12
points, 36-24, before the Gauchos made it a game again.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Barbara outscored USC 16-7 to close out the half, and 9-3
in the last four minutes, with Bunton scoring six of his 10
first-half points in that span.
</P>
</TEXT>
