from New Jersey, said he will consider making a bid to become the
next president of the United States. By Jennifer Preston. (With
photos and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   WARM-WEATHER (New York) _ Throughout the Northeast, as far north
as Vermont and Maine, people were carrying their coats or leaving
them at home and treating themselves to cups of frozen yogurt and
ice cream. There were record-high temperatures in Newark, N.J.,
where it hit 75 degrees; Bridgeport, Conn., which reached 72
degrees, and Providence, R.I., at 71 degrees. By Barbara Stewart.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENSURE (Washington) _ President Clinton's fate in the House now
hinges on the decisions of a small group of Republican moderates
who could tilt an impeachment vote either way. With Republican
leaders likely to prevent any vote on censure, both Republicans and
Democrats who are trying to count votes say that a House vote on a
single count article of impeachment, on perjury, is too close to
call. By Alison Mitchell.
