<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCHDEBT-SIDEBAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT GROWING FOR CANCELING CENTRAL AMERICAN DEBT  
   
  
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT COLLIER  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
As Nicaragua and Honduras begin the long, herculean task of
repairing the damage from Hurricane Mitch, they will be hobbled by
a much bigger burden: their foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   This multibillion-dollar obligation was tough enough even before
the storm wrecked the two nations, which have long been among the
poorest in the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, politicians and civic leaders in the region _ and in
foreign lending countries _ are saying the debt is unpayable and
must be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras, which has total foreign obligations of $4.7 billion,
paid $539 million in debt service last year, about one-third of the
country's total export earnings. Nicaragua, which owes $5.9
billion, paid $349 million last year, nearly one-half of exports.
</P>
<P>
   After the hurricane, France, Cuba and Spain canceled bilateral
debts (those owed directly from one country to another) held by
Honduras and Nicaragua. The United States is allowing the two
countries to postpone bilateral debt payments for the next two
years, and the International Monetary Fund has said it will try to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers demand more, saying foreign donors must give
their aid as unconditional grants rather than loans that are
conditioned on adherence to budget-cutting, free-market economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to make debt payments and adhere to IMF-imposed
austerity measures helped degrade (Nicaragua's) emergency response
capacity,'' said Alejandro Bendana, director of the Center for
International Studies, a Managua think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of budget cuts, our civil defense agency is woefully
understaffed and has no units whatsoever in at least one-third of
the municipalities. Even the national police, which forms the
backbone of any emergency response, got less than one-third of what
it had requested during the most recent budget agreement. We need
immediate cancellation of this unjust, unpayable debt.''
</P>
<P>
   The donors will give their answer next week, at a conference in
Washington of Central American leaders and officials of the IMF,
the World Bank, the United States and other major lenders and
donors.
</P>
<P>
   But no one expects the Central Americans to be offered more than
a tiny fraction of the $4 billion they need to rebuild. Although
some new aid may be announced, international financiers have made
clear their belief that more belt-tightening, not debt
cancellation, is the cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``With great wisdom and courage, this government decided that
however great the dimensions of this disaster, it would not heap
disaster upon disaster by abandoning its course,'' IMF Managing
Director Michel Camdessus said after meeting Nicaraguan President
Arnoldo Aleman in Managua, whom he praised for sticking with an
IMF-designed austerity plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, support for writing off all the Honduran
and Nicaraguan debt is growing. Former President Jimmy Carter has
voiced support, as has Jubilee 2000, a coalition of major churches
and nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco, has taken a leading role in
Congress in supporting long-term U.S. reconstruction aid and debt
cancellation. As the ranking Democrat on the House Foreign
Appropriations Subcommittee, she will play a crucial role in
winning support for the new aid package, which is expected to be
introduced in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States would show great leadership by forgiving the
Honduran and Nicaraguan debt,'' said Pelosi.
</P>
<P>
   But two big hurdles exist: The Republicans are demanding that
any new funds for hurricane aid or debt cancellation be subtracted
from other countries' allotments, and total U.S. aid to Latin
America has already been cut by half since 1988, to $570 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the money going to come from?'' Pelosi asked. ``It's
going to be hard, but we'll do whatever we can to find it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
