<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHOULD THE METS HAVE WAITED?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets traded Todd Hundley to Los Angeles last week,
liberating their loyal catcher and themselves from a sticky
situation. Should they have waited until spring training so that
Hundley could have demonstrated that his elbow was sound and thus
may have brought a better price? No.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets in no way could have gone to camp with Hundley still on
the team. First, he could not have demonstrated anything by playing
an occasional exhibition game. Mike Piazza, after all, will have to
prepare for the season because he is the team's catcher. The Mets
could have scheduled `B' games for Hundley to play, but for teams
to see what they would have wanted to see, it would have required a
steady diet of `B' games, and teams just don't play that many.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Hundley's presence at Port St. Lucie, Fla., would have
created a major distraction that could have undermined the Mets'
chances for starting the season smoothly and successfully. Piazza
and Hundley in camp together? It might been reminiscent of the
Yankees' good old days. The same people who have criticized the
Mets for trading Hundley now would have criticized them then for
creating the distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the idea that the Mets could have secured a better
package for Hundley had they waited until next spring sounds good,
but it is flawed. Teams seeking a catcher might have made other
moves in the meantime, and they might also have spent their money
and had nothing left to pay Hundley's $5.2 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Mets owed Hundley, and by trading him now instead
of making him wait until a few days or weeks before next season
started, they did the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENS HAS STRINGS ATTACHED
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right trade for Roger Clemens will not be as easy as
it might seem. Because he would be traded in the middle of a
multiyear contract _ he has two years left on his Toronto contract
_ Clemens would have the right to demand a trade after next season,
unless his new team signed him to a new contract or a contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have assumed all along if this scenario played out, part of
it would be a contract discussion,'' said Gord Ash, the Blue Jays'
general manager. Some general managers suspect that by asking to be
traded, Clemens wants to boost himself onto the $12.5 million-plus
salary level populated by Pedro Martinez and Randy Johnson and soon
to be by Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding Ash's task, Clemens also has the right to veto a
trade. He has already said he does not want to play for a West
Coast team. ``Gord is supposed to do the best deal he can,''
another general manager said. ``Then when it's done, he calls the
Hendricks brothers'' _ the pitcher's agents _ ``and says, `I have a
deal to go to this city; are you OK with it?' They say yes or no.''
</P>
<P>
   AVOIDING COLLUSION II
</P>
<P>
   In trying to solve the growing problem of payroll disparity,
Commissioner Bud Selig has to avoid leading the owners into
Collusion II. Ten years ago Collusion I cost the owners $280
million (which still has not all been paid out to affected
players), and any future collusion would result in treble damages.
</P>
<P>
   But Selig did tell owners in Chicago last Thursday that all
clubs had to begin complying again with the 60-40 rule. That rule
requires clubs to have a ratio of no less than 60 percent assets to
40 percent liabilities, or debt.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, who proposed the 60-40 ratio about 15 years ago, has not
enforced it in recent years. He did not portray it to the owners as
a panacea, but that is where he is going to start.
</P>
<P>
   The players association filed a grievance against the rule in
1983, feeling it could inhibit salaries, but an arbitrator allowed
the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Another instrument that was aimed at discouraging lavish
spending was the luxury tax that emerged from the 1994-95 labor
dispute. High-spending teams, however, remain high-spending teams.
</P>
<P>
   The final assessments have not been sent to the clubs, but
preliminary figures show Baltimore owing $2.9 million, Boston $2.2
million, Atlanta $696,000, the Yankees $651,000 and Cleveland
$39,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
