<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Dec. 6:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ENGLISH (Berlin) _ English encroachment on Deutsch has
assumed epic proportions, giving rise to a form of speech widely
known as ``Denglisch.'' By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Hugo Chavez, who tried
to storm the presidential palace in a failed coup attempt six years
ago, is the front-runner in elections for the presidency on Sunday.
In some half-dozen voter surveys, he is leading by upward of 15
points over his nearest opponent, a silver-haired two-time governor
of Carabobo State, Enrique Salas Roemer. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ATTACKS (Tehran, Iran) _ An attack on visiting American
businessmen and the assassination of a prominent dissident here
have caused fresh unease among critics of the government, who say
they fear a campaign of violence by conservative forces. By Douglas
Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ARMENIA-PIPELINE (Yerevan, Armenia) _ Throughout the Caucasus
and Central Asia, the most excited conversations and debates these
days are about the coming Caspian energy boom. Everyone wants to
know who's up and who's down, which wells have come up dry and
which are gushers, and most of all where the vital oil and gas
pipelines will be laid. Armenia is the exception. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN (Almaty, Kazakhstan) _ With his open, unlined face,
Nursultan Nazarbayev talks like a man without a care, as might any
entrenched ruler of a resource-rich nation courted by powerful
world leaders. Yet one thing does plainly bother the dapper former
Communist Party leader who rules here. He is puzzled by recent
foreign accusations that he is a power-hungry leader who terrorizes
opponents. ``Fifteen hundred companies are working here and no one
wants a different president,'' he said recently. ``Do you
understand this? Write about it.'' By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-VOTE (Lagos, Nigeria) _ Five months after the death of
Nigeria's longtime military dictator raised the prospect of greater
political openness here, Nigerians cast ballots Saturday for local
government officers across the country. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-KOSOVO (Oslo, Norway) _ Diplomats from 60 countries meeting
here last week pushed to speed the deployment of 2,000 monitors to
Kosovo province in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-NUKES (Washington) _ With North Korea refusing to allow
inspection of a huge underground construction site that could be
used to hide a nuclear reactor, Clinton administration officials
acknowledge that a four-year-old agreement meant to freeze North
Korea's nuclear weapons program could collapse within weeks. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-CONSTITUTION (Madrid, Spain) _ Spain's celebration last
week of the 20th anniversary of its Constitution was supposed to be
a big congratulatory moment to mark the longest period of democracy
in the nation's history. But instead tensions are rising. By Al
Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS-SALES-DISPUTE (Vienna) _ The United States and 32 other
countries concluded four days of arms control meetings here with a
public commitment to exercise ``maximum restraint'' before selling
weapons to regions of conflict. For at least two Wassenaar
countries, Russia and Bulgaria, the pledge of restraint seems
somewhat hollow. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-U.N. _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan went to Libya on
Saturday to throw his weight behind American and British efforts to
have two Libyans turned over for trial in the bombing of a Pan Am
jetliner over Scotland 10 years ago this month. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WYNN-GAMBLING-LOBBY (Las Vegas) _ In a modest office building
across the street from the Deja Vu nude showgirls lounge, 15
workers, most of them elderly, spend their days in a long, narrow
room lined with cubicles, computers and telephones. The telephone
room does not belong to a political party, a candidate or a
consulting firm. It belongs to Stephen Wynn, the chief executive of
Mirage Resorts, the driving force behind the new $1.9 billion
Bellagio casino hotel here, the man most responsible for reshaping
the way the nation perceives casinos. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-WOMEN _ Slowly but surely, college campuses that for
decades were dominated by males are becoming the place where the
boys are not. By Tamar Lewin. (With a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-PULLMAN-FIRE (Chicago) _ Through its storied history, the
Pullman rail car factory has stood for a lot. But after a
spectacular fire destroyed its old clock tower and several adjacent
buildings on Tuesday, hopes of turning it into a transportation
museum were stood on end. By Andrew Bluth.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-NORTHWESTERN (Evanston, Ill.) _ It is reading week, the week
before exams, and the students at Northwestern University are
actually reading. Besides Proust and organic chemistry, they are
looking at headlines: ``4 are indicted in N.U. football scandal.''
By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   NH-PRIMARY-FRENZY (Concord) _ While the rest of nature has gone
quiescent for the winter, the mating rituals here in the
first-in-the-nation primary state are just now heating up. The next
presidential primary here is a good 14 months away, but this is the
season when local officials find themselves ever-more-ardently
wooed by smiling out-of-staters who figure that without the opinion
leaders of New Hampshire, they can forget about the White House. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-STATES (Washington) _ Abortion rights advocates have
slowly and quietly been winning victories in state courts to make
abortions more widely available. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MOOD (Washington) _ Things were odd enough here when the
roses started blooming in December. But then the White House
started complaining that people were not paying enough attention to
the possible impeachment of President Clinton. Indeed, they are
not. The House of Representatives may be gearing up to vote as
early as midmonth on the impeachment of a President _ for only the
second time in history _ but history does not exactly hang heavy on
the air. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUSTAKER-PROFILE (Washington) _ Milton Kaufman never planned
on a government career when he was growing up in Coney Island in
the 1920s. But after he graduated from the City University of New
York with in 1933, the government was the only place hiring. A
tall, gentle man, who wears a suit and tie on the job and off,
Kaufman retired this fall after 64 years of service at the Census
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Retro Patriotism. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ When truth matters less. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
