</P>
<P>
   _ ELISABETH ROSENTHAL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hey, a Guy's Gotta Eat
</P>
<P>
   For a typical suburban family, the monthly bills seem
extravagant: $11,000 for mortgage payments, $1,600 for groceries
and $1,100 for utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But John A. Gotti, the reputed Mafia leader, insists the
expenses are essential for supporting his wife and their four
children, and for the upkeep of two luxurious Long Island homes and
several rural properties. Gotti cited the household overhead in a
plea to a federal judge for a reduction in his bail supervision
costs. Awaiting trial on a raft of federal racketeering charges, he
was released on $10 million bail in October with the provision that
he pay $21,000 a month for private guards to monitor his activities
at his main home in Oyster Bay, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Because prosecutors have frozen more than $3 million of his
assets, including bank accounts and rents from commercial
properties, Gotti says his monthly income is now a mere $11,000. He
claims that unless his assets are freed or the surveillance costs
lowered, he will be unable to pay his bills or his lawyers' fees.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argue that the guards are necessary to prevent him
from meeting with other suspected mobsters and assert that Gotti,
34, known as Junior, is running the powerful Gambino organized
crime family for his imprisoned father, John J. Gotti, 58.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the younger Gotti is convicted, prosecutors say, most of
his assets probably will be confiscated as having been obtained
through criminal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gotti laments that he is scraping by with loans from
his sister, Victoria, an author of crime novels.
</P>
<P>
   _ SELWYN RAAB
</P>
<P>
   Painful Truth, Painful Lie
</P>
<P>
   If the congressional impeachment inquiry into President
Clinton's sex life accomplishes nothing else, it afforded Pam
Parsons a heartfelt opportunity to apologize for committing perjury
by lying about her sex life as a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that I ever denied about myself was what created a
spiraling journey through hell,'' Ms. Parsons told the House
Judiciary Committee. Her appearance was designed by the Republicans
to prod greater public outrage over the president's
sex-and-mendacity scandal by showing that ordinary Americans suffer
jail time for lying.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parsons lost her career as a women's basketball coach when,
at a critical moment of truth, she denied to a sportswriter that
she had been in a gay bar. She later sued for libel and perjured
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her suffering was noted with sympathy last week by Wendy Weaver,
a high-school teacher and volleyball coach in Utah who was faced
with a similar moment of truth and chose to simply admit to a
curious student that, yes, she was gay. Ms. Weaver eventually lost
her coaching job and was barred by the Nebo School District from
talking with students or staff members about her sexual
orientation, even outside of school.
</P>
<P>
   She sued with the help of the American Civil Liberties Union and
finally scored a point for the right to not lie about her sex life.
A federal judge last month ordered the school to backtrack in the
name of Ms. Weaver's ``unblemished'' reputation in the face of
``the private antipathy of some members of a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parsons, as she sadly testified, found comfort in the truth
the hard way. ``That day that I got slapped into recognizing that,
yes, there are things that you pay consequences for, my life had a
chance to turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FRANCIS X. CLINES
</P>
</TEXT>
