<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-CONSTITUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN FETES CONSTITUTION, AS SEPARATISTS CITE ITS FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spain's celebration last week of the 20th
anniversary of its Constitution was supposed to be a big
congratulatory moment to mark the longest period of democracy in
the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   But tensions are rising. As the country seeks ways to end 30
years of separatist violence, Basque nationalists are clamoring to
rewrite the constitution. It stipulates that Spain is united while
granting specific broad powers to regions, but nationalists seek
more power _ even independence. And the two big political parties
in Madrid are squabbling over how to comply with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a relatively new situation,'' said Gabriel Cisneros, 58,
one of the seven men who wrote the constitution, which was approved
by national referendum on Dec. 6, 1978. ``One can now speak about a
pressure on the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   What is clearly missing is the spirit of conciliation that
produced the constitution three years after the Franco
dictatorship's end in 1975. The democratic principles enshrined in
its 169 articles paved the way for Spain to join the European Union
in 1986, ending years of isolation from its democratic neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, whose conservative government
stands firmly for a united Spain, insisted at a meeting Tuesday
honoring the constitution that there was no need to revise it, and
he criticized the ``permanent'' demands from nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Basque region is leading the charge, but some nationalists
in Catalonia and Galicia have also hinted lately that the
constitution does not go far enough in its provisions for regional
parliaments, which control such functions as education and police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Basque people do not fit in the constitution,'' Xabier
Arzalluz, president of the moderate Basque Nationalist Party, said
in September.
</P>
<P>
   His party later backtracked, but it is making political deals
with the leftist Euskal Herritarrok coalition, which stands for
Basque Citizens in the Basque language and unabashedly favors
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is considered the political arm of the Basque
separatist group ETA, which since September has observed what it
calls the first ``indefinite'' cease-fire in its 30-year armed
struggle for Basque independence.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, after weeks of negotiations following the Basque
parliamentary elections in October, Arzalluz's party announced that
it would govern the Basque region in minority, with support only
from other Basque nationalist parties, ending a decade-long
alliance with the Madrid-based Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The move was expected to increase pressure on Madrid for more
Basque autonomy or independence. The recent Basque moves have been
a hot political issue for weeks in Spain, and last week former
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, a Socialist, said he doubted that
Aznar would defend the constitution to the hilt while trying to
negotiate a permanent peace in the Basque region.
</P>
<P>
   That remark added fuel to the fire raging between the Socialists
and Aznar's conservative Popular Party over mutually acceptable
judges to fill four slots on the 12-member Constitutional Court. It
is the highest tribunal in the land, created by the constitution,
and the new appointments _ finally made on Friday _ come nine
months past deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay is most harmful to the image of the court,'' said
Alvaro Rodriguez Bereijo, the Constitutional Court's presiding
judge. ``Citizens could see it as a center of political
in-fighting. The small interests of the parties shouldn't be above
matters of state.''
</P>
<P>
   While politicians bicker over the constitution, 22,000 ordinary
Spaniards braved long lines in cold weather last Tuesday and
Wednesday for a special visit to Parliament. There they received a
free copy of the Constitution and got a rare chance to sit in the
ornate neoclassical chamber where the 350 legislators convene.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the visitors gazed up at the painted ceilings, still
pocked by holes from bullets fired on Feb. 23, 1981, when
rebellious Civil Guard troops stormed the building in a coup
attempt. It failed after the intervention of King Juan Carlos, who
also visited Parliament last week to open an exhibit on the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as fellow visitors filed past, Ernesto Sampere,
78, stood up from a seat normally occupied by a government minister
and made an impromptu speech extolling Spain's democratic
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went off to fight Franco in the civil war,'' he nearly
shouted, adding that he was jailed during the dictatorship. ``I'm
happy this place exists to serve Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd broke into hearty applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
