<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-PRIMARY-FRENZY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE PRIMARY RITUALS ALREADY UNDER WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Pure political Scarlett O'Hara, Barbara Russell
could not immediately say how many presidential hopefuls have
recently asked her on the equivalent of a date, seeking the support
she might deign to cast their way as assistant chairwoman of New
Hampshire's Republican State Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, two, three, four, five,'' she counted slowly, running in
her mind through suitors she was too discreet to name, but
described as ``top-tier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They like to take you out to dinner, meet with you one on one
to talk about message and money,'' Ms. Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of nature has gone quiescent for the winter, the
mating rituals here in the first-in-the-nation primary state are
just now heating up. The next presidential primary here is a good
14 months away, but this is the season when local officials find
themselves ever more ardently wooed by smiling out-of-staters who
figure that without the opinion leaders of New Hampshire, they can
forget about the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like before a baseball game _ they're choosing up
sides,'' said Jean Wallin, a prominent Democrat who was co-chairman
of Jimmy Carter's successful campaign here.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians considering a run ``have to meet with the usual
suspects,'' Ms. Wallin said, ``or at least contact them so no one's
nose is out of joint.''
</P>
<P>
   A friendly passel of such usual suspects was on hand Thursday in
the Legislative Office Building to help with a recount left over
from last month's elections, and some seemed lighted by happy
anticipation that very soon, things were going to start getting
politically interesting again. Perhaps it will be even more
interesting than usual, given the growing tendency among other
states to set their primaries earlier and earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, California and several other Western states are
expected to move their primaries up to early or mid-March, soon
after New Hampshire's usual date in mid-February. Some political
analysts say such ``front-loading'' will divert attention from New
Hampshire. But others say it makes New Hampshire all the more
critical for candidates who lack the money and organization to take
on a giant state like California.
</P>
<P>
   This election cycle, said Hugh Gregg, a former New Hampshire
governor and one of its foremost authorities on the primary, the
new round of courting effectively began the day after the 1996
vote, when former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander put out bumper
stickers advertising his bid for the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has started earlier than any one we ever had,'' Gregg said
in an interview in his Nashua office, noting that Alexander had
already held two gigantic lobster bakes for a thousand or two.
``Usually they start right after Christmas the year before.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg keeps a list of all the people he considers likely to be
candidates and those who have already visited the state. As of
Thursday, among 26 likely Republican candidates, 18 had visited,
with Texas Gov. George W. Bush the most notable Republican no-show.
Among eight Democrats on his list, seven had visited. Vice
President Al Gore has been up a half-dozen times, Gregg said, and
is expected to be back again later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month's election, however, many of the visits carried
something of an altruistic character: the national candidates were
largely lending their room-filling appeal to local colleagues in
need of help. At least that was the official line.
</P>
<P>
   George Bruno, a former chairman of the New Hampshire Democratic
Party and a Gore backer, said he believed such active help from
leaders like Gore helped tip the state Senate from Republican to
Democrat this year for the first time since 1912. It is a nice
two-sided system, he said, in which local candidates get help
``from national candidates in whose interest it was to make sure
there was a Democratic network in the state from which they could
later call in their favors.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are certain people the candidates can depend on: those
they hire. That process, too, is already beginning. Republican
officials say at least five potential candidates, including Steve
Forbes and Dan Quayle, have paid staff members in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, the courting of New Hampshire pols begins
small-scale, from the congratulations and condolence calls Gore
made to state lawmakers who won and lost in last month's elections
to Christmas cards from Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   For those who back a winner, the rewards can be large-scale. The
path from New Hampshire to Washington and beyond is well-trodden by
the likes of former Gov. John Sununu, who became White House chief
of staff for President George Bush after helping engineer his 1988
primary comeback. Bruno, who was co-chairman of Clinton's 1992
campaign here, was later appointed ambassador to Belize.
</P>
<P>
   While all the back-scratching might seem cause for cynicism, the
opportunity for up-close-and-personal political pitches to even
obscure officials and party stalwarts is part of what enthusiasts
say makes the New Hampshire primary valuable.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks and months, said New Hampshire Secretary of
State William Gardner, if you live in New Hampshire and think you
like a candidate, ``If you want to have him to a dining-room or
living-room event and invite 20 neighbors, you pretty much have
that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time the New Hampshire primary is known for,'' he
added. ``It's not the week before,'' when the national media swarm
in.
</P>
<P>
   But this can also be an agonizing time for the hard-core
political workers like Ms. Russell, who was executive director for
Bob Dole's general election campaign here and this time has yet to
decide which candidate deserves her heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had nightmares over a pick for a year and a half,'' Ms.
Russell said, ``because when I jump in, I'm going to give it every
hour of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
