r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSIC-2Take     12-05 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSIC-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR FINDSWORDS TO THANK AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Today'' in story refers to Sunday, Dec. 6.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When he stood up there at rehearsal and began singing the
words to `God Bless America' as he conducted, you could just see he
felt every note. They were coming from the heart, just like
(Irving) Berlin wrote them.'' _ Alvin Mills, conductor of the
Brentwood-Westwood Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ His suit is pressed, his hair is freshly trimmed
and his nails have been immaculately manicured.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Festinger is ready. Now, all he can do is wait. Wait and
remember.
</P>
<P>
   So he sits in the living room of his suburban L.A.-area home
Friday afternoon, and he closes his eyes to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 48 hours from these moments, this 73-year-old
Hungarian immigrant who survived a Nazi concentration camp in World
War II will stand before a symphony orchestra in concert to say
``thank you'' to his country for the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   With absolutely no formal musical training but the feeling in
his heart, he will pick up a baton, look down into the faces of
more than 20 highly trained and skilled musicians, and conduct them
in Irving Berlin's ``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   He will sing the words as he conducts because he must. He cannot
help himself, he says. They mean too much to him.
</P>
<P>
   And he will cry because he must do that, too.
</P>
<P>
   When you have been where he has been, and now find yourself
fulfilling a dream that kept death at bay when you were a scared
17-year-old in a concentration camp, you have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   You must sing. You must cry. And you must formally thank the
country that gave you a new life.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Irving Berlin himself did in composing and writing ``God
Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin could never have known it, but a young, frightened
Hungarian boy was singing his song every night before going to
sleep in a German concentration camp from 1942 to 1945, dreaming
one day of coming to America himself.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the boy had to make his other, more pressing dream
come true.
</P>
<P>
   Making it to 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me then, it seemed so very far away, 20,'' Festinger said
as he waited for the hours to pass until today. ``It was all I and
a lot of other boys taken to the labor camps dreamed of and prayed
for. Making it to our 20th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long and into the night, we repaired railroad tracks
bombed by the Allies, and carried steel slabs to the German workers
building train cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night, before bed, we had our dreams. Mine was coming to
America, like Irving Berlin. As a child in Hungary, I used to
listen to American records and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the songs I loved the most was `God Bless America.' It
was like every word came from my heart, too. I could picture Berlin
coming into a new country that had invited him, embraced him, and
sitting down later to write this song from his heart to say thank
you.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 1407EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
