<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4635 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSIC-2ndTa     12-05 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSIC-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES:   say thank you. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I wanted so much to be invited in and embraced by America,''
Festinger said. ``But first, I had to make it to 20.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what he was when his camp was liberated, and he
applied to come to this country as a refugee. He had to wait three
years to be invited in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived in New York, there were already so many
refugees in the city that the government was asking anyone with a
profession to speak up so they could be placed outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come from a family of dentists and knew how to work as a
dental technician by the time I was 14,'' he said. ``I was placed
in a job in Waterbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two nights a week, I went to the University of Connecticut to
learn English. Next door, there was an electronics class going on.
I fell in love with it, so two nights a week I took English, and
two nights electronics.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1956, he had his own electronics repair shop in Waterbury
before moving to California in the 1970s to be near friends. He
opened Reseda Television Sales and Service, finally retiring in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   America had been good to him, Festinger knew. But what had he
done for America to say thank you?
</P>
<P>
   Berlin had written his patriotic song, but what could he _ Fred
Festinger, retired television repairman _ do?
</P>
<P>
   There had to be something, he thought this year, on the 50th
anniversary of being invited in and embraced by America.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Mills put down the telephone and pondered the request from
Los Angeles Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski's office. A man by the
name of Festinger, a Holocaust survivor, had written her office
requesting an opportunity to conduct ``God Bless America'' in front
of a full orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   It was a touching, poignant letter. Would Mills, the founder,
music director and conductor of the Brentwood-Westwood Symphony
Orchestra, consider the man's request for an upcoming performance?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our program was already set, and I thought, maybe I could let
him conduct at one of our rehearsals,'' Mills said Friday. ``But, I
thought that wouldn't be right, so I put him on the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills quickly saw something in Festinger standing up there on
the conductor's podium at rehearsals that transcended training,
timing and musical experience.
</P>
<P>
   Something that went right to the heart of what Irving Berlin was
trying to tell this country when he wrote ``God Bless America'' in
1918.
</P>
<P>
   It was that special something that too many people born in this
country fail to fully understand or feel because they haven't been
where Berlin or Festinger came from _ countries where the living
was hard, brutal and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the people who have had hardships and get a little
decency in this country who appreciate it the most,'' Mills said.
``Berlin loved this country, just like Fred does. The words and
music come from their hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   The program says he comes on today after Chopin's Piano Concerto
No. 2 in F Minor, Opus 21, and Haydn's Symphony No. 104 (London) in
D Major.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's ``God Bless America,'' it says. And in parenthesis _
``Fred Festinger, Holocaust survivor, conductor.''
</P>
<P>
   His suit is pressed, his hair is trimmed, his nails are
immaculately manicured.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Festinger is ready.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
