<DOCNO> NYT19981205.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEXIS-NEXIS-LEADER06-     12-05 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEXIS-NEXIS-LEADER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Hans Gieskes, the Dutch-born president and chief
executive of Lexis-Nexis, is like the captain who tells his crew
not to worry because waves are breaking over the bow.
</P>
<P>
   Gieskes (pronounced GEES-kes) became head of the Miami
Twp.-based broker of legal and business information and news last
December. Since then, the electronic publishing industry has grown
even more competitive and less predictable. Lexis-Nexis, its
competitors and their parent companies are in a shake-out period
that will likely lead to more consolidation and turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   But Lexis-Nexis is fortunate in that it has a well-heeled parent
willing to invest millions in it. Reed Elsevier plc, an Anglo-Dutch
publishing giant, bought Lexis-Nexis from Mead Corp. in late 1994
for $1.5 billion. Since then, Reed Elsevier has invested heavily in
the company to improve its products and services. Perhaps the most
significant investment to date is Reed Elsevier's purchase of
Matthew Bender &AMP; Co., the country's leading publisher of analytical
legal information, and Shepard's Co., the leading U.S. legal
citation publisher. The acquisitions dramatically boosted the Lexis
side of the business, which still accounts for about 60 percent of
the company's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But such large investments, coupled with increased competition,
have impacted Reed Elsevier's earnings. Last week, Reed Elsevier
warned investors that its full-year pretax profit will fall 6
percent because of lower demand for its publishing products and the
weakening worldwide economy. Reed Elsevier also said stronger
competition for online legal and business information in the United
States is cutting revenue growth at Lexis-Nexis.
</P>
<P>
   The news further dampened Reed Elsevier's stock prices. Shares
in Reed International Plc have fallen 29 percent this year, while
Elsevier NV shares have fallen 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety has spread to Lexis-Nexis headquarters as well.
Rumors of pending job cuts and restructurings circulate daily among
the company's 2,400 local employees.
</P>
<P>
   But in a wide-ranging interview last week, Gieskes dismissed
those rumors and said Lexis-Nexis remains profitable, competitive
and strong. He also said he is enjoying steering Lexis-Nexis at a
critical point in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the highlights of the interview:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you expect and what did you actually find when you
became president and chief executive of Lexis-Nexis?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are always surprises, good and bad. Otherwise, life
would be very boring. But on balance, I'm very happy with what I
found. We have gone through terrific change. The Matthew Bender
acquisition, the consolidation within the industry and changes in
technology here have been tremendous. But we have positioned
ourselves well for the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lexis-Nexis is more than a company based in Dayton, Ohio.
We now talk about the Lexis-Nexis Group, a third of which only is
Dayton-based. That means we have more of a group culture arising
here and it's no longer the Dayton culture or the Dayton business.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a major culture change occurring here?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The company is changing culture because it's no longer
the only company we have. The influence of our non-Dayton-based
businesses is strong and our outlook is changing. I think the
company has opened up and realized there's a big market out there
(that we must pursue). And we will continue to change.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of changes are you talking about?
</P>
<P>
   A: The way we have embraced the browser-based customer
interface, and the way we will move forward in a very focused way,
compared to the way in the past, where we moved in many different
ways, is a big change in our culture. The decentralization that we
started four to five years ago has been very successful in
improving productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you responding faster to the market these days? The
complaint against Lexis-Nexis has been that it moves too slow to
market forces.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, we are moving faster. The way our industry is moving,
you want to be much faster to market than ever before, but you want
retain all the good things of the original model. And if you have a
huge customer base, you have a built-in hesitation to launch things
too quickly. But we certainly move much faster, and that's because
of the way we have empowered (people) throughout the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What other accomplishments or goals have you reached so far
during your tenure?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Matthew Bender acquisition was very important,
particularly from a legal market position. But the entire company
is growing and very successful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you meeting your numbers and projections?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh yes. Within Reed Elsevier, we are a highly appreciated
company. The way we are leveraging the Lexis-Nexis know-how and
infrastructure for the rest of (Reed Elsevier) is very important.
This is a core business.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are revenues still roughly split 60 percent from Lexis and 40
percent from Nexis?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. But what's interesting is that lawyers are increasingly
using non-legal information, which is why marriage of Lexis and
Nexis is so strong. Lawyers need information from a very broad
spectrum these days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the Nexis (news) side of the business one day surpass
the Lexis (legal) side of the business?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. I don't think so. But Nexis is a very important part of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has the volatility in the on-line industry affected
morale here?
</P>
<P>
   A: Anybody working in a large corporation in this day and age is
affected by global competition and should have some anxiety as to
what could be around the next corner. I would be worried if people
were more complacent. We all should be focused on what's happening
in the world market. If that causes some anxiety, then I think
that's probably not a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Any anxiety is par for the course for any large organization. We
need people who are able to cope with change, create change and
manage change. That's a very important function. It's very
important that we reward those who instigate and manage change.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think the recent rumors about Microsoft (buying
Lexis-Nexis), the failed ($8.8 billion) merger with Wolters-Kluwer
(by Reed Elsevier) and shaky stock prices are contributing to this
anxiety among employees.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know. But people here are much more focused on the
stock market than they are in Europe. And if you work for a U.S.
subsidiary of a global organization, and there are changes at the
high executive level, it's bound to affect anybody. People will
worry about things they shouldn't worry about, and when you tell
them not to worry, they will worry even more. These things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give a progress report on the search for a new chief
executive of Reed Elsevier?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I can't because all I know about that is what appears in
the press. But I can certainly understand why some people are
concerned about that. People in this country have an obsession with
leaders. I don't think it's necessarily a good thing, but I
understand it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What makes a good leader?
</P>
<P>
   A: Results. Results and respect, and respect is something you
earn. When you are a leader or a manager, you have to add value
every day. You should not take anything for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can we expect from Lexis-Nexis in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot. We will continue to battle for leadership of the
various markets around the world as the competition heats up. We
also will make investments in product development and continue to
re-engineer our processes in such a way that, in a changing market
place, we can be as effective a leader as we have been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
