<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GI Dough: Vet has currency from here to eternity
 &HT;    By Matt Reed
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Bob Cowan isn't the type who gets teary-eyed
about Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was there 57 years ago today, a young frightened Army
sergeant from New York in charge of anti-aircraft guns on Waikiki
beach. But ask Cowan about his stint in the Pacific and he's more
likely to show off his favorite war memorabilia, gathered in
nightclubs while on leave with other soldiers and sailors.
</P>
<P>
   They played a game of sorts back then, in clubs like the Royal
Hawaiian, the Moana Hotel and later on the Marshall and Gilbert
Islands. Fighting men would sign and trade currency from other
nations, collecting unusual bills as they traveled the globe.
</P>
<P>
   They even had a snappy, 1940s-style name, ``the Short-Snorters
Club,'' though Cowan never did figure out what that meant.
</P>
<P>
   It worked like this: If you met another GI, Marine or sailor in
a bar, you'd ask, ``Hey buddy, are you a member of the
Short-Snorters Club?'' Then they would have to produce a type of
money you didn't already have _ say, an Italian Lire or
military-issued Hawaiian dollar _ sign it and hand it over. The
trading went on from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talked to each other more back then,'' Cowan said. ``It
wasn't the value of the money, it was the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   By war's end, Cowan had a yards-long strip of currency taped
end-to-end _ signed by some of the day's most notable and unlikely
soldiers: actor Clark Gable and band leaders Artie Shaw and Claude
Thornhill.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, the chances of meeting celebrities were
extra slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that easy to get out on leave, believe me,'' Cowan
said. ``Most of the time, I kept this rolled up in my foot
locker.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cowan's collection of 37 yellowing bills includes money
printed in Canada, Nazi Germany, France, Nicaragua. There's even
one from wartime Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   All are signed in black or blue ink in tidy handwriting by
people Cowan never saw again. He can only guess what became of some
of those men, as thousands fought and died in the bloodiest battles
of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Now a retired insurance executive living in Jupiter, Cowan isn't
sure he can part with his collection of money and autographs.
Christie's auction house in New York recently showed some interest
in selling it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People collect things like that,'' Cowan said, unrolling and
re-rolling the money. ``I really never thought about that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
