<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DDN-PSYCHO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Method to Van Sant's madness works in new `Psycho'
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``We all go a little mad sometimes,'' Norman
Bates says to Marion Crane over a plate of sandwiches and milk.
``Haven't you ever gone a little mad?''
</P>
<P>
   Gus Van Sant's sanity has been similarly called into question in
recent months over his controversial, shot-by-shot ``re-creation''
of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho.'' The Academy Award-nominated
director of ``Good Will Hunting'' has restaged the 1960 suspense
classic with a new cast and in color, using Joseph Stefano's
original screenplay, Hitchcock's storyboards and Bernard Herrmann's
indelible score.
</P>
<P>
   The audacious concept is as perilous as playing with knives. Yet
Van Sant emerges from the Bates Motel remarkably unscathed _ unlike
the less-fortunate Miss Crane.
</P>
<P>
   With a few notable exceptions _ such as the $40,000 Marion
steals from her employer being adjusted for inflation to $400,000 _
Van Sant's update of Hitchcock's most notorious thriller remains
true to the original. The Saul Bass-designed title sequence now has
green and black horizontal stripes, rather than black-and-white,
but it still leads to an opening helicopter shot of Phoenix, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the rare instances where Van Sant has improved on the
original, his camera zooms continuously from the city skyline
through a hotel window to a couple in bed. Because of the
technological limitations of the time, Hitchcock had to cut the
planned sequence into two shots.
</P>
<P>
   However, the characters, dialogue, blocking and camera angles
all remain the same. So does ``Psycho'' 's rhythm, smartly
maintaining the tension and suspense of the original, even for
those who know where the story is going.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the ``Scream'' generation has little interest in
watching black-and-white movies, and a digitally restored
re-release of Hitchcock's version would probably only appeal to
older fans and films buffs. But by casting such hot young stars as
Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche, and shooting the film in color with a
Dolby digital soundtrack, Van Sant is introducing the film to a new
audience.
</P>
<P>
   And by taking the unprecedented literal approach, he doesn't
hack it up by needlessly changing things around, as Andrew Davis
did earlier this year with ``A Perfect Murder,'' a glossy
bastardization of Hitchcock's ``Dial M for Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense one gets from watching Van Sant's ``Psycho'' is that
of a solid repertory company restaging a familiar production, as
happens in the theater with everything from Shakespeare to
``Brigadoon.'' Musicians also record and perform note-for-note
reproductions of one another's works. It's just novel for the
relatively new medium of film.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the cast, which also includes Julianne Moore, Viggo
Mortensen and William H. Macy, has previously worked together in
such films as ``Return to Paradise,'' ``The Lost World'' and
``Boogie Nights,'' lending to the repertory feel.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is much more physically imposing as Bates than the
bird-like Anthony Perkins, obscuring some of Hitchcock's symbolism,
while Heche lacks the sensuality of Janet Leigh's Crane. But both
bring their own frame of reference to the roles. Vaughn is
tremendously creepy, particularly after the film's focus shifts
from Crane to Bates and his invalid mother.
</P>
<P>
   The original's flaws _ a slow opening and 5-minute monologue
finale _ also survive intact. Van Sant's alterations largely
involve making Norman's attraction to Marion more overtly sexual,
and making the legendary shower scene more bloody. Subtlety and
restraint were the keys to Hitchcock's landmark film, but viewers
today have a much higher threshold for sex and violence. Clearly,
there was a method to Van Sant's madness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
