<HEADER>
A4646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACT19-DRUG-HUFF06-C     12-05 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACT19-DRUG-HUFF06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tract 19 whites `huff' away the pain of poverty
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Over the years, Denise Thomason has cut, torn,
ripped up hundreds of towels, sheets, blouses, wash cloths, dish
cloths, handkerchiefs, socks, panties.
</P>
<P>
   In a haze of flying fibers and threads, she has fashioned a rag
just so, doused it with oily paint thinner, pressed the poultice to
her chapped lips, inhaled, then closed her eyes with relief,
drifting into light-headed bliss brought on by oxygen deprivation
to her brain.
</P>
<P>
   It is the cheapest, most continuous high that she knows.
</P>
<P>
   She started at age 10. She is 35 now. Other addictions have come
and gone _ alcohol, crack, and a cocaine and Dilaudid brew via her
veins. But ``the tol,'' slang for toluene, a potent chemical in
paint thinner, remains with her always. After alcohol, inhalant
abuse or ``huffing'' solvents, gasoline, correction fluid, aerosol
sprays, refrigerants or other chemicals is the addiction of choice
in Tract 19, say police, preachers and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   About 21.6 percent of households reported that dealing with
alcohol and/or drug abuse was the major family problem, according
to the private study commissioned by St. Paul United Methodist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   The addiction has managed to survive competition from pricier
urban drugs, said Dayton Police Officer Mitchell Olmsted, who
conducts community-based patrols in the First District.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love silver and gold spray paint; it's easily
available,'' said Olmsted. ``I've been in places where you can just
tell there's flammable odor.'' Abusing harmful intoxicants is a
fourth degree misdemeanor punishable by fine. So far this year,
there have been only six arrests in Dayton. Police say they are
focused on more serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Huffing can cause violent behavior, hallucinations, convulsions,
drowsiness, unconsciousness, even cardiac arrest and suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   When suburban teen-agers die suddenly from huffing, it makes
headlines. But the slow deaths of lifetime huffers in Tract 19 go
unreported.
</P>
<P>
   Along East Fourth Street and Huffman Avenue, Denise Thomason is
infamous for her addiction and embarrassing arrests for assault and
public-drunkenness. She points to others on ``the tol,'' pronounced
``toil,'' walking through the alley like ghosts, present but not
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tol'' is why Thomason's hand shook as she held a glass of
milk to her lips on a recent afternoon. It's why she has not worked
in years. It's why she receives food stamps. It's why she is
scraping to get $365 to pay last month's rent and $365 more for
this month's. It's why she is among the 48 percent in Tract 19 who
are not in the labor force. It's why she is applying for
Supplemental Security Income benefits for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not stable,'' she says, repeating language a social
worker used to describe her situation. ``I get where I can't
remember things. It deteriorates my system so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an everyday habit. It seems weird not being high
because I've been on it for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, her stomach knots into cramps, she perspires like mist is
falling all the time, her head pounds.
</P>
<P>
   She has tried to quit and currently is attending a rehab
program.
</P>
<P>
   In the meal hall kitchen at St. Paul United Methodist Church,
Thomason talks about her life with slurred speech. Her head hangs
down and stringy blonde hair falls over a limp smile and eyes that
are blank but bright. Like a rag doll, her crossed leg dangles, her
white tennis shoe flops against the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't raise none of them,'' she says of the six daughters,
ages 20 to 11, whom Child Protective Services took away, gave back,
then took away permanently. They have four different fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Two daughters live on their own across town. One lives in
Illinois with a grandparent. ``My 15-year-old, they just sent her
to Texas to relatives. I'll never be able to get her back.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomason doesn't want the 11- and 12-year-olds back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like them to be around me too much because it's got
that really bad odor. It's all I can do to take care of me. I don't
want to go see them and get their hopes up and then not show up for
months and months. So I just keep my distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I been through it for 19 years. I try not to think about it
because if I do, that sets me off, depresses me. I get a lot of
guilt and shame from everything I put them through.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know what kind of mother she might have been. But
she says she wouldn't cuss and carry on or call her children ``good
for nothing,'' the way she says her own mother raised her, two
brothers and a sister. About year ago Thomason learned that she had
contracted hepatitis C, an inflammation of the liver common among
drug abusers. ``If it kills me. . .'' she says, her voice fading.
``If it kills me. . .''
</P>
<P>
   She rests her head on the table, dozing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired. I don't get involved with people outside of here
and what they think.''
</P>
<P>
   If somebody called her ``poor white trash,'' she probably
wouldn't put up much of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastor David Beach of St. Paul's would fight for her. He is
encouraged to see her at the church nearly every day, putting in
required hours to receive $125 month in food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I need to talk, I can go right in there to Pastor
Dave,'' Thomason says.
</P>
<P>
   And Pastor Dave will tell her once again that she is afraid of
``God's great overwhelming love.'' And he will tell her again that
when she banishes that fear, she will breath in God's love and be
set free from ``the tol.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a mind of my own. Nobody forces me to do this,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   That limp, snaggle-toothed smile begins to seep over her face,
and she holds her head up, just for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
