<HEADER>
A4647 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACT19-POVERTY06-COX     12-05 1716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACT19-POVERTY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cloudy future looms for poverty-stricken whites in Ohio's Tract
19
 &HT;    WITH TRACT19-DRUG-HUFF, TRACT19-TEENS
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On Tuesdays at St. Paul United Methodist Church,
the listless figures move steadily through the free lunch line
toward a plate of salty beef, noodles and a sweet paper cup of
Kool-Aid.
</P>
<P>
   Wilma Jean Griffieth gently guides her 33-year-old mentally
disabled daughter by the elbow. It's the end of the month. The
$1,200 from their two government checks has run out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's getting near the end of the month, if I couldn't
come here I don't know where I'd go,'' says Griffieth, her lungs
wheezing on this windy, rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   On another Tuesday, Dona Baker, who danced some nights to buy
Cheerios, milk and McDonald's for her two children while her
husband was out of work, pushes the kids forward. She cautions them
not to be slow pokes. ``These people are hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Watts, a burly man who says he is an out-of-work
pipefitter, is among the procession from the church pantry carrying
bags of groceries and sacks of bread. They file past St. Paul
Pastor David Beach. He nods at each grim face as if bestowing a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even like coming here,'' says Watts, 36, and the
father of three grade-schoolers. ``I don't like charity. I was
raised that a man got out and supported his family. Right now I'm
just down on my luck.''
</P>
<P>
   At folding tables, about 150 people dine as Jesus Christ looks
down from a portrait in the center of the meal hall, his arms
reaching out. Beneath the portrait are loaves and loaves of
days-old bread _ sweet rolls, onion rolls, doughnuts, muffins.
</P>
<P>
   The diners are some of the poorest white people in Montgomery
County. They are the citizens of Census Tract 19 in southeastern
Dayton: population 6,000, about 97 percent white; per capita
income, $6,979, nearly a third of the per capita income for the
county ($17,748) and less than half the state ($16,644), according
to the most recent U.S. Census.
</P>
<P>
   They are, sociologists say, a peculiar minority, a large
concentration of poor non-Hispanic whites.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, non-Hispanic whites made up 76 percent of the U.S.
population, but were only 23 percent of the population in poor
neighborhoods, according to a Census-based study by the Center for
Budget and Policy Priorities in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   National media and advocates for the poor often draw attention
to minorities who are poor. And this fall, the Rev. Jesse Jackson
drew attention to the condition of poor whites in rural Appalachia.
He marched, preached and called on Wall Street. But the plight of
poor inner-city whites, many of whom migrated from Appalachia to
urban areas like Tract 19, remains silent and out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   WhiIe many Americans ride a wave of prosperity, the residents of
Tract 19 are stranded by discrimination, a lack of grass-roots
leadership, alcohol and drug abuse, dependence on public assistance
and an economic shift that has left low-skilled white workers
scraping to earn a living wage.
</P>
<P>
   The shift from an industrial- to a service-based economy has
left many young, unskilled white males working low-wage fast-food
and convenience store jobs. Between 1973 and 1991, the number of
white workers earning a wage too low to lift a family out of
poverty rose from 20 percent to 28.1 percent. For blacks, the
figure is closer to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a number of trends in the economy that have
hurt low-wage workers, the decline in unions, decline in real value
of minimum wage,'' said Jared Bernstein of the Economic Policy
Institute in Washington, D.C. ``Those trends have
disproportionately affected minority workers. However, those trends
also hurt low-wage whites. And poverty among blacks is down, while
it is increasing for whites.''
</P>
<P>
   Education levels remain low among many poor whites. In Tract 19,
about 54 percent of residents are high-school dropouts, according
to one study.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an uncertain future, in which marriage and family
do not appear to be viable options.
</P>
<P>
   Substance abuse, teen-age pregnancy and other social ills are
rampant in Tract 19, police and health department officials say.
``Huffing,'' or inhaling aerosol propellants or other chemicals
such as paint thinner, is a preferred addiction.
</P>
<P>
   About 48.5 percent of Tract 19's residents are not in the labor
force, according to a 1997 survey. That figure suggests that a
large percent are disabled in some way and receive welfare, Social
Security, SupplementaI Security Income or some other form of public
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when people are on welfare there is a complacency _
my father did it, my mother did it. `It's good enough for them,
it's good enough for me,' '' said Dean Vickers of the Southeast
Priority Board, which serves Tract 19.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike poor blacks who link poverty to racial discrimination,
whites tend not to politicize and protest their poverty. While West
Dayton has produced grass-roots leaders such as Annie Bonapart, few
have emerged on the east side.
</P>
<P>
   From his humble pulpit at St. Paul, in the heart of Tract 19,
the Rev. David Beach attempts to arouse activism among those who
live in unsparing poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In poor white communities, people are more likely to just
accept this as their lot,'' Beach said. ``Poor whites don't see
themselves as a distinct group with any political clout. So they
don't mobilize or go marching down to city hall. And they ought
to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear a progressive, class-based voice coming from
the poor white community,'' said University of Dayton sociology
professor Steven Dandaneau, who serves on the Dayton Poverty
Reduction Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the white leaders who are going to parallel their
black counterparts on poverty issues? Why aren't they with them
fighting the good fight?''
</P>
<P>
   Some outsiders disdain, ridicule and discriminate against Tract
19 residents as ``poor white trash'' with no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They migrated here from Appalachia the way blacks migrated
from the South toward industrial jobs in the North,'' says
Dandaneau. ``They've experienced pretty considerable discrimination
that black Americans experience. They're still treated as less
valuable or second-class citizens of sorts. They're called mountain
folk or hillbillies and sort of ghettoized in their own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Just east of downtown, Tract 19 is a stubborn crossroad of urban
hope and despair, a hodgepodge of sagging, battered dwellings and
expensive rehabs with pastel trim. On the north, the Mad River
brooks the poverty. To the east and west are Findlay and Keowee
streets. To the south, U.S. 35 stretches to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1990 census, per capita income was $6,979. But
a 1997 private study of the 2,297 households showed that per capita
income had nearly doubled to $12,445. The survey attributes the
increase to a scattering of middle-class professionals who recently
have purchased aging homes with visions of restoring the area's
architectural splendor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentrification is the primary factor in elevating the median
income,'' said Beach, whose church commissioned the survey. ``And
that means we have a lot of tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Tract 19, an autumn wind puffs up ``Huffman
Historic Area'' banners displayed on some renovated porches. The
elegant home of Dayton Mayor Michael R. Turner, an attorney, stands
three blocks from the aroma of free meals served at St. Paul
church.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, 1,321 or 57.5 percent of housing units here are
tenant-occupied. The average property value is $29,288.
</P>
<P>
   And on June, Terry and Ringgold streets, are the four or five
blocks of the poorest whites in Montgomery County: 34 residents
with a per capita income of $2,911, the lowest in the county,
according to the 1990 census. With a median household income of
$5,360, 100 percent lived below half the federal poverty level in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and police say crack houses open, close and reopen
here like ``moveable feasts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not peaceful in the least, but it's not a war zone,''
said Cyndi Johnson, 20, a convenience store worker who lived on
Ringgold Street last summer.
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 city nuisance ordinance, which can require landlords to
evict tenants involved in drugs or prostitution, appears to have
lowered residents' tolerance for crack traffic, Dayton Police
Officer Mitchell Olmsted said. Since 1993, calls to police on
narcotics violations in the June Street area have risen from six in
1993 to 54 so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe it's bottomed out, hit rock bottom, and it's
turned the corner,'' Olmsted said. Others who live in Tract 19 come
and go, boarding in one room here or there, drifting in and out of
trouble with the law, finding shelter with friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   When it is meal time at St. Paul Church they all fall in line
together. The felons and loafers, the unfortunate, the mentally and
physically impaired. Those pummeled by bad breaks and setbacks. The
people who came this close to being somebody. The fast-food and
convenience store clerks for life. The decent, working folk trying
to hold on to their pride.
</P>
<P>
   Some seem to flinch and twitch with survival worries, no food,
no DP&AMP;L, no job, no insurance, no way. On folding tables, rows of
paper plates run the length of the gymnasium-sized room.
</P>
<P>
   James Dean, a convicted rapist who was released in 1994 after
serving 15 years in prison, is looking for a job. ``You just can't
hold down a job when you can't read and write hardly,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Joann Ward, 55, bites into hamburger casserole while explaining
that she has ``no medical'' to cover a gallbladder operation. ``Do
you know where I can get some help for it?'' she asks a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Hess, 45, says she has hurt her knee and is no longer
able to work maintenance jobs. She wants her two grandchildren to
be ``adopted'' by a church for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   When the meal is done they go from the church, down streets to
houses with no heat and empty cupboards, or down alleys to nowhere
in particular, leaving behind the portrait of Jesus with outreached
arms, and beneath it, no bread.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
