<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981205.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACT19-TEEN06-COX     12-05 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACT19-TEEN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dayton youth hold out hope for better life provided by
tool-and-die work
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In June, Mark Shade was 16 and back on the right
track.
</P>
<P>
   After a bad year in which he skipped ``way too many days'' of
school.
</P>
<P>
   After a school nurse telephoned his dad because he smelled like
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   After discarding a pretty rough crowd that ended up getting
locked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's LD,'' says William Shade, 47, referring to his son's
learning disability. ``When he tries to read, the letters go
backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark was part of the St. Paul United Methodist Church Youth
Group. Sincere people like program director Monica Huffman were
prepping him and others for summer jobs, driving him wherever he
needed to go to fill out an application and encouraging him to
straighten up because opportunity is out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a numbness, I think, in the youth,'' Huffman says.
``Almost a doomsday atmosphere. They are living day by day. Even
when we talk about violence, it's `So what if I get beat up?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the church basement she hands out crayons for a goal-setting
exercise. ``They may not become an engineer, but at least they can
go beyond where they are now.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than 20 years, between 1973 and 1991, the number of
white workers earning a wage too low to lift a family out of
poverty rose from 20 percent to 28.1 percent, or nearly three in
10. If that trend continues, the odds can turn against kids like
Mark Shade ever bringing home a paycheck that will support a
family.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away at the Southeast Priority Board on East Fifth
Street, community service adviser Dean Vickers says residents in
the Burkhardt-Springfield area within Census Tract 19 are often not
prepared to take advantage of some 17,000 jobs provided by the 600
contract tooling and machine companies in the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a major need for tool-and-die industry (workers),''
Vickers says. ``Part of the city plan for 2,000 addresses educating
people for the tool-and-die industry that's been a staple in Dayton
for years. But people in this community are being overlooked or
aren't taking initiative, or companies are not willing to take a
risk with these people.''
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Mark Shade tried to become a boy worth a
risk, believing that if he ``did good'' at the Patterson Career
Center in the semesters to come, a good manufacturing job would
await him upon graduation.
</P>
<P>
   He worked part time at St. Paul's alongside his father, whom
Pastor David Beach hired three years ago as church janitor.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, blond, soft-spoken and sociable, Mark had a new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, Monica and Pastor Dave helped me out,'' he says.
``It's really stupid how I used to smoke weed. It don't do nothing.
A lot say it's addicting, but to me, it ain't. If you want to stop,
you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys I used to hang out with, they're still talking about
going out and doing stupid stuff that they they got locked up for
in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that a teacher at the Patterson Career Center told
him he had skill in putting things together. ``She taught me not to
give up so easily on things 'cause I get frustrated and want to
break it.''
</P>
<P>
   An infant daughter is crying.
</P>
<P>
   Mark peers into the squinty blue eyes of his 1-month-old
daughter, trying to answer the mystery of her tears. He frowns. He
is cradling her, seated on an old sofa in an alcove of the church
basement. Next to him is his ``ex,'' a 15-year-old whose mother
asked that she not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and her mom is not seeing each other,'' he explains. ``We
broke up four months before we knew she was pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark hands the baby to its mother. A pretty, wide-faced girl,
she stares into the blanket. They giggle. Mark shrugs his
shoulders. The mother asks her girlfriend seated nearby, ``Do you
want to hold her? Or is she still too little?''
</P>
<P>
   The friend shudders. ``She's still too little.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, welfare provides for the baby. ``She has everything she
needs. And she is going to have everything,'' Mark says with pride
and protection.
</P>
<P>
   In late August, Mark is all acne and uncertainty. His summer job
at the church is about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Mark sits on a window seat, his silhouette aglow with the
stained glass. He recalls a venture beyond Tract 19 and East Dayton
to suburban Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going in Kroger's and some rich stuck-up people coming
through the door were just staring at us. I could feel it and see
it. It felt weird. Somehow, they could just tell we weren't from
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do look down. They think they are better than us. ``
</P>
<P>
   It's November. Mark is 17. His baby is 6 months old.
</P>
<P>
   On a Friday night, Mark is outside the duplex where he lives
with his father, younger sister and twin brother. Mark grins into
the driver's-side window of a pinkish car caught in the blink of
blue Christmas lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my new girlfriend,'' he says as the car pulls away from
the curb.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the semester has not gone well. Out of 45 days
in the first quarter of the school year, Mark attended 13 days, his
father says.
</P>
<P>
   William Shade is less optimistic now. ``I don't know if he'll
stay in school or not,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark has a lot of girlfriends always calling the house. If he
can get some attention, he'll go along with it. He gets in with the
wrong crowd sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But William Shade is betting on his other boy, Matthew, Mark's
fraternal twin. ``Matthew is the smart one,'' Shade says.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew is short and shy. He works part time after school in the
church computer lab. So far his grades are F's and D's, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Matthew is optimistic about the future. ``Dayton's
got plenty of tool-and-die companies,'' he says. ``I'm pretty sure
I'll be able to get a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark is feeling renewed confidence, too. ``Some kind of
manufacturing job, that's what I want to do. Hopefully having a
house and a family. It's going to be hard, but you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
