<DOCNO> NYT19981205.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLLEGE-TAXBREAK-2     12-05 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLEGE-TAXBREAK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS RUSH TO INVEST IN COLLEGE SAVINGS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By LESLIE EATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When state officials announced the creation of New York's
College Savings Program in September to help parents pay for their
children's educations, it sounded like a narrow _ if nice _
election-year initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of investors, some with children who have already
graduated from college, have signed up, drawn by the program's
unusual flexibility and a tax break that is the largest in the
nation for such plans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the program began, more than $15 million has poured into
more than 5,000 accounts, and many more people are likely to sign
up this month to beat the Dec. 31 deadline for getting the tax
breaks this year; 75,000 information packets and applications have
been mailed out, according to TIAA-CREF, a private company that is
managing the program.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they are encouraged by the early response to
the program, which has not been widely advertised. ``This much in
two months _ wow,'' said Robert Maurer, president of the state's
Higher Education Services Corp., which administers grants. By this
time next year, he forecast, the program will have about 50,000
accounts and $350 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The program puts New York on the leading edge of a nationwide
trend, as states try to come up with new ways to help middle-class
residents pay for higher education. More than a dozen states have
similar programs, and at least seven more are developing them,
using New York as one of their models.
</P>
<P>
   New York's program is open to people with a lot of money and
people with just a little, people with a lot of children and people
with none. Investment accounts can be set up for grandchildren,
godchildren, friends, even for the investors themselves. And the
money in these accounts can be spent at any accredited school,
anywhere in the country, so it can be used for an undergraduate
degree, law school or courses in creative writing or cooking. If
the money is not used for education, it will be fully taxed and a 1
percent penalty will be assessed on the earning.
</P>
<P>
   A couple can put up to $10,000 a year into these accounts and
deduct that money from the income on which they pay state taxes.
People in the highest state tax bracket could cut their tax bills
by almost $700, and those who live in New York City could save
almost $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the money stays in the account and is ultimately
spent on education, the state will not tax it or the investment
profits in the account. In addition, federal taxes on the profits
will be deferred until the money is withdrawn. There is no limit on
how much anyone can contribute, though no student-to-be's account
can receive more than $100,000 in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they did not intend to create a stealth tax
break, but admit they may have soft-pedaled the program a little.
``All of us have been so involved in campaigning, and we didn't
want to give the impression that this was a campaign gimmick,''
said H. Carl McCall, who easily won re-election as state
comptroller last month and is now considering a run for the U.S.
Senate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 states have adopted some kind of tuition savings
plan, according to the National Association of State Treasurers.
And while some of these are the more common, limited programs that
allow parents to prepay tuition at a state school, for example,
many of the newer programs are like New York's and a similar
program that began in New Hampshire in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something between New York and New Hampshire is going
to be the model,'' said Peter Mazareas, executive director of the
Massachusetts Education Finance Authority. Massachusetts is among
the seven states known to be developing one of these educational
investment plans; the state already has a more common prepayment
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed legislation authorizing the states to set up
such plans in 1996. It also gave them a key piece of federal tax
relief: the investment earnings of money in these plans are not
taxed until the money is withdrawn, and then it is taxed not at the
rate of the giver, but at the presumably lower rate of the student.
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures, including New York's, began passing bills to
create the plans in 1997, but many are just now getting under way,
in part because the IRS put out the regulations governing these
plans only over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   States justify these programs by saying that it is in their
economic interest to have a well-educated work force. But elected
officials acknowledge that there are political benefits, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what people want, as the soccer moms of America have been
telling anyone who will listen,'' said Mississippi State Treasurer
Marshall Bennett. ``I've gotten more public reaction to this than
anything else that I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The investment programs are open to people with very limited
means _ New York's, for example, accepts annual contributions as
low as $250, which can be paid in $25 installments. But because
these programs rely on tax breaks, they appeal most to those who
pay taxes but find them burdensome: middle-class voters.
</P>
<P>
   And that troubles some critics, who complain that these programs
do nothing for young people whose parents are too poor or too
troubled to save for their educations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives a good deal of help to people who really don't need
it,'' said Edward Sullivan, the Manhattan Democrat who is chairman
of the Assembly's Committee on Higher Education, and who voted
against New York's program. ``How many single mothers working as
waitresses can put aside a significant amount? Those are the people
we should be helping.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall dismisses criticism of the program's appeal to
middle-class voters, calling it silly. ``People can always find
some reason to be critical,'' he said, ``but this is being marketed
to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   And many backers of such plans say they help the people who need
it most. ``If you've got a lot of money, you can afford to go to
college, and if you're lower-income, you can get grants and
fellowships,'' said Georgie A. Thomas, Treasurer of New Hampshire.
``It's the middle class that gets taken to the cleaners.''
</P>
<P>
   The $5,000-a-person tax deduction in New York's plan appears to
be the most generous in the country, although at least one other
state, Missouri, has announced plans to allow an $8,000 deduction.
Some states, like Connecticut, do not give tax deductions for
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the cost to the state is low _ it will forgo
between $20 million and $30 million of the $15 billion it collects
in personal income taxes. The administrative costs of the fund are
covered by a very small annual charge to the accounts. (It is less
than 1 percent, and about half the cost of a similar mutual fund.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Legislators decided to use the tax deduction because they
thought it would entice people to start saving, said Paul Tonko, a
Democratic assemblyman who represents Amsterdam, near Schenectady,
and who is the original sponsor of the plan. ``That way, it is not
only a savings vehicle, but also a springboard to encourage
savings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the immediate tax deduction, rather than the long-term
benefits of saving for college, that is drawing people into the
plan, said Ed Slott, an accountant in Rockville Centre who
specializes in taxes and estates. ``The things people do to save a
buck on taxes,'' he said. ``If the state gave us a tax deduction
for building a new Yankee Stadium, it would be up already.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, Slott said, the tax incentive is pushing
people to participate in a good program that has other benefits.
One of them is that the money in these accounts must be used for
education _ tuition, room, board, books, supplies _ and cannot be
spent on, say, a car. This has a big appeal for grandparents, Slott
said, because ``they like to give money to kids that the kids can't
spend'' on other things.
</P>
<P>
   Some private firms that sell investment products and services
complain that they will not be able to compete against the state's
program because they cannot offer a tax deduction. ``The tax
benefit is so compelling, it will crowd out competition in the New
York market,'' said Peter Roberts, who runs the College Savings
Bank in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But some accountants say the wealthy and the financially
sophisticated may not find the state program very appealing. The
tax deduction, though a great benefit to the average consumer, is
not big enough to be significant to millionaires, said Michael
Kilgallen, a senior supervisory tax specialist at KPMG Peat
Marwick, the big accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   And the program does not allow the donors to control how their
money is invested, Kilgallen noted. To comply with federal rules,
TIAA-CREF handles all the investing, and has set up a system under
which about half the money in an account is invested mainly in
stocks when the beneficiary is young; the investments become less
risky as the child gets closer to age 18.
</P>
<P>
   The program's managers say it is still too early to tell exactly
who is going to participate in the plan. But they do know that the
biggest group of accounts _ a fifth of the total so far _ are being
opened for people who are 16 or older, said TIAA-CREF vice
president Timothy Lane. Although the exact breakdown is not yet
clear, some of these are adults opening accounts for themselves, he
said, while others are parents with teen-age children, for whom
``college is more than a theoretical reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the same account may serve both purposes. Maurer, of the
Higher Education Services Corp., said he had opened an account for
his son, who just graduated from college and may want to go to
graduate school. But if his son decides against it, Maurer said, he
hopes to use the money himself, to take courses at the Culinary
Institute of America in Hyde Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
