<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVLON-RECONVERSION-R     12-05 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVLON-RECONVERSION-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 CONVERTING THE FORMER REVLON COMPLEX IN EDISON, N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RACHELLE GARBARINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last 40 years, Revlon Corp. has owned a 63-acre complex
in the heart of the Middlesex County, N.J., township of Edison,
which includes the cosmetics giant's worldwide research and
development center.
</P>
<P>
   It consisted of a vacant 750,000-square-foot manufacturing
plant, a 250,000-square-foot office building and a
100,000-square-foot research component. The property now has a new
owner and a different future as a mixed-use complex for multiple
tenants, including Revlon.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago Starwood Heller LLC paid $24 million for the
property, a huddle of office, research and manufacturing buildings.
It then leased back to Revlon the research component as well as
75,000 square feet of space in the office building.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Starwood Heller _ a joint venture of G. Heller Enterprises
of Edgewater and Starwood Opportunity Fund IV, an affiliate of
Starwood Capital Group of Greenwich, Conn. _ is advancing a
$25-million modernization, redevelopment and expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes the introduction of a new retail component for
the complex, a mile and a half southwest of the intersection of
Route 27 and Interstate 287. The redevelopment of the property,
which the partners are financing, will be done in stages and is
expected to take two years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for overhauling the four-story office building and
razing all but 140,000 square feet of the 750,000 square feet in
the vacant manufacturing space in two connecting buildings. The
remaining industrial space will be refurbished and the razed space
will be replaced with a 250,000-square-foot warehouse and
distribution structure built on speculation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, discussions are under way with township officials
to turn some 18 undeveloped acres in the middle of the property
into 150,000 square feet of retail space. The initial design for
the retail component was rejected, but the partners are redesigning
it to resemble a traditional town center with a village green
surrounded by shops and a clock tower whose site has not yet been
determined. The village green will be across from Edison's
municipal complex.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood Heller president Gene Heller said the hope is that the
retail component, which requires a zoning change and municipal
approvals, will serve as a true town center for the community,
which does not have a traditional downtown, as well as an amenity
for the office and industrial users on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Edison Mayor George Spadaro said the retail concept ``is a
potentially attractive idea if the developers come up with a
workable plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But of the overall concept of redeveloping the property, Spadaro
said: ``Edison is at a point that some of its older commercial
areas have become a bit dilapidated and we are looking hard at them
for redevelopment.'' If successful, he said, this project will
replace empty old factories with new construction, which will
``beautify the neighborhood and bring in additional tax revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Revlon once occupied all the buildings on the site, which it
purchased in the early 1950s from Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the
health-care giant. At that time a single 75,000-square-foot
manufacturing building sat on the property, which Revlon expanded
over time to 10 times its original size. In the 1980s the company
added the office and research buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Early this decade Revlon sold its Max Factor division to Procter
&AMP; Gamble, thus reducing its need for the manufacturing buildings,
which it closed five years ago. In turn the administrative support
staff for the manufacturing operation was relocated to other plants
in Arizona, North Carolina and Florida, decreasing the amount of
office space Revlon occupied to 75,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesperson, who declined to be named, said the sale
of the property had been a purely financial decision and had no
impact on the current or future operations in Edison. There is a
stable workforce in place there and it made sense to keep it there,
the spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   Heller said Starwood Heller had purchased the site because ``we
saw the ability to improve the property from an old manufacturing
facility to a higher and better use.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor was the site's location on Route 27, not far from
such major roadways as Interstate 287, the Garden State Parkway,
the New Jersey Turnpike and Routes 1 and 9. Retaining Revlon as a
tenant also provided ``us with an immediate income stream,'' Heller
added.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex County has 15.6 million square feet of office space,
making it one of the larger submarkets in the 11-county northern
New Jersey office market. As of the third quarter the vacancy rate
for Class A space in the county was 15.8 percent, up from 8.2
percent the same time last year _ the result of AT&AMP;T's vacating
late last year a 420,000-square-foot block of space in East
Brunswick. For Class B space, like the former Revlon office
building, the rate is 19.6 percent, down from 25.4 percent,
according to Grubb &AMP; Ellis, the national commercial brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing more space being leased than is being returned
to the market,'' said Arthur Della Salla, regional director of
research at the brokerage's West Orange office. ``In turn rents are
rising.'' For instance, annual average per square foot rents for
Class B space rose to $20.77, from $19.44 in 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heller said the partners expected to lease the remaining 175,000
square feet of office space at the Edison project for about $18 a
square foot ``to beat our competition.'' He said they also planned
to invest $3 million in improvements to the office building.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The work, to begin in 30 to 60 days, includes upgrading the
mechanical systems, lobby and elevators, as well as refurbishing
common areas and enhancing the landscaping around the building.
Heller said the site had 2,229 parking spaces, which he called more
than adequate for the multiple tenants the project intends to draw.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex County is one of the state's largest industrial
markets. It has been accommodating companies looking for regional
locations, with the New Jersey Turnpike corridor, especially the
stretch from Exit 10 south to exit 8A, drawing much of the
attention. The Starwood Heller project in Edison is not far from
Exit 10.
</P>
<P>
   Grubb &AMP; Ellis put the third-quarter industrial vacancy rate in
the county at about 3.4 percent, down from 4.5 percent for the same
period in 1997. In that same time average per square foot asking
rents rose by 29 cents to $4.60 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are competing for the same tenants who are shopping
around,'' Della Salla said, noting that more than 4 million square
feet of warehouse/distribution space was under construction or
proposed in the county in both build-to-suit and speculative
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it is in Edison, where the largest of the speculative
projects is under way. A 1.3-million-square-foot development
consisting of office, warehouse and distribution space in three
connecting buildings is rising on 50 acres in a 410-acre industrial
park at the foot of Mill Road in the eastern sector of the
township. The developer is Heller Industrial Parks of Edison, which
owns the park (and has no connection with Starwood Heller).
</P>
<P>
   Heller Industrial Parks president Jeffrey Milanaik said the
first 250,000-square-foot building had been fully rented at $4 to
$4.25 a square foot as has 50,000 square feet in the second,
480,000-square-foot building. ``Based on that activity we expect
the entire project to be completed and leased by June,'' Milanaik
said. He added, however, that if all the proposed projects are
built there could be a glut.
</P>
<P>
   Heller thinks otherwise. ``There is enough room for everyone to
succeed,'' he said. But to compete, he said, much of the existing
industrial space at the Revlon site, which with its 14-foot high
ceilings is obsolete, will be demolished and replaced with a
250,000-square-foot structure with 28- to 32-foot ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition of the old industrial building is to start next
month, with construction of the new one to begin in March.
Completion will follow nine months later. Rents are expected to be
in the $4 a square foot range or possibly higher.
</P>
<P>
   The possible start of the retail component is still a year away,
Heller said, noting that he was hopeful that a plan could be
devised that the township would support. Otherwise, he said, he
will redevelop those 18 acres as additional office or
warehouse-and-distribution space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
