<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT &LR;      12-05 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONALISTS OUST TAIPEI MAYOR IN VOTE WATCHED BY CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ The Nationalist Party challenger unseated
Taipei's popular mayor Saturday in a suspenseful election that was
closely watched abroad because of its possible effects on Taiwan's
relations with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Defeating the incumbent by a surprising 51 percent to 46
percent, according to unofficial results, the challenger, Ma
Yin-jeou, 48, established himself as a new star of the Nationalist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter whether you voted for me or not, my victory
is everybody's victory,'' he said Saturday night in a speech to
tens of thousands of wildly celebrating supporters in midtown
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the mayoral contest, the Nationalist Party reasserted
itself across much of Taiwan. In elections for the national
legislature, which was expanded to include 225 representatives, the
party won a commanding 124 seats, according to preliminary
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the mayoral contest, considered too close to call,
that captivated the country. By defeating Chen Shui-bian, 47, Ma
set back the career of a man considered a major contender for the
presidency in elections in March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's Democratic Progressive Party pledges to seek eventual
independence from mainland China, which regards Taiwan as a
renegade province. The party's ascension to national power would
raise tensions across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalist Party, or Kuomintang, while promoting Taiwan's
separate status in the world, is formally committed to eventual
reunification with the mainland. This symbolic gesture is
considered crucial by China, which threatens to attack if Taiwan
ever declares legal independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters are giving the Kuomintang another chance,'' said
Andrew Yang, a political scientist at National Sun Yat-sen
University in Kaohsiung. But Yang said the approval of many voters
was contingent on further efforts by the party to rid itself of
cronyism, to make its internal operations more democratic and to
define a program for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were a major setback for the Democratic
Progressive Party, which was born in the 1980s in opposition to the
Nationalist dictatorship that dated to 1949, when Chiang Kai-shek
fled the Communist victory on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Chen became Taiwan's first directly elected mayor in 1994 and
won high public approval for improving traffic flows and attacking
vice. But some saw him as high-handed and he lost ground Saturday
in former strongholds where his efforts to suppress karaoke bars
and prostitution cost jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He met his match in Ma, a former justice minister and a graduate
of Harvard Law School who is known for his scrupulous honesty.
There were few substantive issues in the campaign. Ma promised to
do a better job and make Taipei a ``world class city.'' Handsome
and vigorous, he used a drawing of a jogger as his campaign logo.
</P>
<P>
   Ma was greatly helped as many members of the New Party, _ which
comprises breakaway Nationalists who are strong supporters of
reunification with the mainland _ deserted their own candidate to
support him and insure the defeat of Chen. In legislative
elections, too, the New Party suffered a collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Ma overcame a feared bias against ``mainlanders'' _ those from
families that fled China in 1949 _ who are sometimes resented by
the majority of ``native'' Taiwanese. Ma was born in Hong Kong and
moved here when he was 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to work with you all together,'' he said in his
victory speech, extolling his ethnically inclusive concept of a
``new Taiwan person.'' At one point he switched from Mandarin
Chinese to the Taiwan dialect.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's popular president, Lee Teng-hui of the Nationalist
Party, says he will step down after this term. Within Nationalist
Party circles Ma is considered too young and inexperienced to run
in 2000, and he has not been close to Lee or the party
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But his victory and the party's strong national showing have
prevented a serious crisis of confidence in the party. Vice
President Lien Chan and another party heavyweight, James Soong, are
considered leading contenders for nomination for the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   Chen remains the best-known opposition figure, popular in much
of Taiwan, and political experts here do not count him out as a
candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Before a dejected crowd Saturday night, Chen offered
congratulations to Ma and said, ``I hope he can fulfill the city's
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I lost,'' he said, ``I feel my team has done a good
job in making Taipei a better place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rare plus for the Democratic Progressives, Frank Hsieh,
their candidate for mayor of the second-largest city, Kaohsiung,
was a surprise victor by a narrow margin over the Nationalist
incumbent, Wu Den-yih.
</P>
<P>
   Taipei itself was quiet Saturday after a week of frenzied
campaigning. Residents strolled to neighborhood polling places in
schools, fire stations and temples where they stamped their choices
for mayor, city council and the national legislature on long paper
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters marveled at a democratic process that in just one
decade has become deeply ingrained.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the late 1980s did the Nationalists give free rein to
the building opposition. The first direct legislative elections
were in 1991, the first mayoral elections in the two major cities
were in 1994, and the first presidential election was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Vote-buying has been a problem, especially on the part of the
wealthy and well-organized Nationalists, but it is declining and
mainly confined to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the elections are peaceful and well organized, and after
we get the results everyone will accept them,'' said Tseng Li-ming,
a 64-year-old bank officer, as he left the midtown college where he
voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you don't do a good job, you'll get voted out,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
