A4672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUNS06-COX     12-05 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS FOR NATIONAL WAITING PERIOD FOR GUN BUYERS
 &HT;    350&AMP;add.
 &HT;    Eds: Subs for the previously budgeted SOCIAL-RADIO.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Saturday he would ask
Congress next year to impose a national waiting period on handgun
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly national radio address, Clinton said a federally
mandated delay between the purchase and delivery of a handgun would
be one of his top priorities. He did not indicate how many days he
would seek. Many states already impose a delay, but the time
periods vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This 'cooling-off' period will help prevent rash acts of
violence and give authorities more time to stop illegal gun
purchases,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the national handgun waiting period, Clinton said
he would ask Congress for a lifetime ban on gun ownership for
juveniles convicted of violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why young people convicted of violent crimes
should be allowed to buy guns on their 21st birthday,'' Clinton
said, ``and I want to thank Sen. Bob Dole for his recent strong
public support of this idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's call for a ban on gun ownership for juveniles
convicted of violent crimes comes after a year in which the nation
has been shocked by children gunning down their classmates in
schools, and then frustrated to learn that the killers would be
free when they became adults.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he also was concerned that guns sold at gun
shows might not be subject to federal laws requiring background
checks. Clinton said he would ask Attorney General Janet Reno and
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin `` to find ways to close this
loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida last month passed a constitutional amendment allowing
counties to require background checks for sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said national background checks by the Justice
Department began last week, and that over 100,000 checks blocked
more than 400 convicted felons from purchasing guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more that 100 illegal gun sales blocked each day. Who
knows how many lives were saved?'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton noted the new checks have been challenged in
federal court by the National Rifle Association. Clinton said he
would oppose any efforts to weaken the Brady Bill, which
established the checks.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the weekly Republican radio address that follows Clinton's,
Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr. of Florida outlined GOP goals for reforming
Social Security. Shaw will be one of the participants in the White
House Social Security conference Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who will be chairman of the House Ways and Means Social
Security subcommittee when the new Congress convenes next month,
called Social Security ``one of the best things about America.''
</P>
<P>
   But the congressman, a father of four and grandfather of eight,
noted that the program's long-range financial future is in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said Republicans would seek to reform the system in ways
that would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Protect current and future retirees, especially women.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improve fairness across generational lines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maintain the safety net for the needy and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide new options for younger workers.
</P>
<P>
   While not offering specifics of those options, Republicans, in
general, have supported allowing workers to directly invest a
portion of their payroll taxes toward their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw echoed other Republican leaders in calling on Clinton to
offer a plan for reforming Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how Social Security reforms always began in the past,
and we agree with the president that we should save Social Security
first,'' Shaw said. ``Because the president is elected by all the
people, he alone is best positioned to build a bipartisan consensus
to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has indicated that Clinton will not offer a plan
if it appears _ as they believe it does now _ that doing so would
polarize debate over reform.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
