</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-WITNESS-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS OFFICIALS NOT TO BLAME IN DEATH OF WITNESS' MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A jury on Friday rejected the assertions of a
witness in a murder case who sued local authorities on the basis
that they failed to protect his mother, who was killed in a
drive-by shooting after he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Cooksey, 37, said officials from the city of Compton,
Calif., and Los Angeles County had a duty to protect him and his
mother, Viola Woods, in exchange for his testimony. Though Cooksey
was placed in protective custody at a hotel, Ms. Woods, 51, was
not.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woods, who was often homeless, was shot and killed while
walking down a street in the Watts section of Los Angeles on Aug.
6, 1994, 12 days after Cooksey said he received a death threat that
mentioned his mother. Cooksey had testified at a preliminary
hearing in the murder case nine months before.
</P>
<P>
   The Superior Court jury, which began deliberations late
Wednesday, found that the county was not negligent in failing to
protect Ms. Woods. Though jurors found the City of Compton
negligent, they did not award Cooksey damages for infliction of
emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Cooksey's case was in part the impetus for a law that took
effect in California this year creating a comprehensive statewide
witness protection program and setting aside $3 million to pay for
it. The case inspired some of the bill's provisions, including one
requiring a written agreement between the witness and the
authorities. Cooksey asserted that he was verbally assured that his
mother would be protected but that the authorities failed to follow
through on the promise.
</P>
<P>
   Cooksey had testified at a preliminary hearing for Regis Thomas,
a reputed gang member who was a suspect in the killing of two
Compton police officers in February 1993. Cooksey was arrested on
an unrelated charge a month later, and told investigators that
Thomas had bragged to him about shooting the officers and had given
him a gun, which Cooksey sold.
</P>
<P>
   Cooksey helped police recover the weapon, which matched the
results of a ballistics test, and agreed to testify against Thomas,
who was convicted and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Compton and the county questioned the authenticity
of the death threat Cooksey said he received, and maintained that
they had made efforts to find Ms. Woods and find a place for her to
stay. No direct link was ever established between Cooksey's
testimony and his mother's death; no suspect in Ms. Woods' killing
was ever arrested, and police believe the bullet that killed her
may have been intended for rival gang members on the street at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   Two other legal claims in Cooksey's suit were dismissed midway
through the trial, when the judge ruled that there was no special
relationship established between the authorities and Ms. Woods that
required them to protect her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a witness protection case,'' said Peter Glick, a
lawyer who defended the county. ``There's no credible evidence that
Ms. Woods' killing was related in any way to Calvin Cooksey
testifying. There was no evidence of a special relationship that
would place liability on the County of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooksey's lawyer, Daniel Rodriguez, said that his client's
criminal record made him an unsympathetic plaintiff, and that the
verdict could be a disincentive to the authorities to protect
witnesses and their families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
