<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISSUEADS06-COX     12-05 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISSUEADS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign funding focus predicts more attack ads, soft money
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Academics, political consultants and journalists
gathered at the National Press Club last week to digest the results
of the Nov. 3 elections, focusing not on who won or lost but on how
the game was played.
</P>
<P>
   Such academic exchanges usually produce a wide variety of
conflicting opinions. But on one point, the group agreed: the
federal system of contribution limits enacted after Watergate is
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barriers are down,'' said Alex Castellanos, a noted
Republican media consultant. ``Really, there are no rules.''
</P>
<P>
   While analysts differ over whether this development is good or
bad for American democracy, the implications for the 2000 elections
are already clear:
</P>
<P>
   _ The two political parties, which many believed were becoming
increasingly irrelevant in American elections, have re-emerged as
the dominant players. Issue ads, produced by the parties and funded
by unregulated soft money, greatly expanded the reach of the
parties in 1998 and will be an even bigger force in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Campaign advertising will become even more negative.
Researchers for the Annenberg Public Policy Center here found that
60 percent of the issue ads produced by the political parties after
Sept. 1 were ``pure attack.'' Voters across the country who
complained about the negative advertising and who turned out in
record low numbers this year, will likely see even more negative
advertising in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unions, corporations and other special interest groups
historically barred from giving to campaigns will contribute even
greater sums of unregulated soft money to the two major political
parties, which will then spend it on issue ads in targeted races.
The influx of soft money will ensure that the airwaves are
saturated with political advertising and, some argue, put more
pressure on the parties to reward the contributors with favorable
legislation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money that is coming in is coming in from interests whose
goal is simple: to get public policy decisions to benefit them,''
said Fred Wertheimer of Democracy 21, an opponent of soft money.
``Very often that comes at the expense of the voter, the taxpayer.
If you wonder why tobacco legislation or health care legislation
gets all bogged up in Congress and you never get to decisions on
the merits, I suggest you look at all the money pouring into the
parties for soft money ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax exemption exploitation
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer estimates that unregulated soft money contributions
to the political parties could reach $750 million in 2000, more
than three times the amount donated in 1996. Federal law bars
unions and corporations from giving directly to candidates, but
they can give unlimited amounts of soft money _ intended for
general party-building activities _ to parties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the two parties collected soft money contributions and
spent much them on issue advertisements for President Clinton and
GOP nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the political parties adopted the same strategy toward
the congressional midterm elections, channeling millions in soft
money to issue ads in specific states and districts. Issue ads,
even if they mention a candidate by name, are not subject to the
same funding restrictions as candidate ads, which must be paid for
with money raised from individuals in donations of no more than
$1,000 per election.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, millions of unregulated donations also flowed to
outside groups, many of which exploited their tax-exempt status to
accept contributions and channel them into issue ads targeted at
specific candidates. Many analysts predicted the influence of these
groups to be even bigger in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the political advocacy of independent organizations in
individual Congressional races paled in comparison to the money
spent on issue ads by the two major parties. The Annenberg Center
estimates the two parties spent around $66 million on issue ads,
with Republicans outspending Democrats 2 to 1. But that figure
doesn't include the amount state parties kicked in to match the
national party contributions to produce the ads.
</P>
<P>
   After Sept. 1, the two political parties accounted for 70
percent of the more than 400 issue ads appearing on television,
with only 11 independent organizations accounting for the remaining
30 percent, Annenberg found.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Owens, who heads the Internal Revenue Service's divisions
on tax exempt organizations, said there appeared to be less
activity from tax exempts but that may only have been because 1998
was not a presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen what happens in about a year when the
presidential elections start heating up,'' Owens said. ``Then we'll
see if there has been a sea change here.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the outside spending was decidedly mixed.
Americans for Job Security, a trade association representing large
insurance companies, reportedly spent $1.8 million against Rep.
Frank Pallone (D-N.J.) in New Jersey's 6th Congressional District.
Pallone captured 57 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate GOP group 3-for-9
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation for Responsible Government, a moderate
Republican-leaning group which spent more than $800,000 in nine
Congressional Districts, lost six races and won only three.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups may have amassed the clearest track record.
The Sierra Club, which spent $6 million in 1997 and 1998 on issue
ads, voter guides and field operations, won 20 out of 23 targeted
races. The group ran negative ads against several incumbents who
lost, including Sen. Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.), Sen. Alfonse D'Amato
(R-N.Y.) and Rep. Bill Redmond (R-N.M.). It's impossible to
determine if the group's spending was the deciding factor in any of
these contests.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, head of the Annenberg Center, argued
that the diminished role of outside groups and the increased
activity of the parties was essentially a positive development in
1998. Voters have an easier time understanding the agenda of the
political parties than they do outside organizations that may not
be familiar to them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With parties running negative ads, candidates themselves were
free to run more ads that were either positive or contrasted their
record with that of their opponent, Jamieson said.
</P>
<P>
   The money spent on issue ads by the political parties also
produced mixed results. The Republican Party spent more than the
Democrats on congressional races, but ended up losing five seats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats outspent Republicans in North Carolina and pulled off
an upset with the election of trial lawyer John Edwards over
Faircloth. Yet in Wisconsin, Republicans poured at least $1 million
and perhaps $2 million into issue ads to defeat Sen. Russell
Feingold (D-Wis.) and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold was the chief Democratic sponsor of campaign finance
reform legislation in the Senate. The bill, which was blocked by
Republicans, would have banned soft money to the political parties
and made issue ads launched in the last 60 days of a campaign
subject to the same funding guidelines as candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that many analysts considered political suicide,
Feingold refused an offer from the Democratic Party to counter the
GOP ads with issue ads of its own. When the Democratic Party
decided to run ads anyway, Feingold demanded that the party stop
advertising on his behalf, a public show of integrity that may have
worked to his ultimate advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to have a Wisconsin-based, restrained campaign
that responded to the thing that I have heard Wisconsinites say
over and over again,'' said Feingold, who won by 35,000 votes.
``They believe, like most Americans, that campaigns are too long,
too expensive and too negative.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
