<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS06-COX     12-05 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stores offer broad range of topics for business-minded reader
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seldom in recent years have gift-givers had such a
broad range of topics to choose from in the business, economics and
investment sections of bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   There's this year's bearish stock market, the many fables and
foibles of American business, the escalation of the importance of
cyberspace in our lives and, of course, the approach of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   No article about books in this genre can do more than point the
way, which is all this attempts to do. The best advice is to visit
a good bookstore and browse.
</P>
<P>
   Being gift suggestions, these are all hardback books. But good
paperbacks are also available, and less costly.
</P>
<P>
   As for price, an effort was made to keep the list as inexpensive
as possible. If those on the list appear pricey, it's because books
are pricey.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Wall Street emerged as one of the most important topics
of 1998, given the number of us who have retirement money in mutual
funds and stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A timely arrival was ``The Bear Book: Survive and Profit in
Ferocious Markets'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $24.95). Author John
Rothchild aims to convince investors they can make money in a bear
market as well as in a bull market. This has been a good year to
test his thesis, and we may get another chance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the revised and updated edition of ``Stocks for the
Long Run'' (McGraw-Hill, $29.95), a landmark study of the stock
market by Wharton economics professor Jeremy J. Siegel. It makes a
compelling case that common stocks really are the best long-term
investment.
</P>
<P>
   In ``What Works on Wall Street: A Guide to the Best-Performing
Investment Strategies of All Time'' (McGraw-Hill, $29.95), money
manager James P. O'Shaughnessy looks at the many strategies
investors have used to make money. This is a good reference book.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone interested in the history of investment markets,
``Wall Street: A History'' (Oxford, $30) by Charles R. Geisst is
readable and authoritative.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there are many ``how-to-do-it'' books for people
interested in the techniques of personal finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiplinger's Practical Guide to Your Money'' (Kiplinger Books,
$29.95) by Ted Miller, editor of Kiplinger's Personal Finance
Magazine, is a comprehensive example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schwab's Guide to Financial Independence: Simple
Solutions for Busy People'' (Crown, $23) comes from the man who
pioneered discount investing.
</P>
<P>
   More complex is ``Contrarian Investment Strategies: Beat the
Market by Going Against the Crowd'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25), by
Wall Street money manager and frequently quoted mutual fund
executive David Dreman.
</P>
<P>
   Author Peter Siris sees brokers and other market pros as the
investor's chief adversary in ``Guerrilla Investing: Winning
Strategies for Beating the Wall Street Professionals'' (Longstreet,
$24).
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for Wall Street's turmoil this year is the
nature of the new global economy. Several very good books offer
insights into how the global economy got that way and what may come
next.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most complete is ``The Wealth and Poverty of Nations:
Why Some Are So Rich and Some So Poor'' (Norton, $30). With wit,
wisdom and authority, Harvard historian David S. Landes provides
valuable insights on why today's world is the way it is,
economically and politically.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Commanding Heights: The Battle Between Government and
the Marketplace That Is Remaking the Modern World'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $26), authors Daniel Yergin and Joseph Stanislaw look at
the post-Cold War world and the forces that enabled the West's
market economy to prevail over the Soviet-brand command economy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest engines driving global economic change is the
computer, and the worldwide network of computers known as
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   For history-minded readers, here's a recent book that
demonstrates the Internet is not the first technology that
revolutionized our lives. In ``The Victorian Internet: The
Remarkable Story of the Telegraph and the Nineteenth Century's
On-Line Pioneers'' (Walker, $22), Tom Standage shows how the
telegraph did to 19th century society what the computer and
Internet are doing to ours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information Rules: A Strategic Guide to the Network Economy''
(Harvard Business School Press, $29.95), by Carl Shapiro and Hal R.
Varian, warns those who must apply the new technology not to ignore
``basic economic principles.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wired magazine Executive Editor Kevin Kelly takes a
different position in ``New Rules for the New Economy'' (Viking,
$19.95), contending the new economy of networking has changed the
rules and you'd better know them to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   On a more practical level, author Patricia Seybold explains
business via the Internet is already widely popular with business,
and is likely to become more popular with consumers. Her book is
``Customers.Com: How to Create a Profitable Business Strategy for
the Internet and Beyond'' (Times Business, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed is our fascination with the movers
and shakers of business, living and dead. Biographies are among the
most readable of gift books.
</P>
<P>
   The all-capitals part of the title of ``TITAN: The Life of John
D. Rockefeller Sr.'' (Random House, $30) reminds us how few titans
there are in today's structured business environment. Author Ron
Chernow's portrait of one of the biggest of America's 19th century
robber barons is compelling and highly readable.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Welch, General Electric's chief executive officer, has been
the subject of at least two mostly favorable books in recent years.
In the latest _ ``Jack Welch, General Electric, and the Pursuit of
Profit'' (Knopf, $29.95) _ author and former Wall Street Journal
reporter Thomas F. O'Boyle is considerably less friendly to the
head of one of the world's most admired corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Another personality book is ``In Sam We Trust: The Untold Story
of Sam Walton and How Wal-Mart Is Devouring America'' (Time Books,
$25.95). Author and journalist Bob Ortega clearly admires his
subject, the legendary founder of the Wal-Mart chain. But as the
subtitle suggests, he is also concerned with the devastating impact
Walton's price-cutting strategy has had on small business.
</P>
<P>
   Bigness is the focus of Bruce Wasserstein's ``Big Deal: The
Battle for Control of America's Leading Corporations'' (Warner
Books, $30). A deal maker himself, the author takes the reader on a
tour of some of the biggest in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work In Progress'' (Random House $27.95) is Michael Eisner's
account of how he and his partners rescued the legendary Walt
Disney Co. from near-disaster and went on to create one of the
world's biggest entertainment-communications empires.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the coming millennium has already inspired a
host of books, with more to come in 1999. Many are apocalyptic in
nature.
</P>
<P>
   But there are books available for readers looking for upbeat and
logical forecasts of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roaring 2000s: Building the Wealth and Lifestyle You
Desire in the Greatest Boom in History'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is
an updating of Harry S. Dent's earlier book on the same subject. He
contends baby boomers, just now entering their peak spending and
investment years, will fuel unprecedented economic growth for years
to come.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Kiplinger, editor-in-chief of Kiplinger's Personal
Finance Magazine and The Kiplinger Washington Letter, argues in
``World Boom Ahead: Why Business and Consumers Will Prosper''
(Kiplinger Books, $27.95) that we are on the threshold of an
unprecedented surge of economic prosperity, driven by technology.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything on the business bookshelf has to be serious, of
course. Here, too, gift shoppers have much from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   For humor, there is Dilbert, whose latest misadventures are
chronicled in ``Journey to Cubeville'' (Andrews McMeel, $19.95) by
author Scott Adams. The ``Everyman'' geek of the computer era has
become a cult cartoon figure (and Atlanta Journal-Constitution
regular).
</P>
<P>
   Satirist P.J. O'Rourke tackles the topic that fascinates
everybody _ money _ in ``Eat the Rich: A Treatise on Economics''
(Atlantic Monthly Press, $24).
</P>
<P>
   ``Pickup Trucks: A History of the Great American Vehicle''
(Black Dog &AMP; Levanthal, $24.98) offers an affectionate look at the
vehicle that has come to dominate interstates as well as back
roads. Justin Lukach explains why.
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous reference books of value to someone in, or
interested in, business, investments and economics.
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point for a reference shelf is Stuart Crainer's
``The Ultimate Business Library: 50 Books That Shaped Management
Thinking'' (Amacom, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   As the subtitle suggests, it is about the most important
business books in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
