<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Know where your donations are going
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During the holiday season, you may give to charities
``from the heart.'' But be sure to use your mind also to avoid
wasting your money.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday spirit leads many people to give more freely, and
solicitors _ honest and dishonest _ know this. Americans annually
give more than $100 billion to charities and other nonprofit groups
_ and about $1 billion goes to frauds.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Mendoza, a Columbus resident who is a national board
member of AARP, said a recent survey by the organization showed
that Americans over the age of 25 receive more than five charitable
solicitations per week by mail or telephone, with most people
deciding to contribute during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   To give wisely, there are three basic guidelines to follow:
</P>
<P>
   _ Look out for fraudulent or misleading charity solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check out the accounting and spending practices of legitimate
charities to ensure they are using your donations as you want.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are looking for an income tax deduction, be sure the
organization is not only tax-exempt but also ``qualified'' as
tax-deductible by the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``While most charity fund raising is done honestly and for good
purposes, there are con artists that take advantage of Americans'
generosity,'' said Edward Smith, president of the Atlanta Better
Business Bureau. ``But proceed carefully, and you can spot them.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips that will help you avoid fraudulent or
misleading solicitations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch out for ``copycat'' names. A shyster group may use a
name very similar to a well-known charity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reject high-pressure sales. Legitimate charities will welcome
your gift whenever you want to send it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look out for vague appeals. A legitimate charity will clearly
state its purpose, and provide written materials about its
operations and finances if you ask.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't give out credit card numbers, checking account numbers,
Social Security numbers and other personal information to unknown
telephone charity solicitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Say no to ``runners.'' Some charity cons will offer to send
someone to your house to pick up your contribution. That's a fast
way to say goodbye to your money.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Smith, look out for heart-rending appeals, full of
tears but short on facts. ``Don't give to a group simply because
`children' or `hurricane victims' or any other sympathy pull is
included in the name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ways to check things out
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate charities are just that _ honest. But they may still
be spending contributions in ways you would disapprove. They might,
for example, be spending too much on salaries and administration
expenses, not enough on helping their cause. There are, however,
several ways to check on them.
</P>
<P>
   First, you may ask the soliciting organization to send you a
copy of its most current certified audit and annual report. Even a
newly established charity should be able to provide a program
brochure and budget plan for collected funds.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources of information include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Atlanta BBB evaluates local and national soliciting
organizations based on a set of standards. For information on
charities and a copy of the bureau's charitable standards, call
404-688-4910 or write to P.O. Box 2707, Atlanta, GA 30301-2707.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Philanthropic Advisory Service of the Council of Better
Business Bureaus has published a holiday edition of its newsletter,
``Give but Give Wisely,'' which evaluates national charities on 23
standards. For a free copy, send a self-addressed, stamped
business-size envelope to Holiday Giving, Council of Better
Business Bureaus, 4200 Wilson Blvd., Suite 800, Arlington, VA
22203.
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Charities Information Bureau publishes a
quarterly newsletter, ``Wise Giving Guide.'' The first copy is
free, but there is a charge for subsequent issues if you want them.
Write to NCIB, 19 Union Square West, New York, NY 10003.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Georgia, call the secretary of state's office at
404-656-3920 to see if a charity is registered with the state. But
remember that a registration is only that _ it does not constitute
official approval. The state's information on charities may also be
accessed on the Internet at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.sos.state.ga.us/securities/charitysearch/htm.
</P>
<P>
   Rules for deductions
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to take an income tax deduction for your charitable
contribution, there are several important IRS rules to remember:
</P>
<P>
   _ You can deduct contributions only if you make them to a
``qualified organization'' as determined by the IRS. This means the
group is not only tax-exempt, but that your donation to the group
is deductible by you. All tax-exempt groups are not tax-deductible.
</P>
<P>
   _ A charitable donation is deductible only if you itemize your
deductions. If you do itemize, you will need an official receipt
for any gift of $250 or more. A canceled check is not an adequate
receipt.
</P>
<P>
   _ You may only deduct the portion of a donation that is truly
given away. You cannot take a full tax deduction on your gift if
you received anything of value in return, such as a dinner or
tickets to some affair. The value of what you received has to be
subtracted from what you gave.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some donations are not tax-deductible, including items such as
volunteer time and services and gifts to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   There are various IRS rules that apply to large donations to
charities. This gets very tricky, and you should consult a tax
attorney if you are considering a large donation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
