<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Santa's waiting for e-mail
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You won't be surprised to learn the North Pole is
wired with the latest in T3 high-speed data lines and the finest
and most powerful of servers. Santa Claus, after all, does not mess
around.
</P>
<P>
   Kids have been writing letters to Santa for a long time now.
Each year, the post office routes any letter addressed to Santa
Claus at the North Pole to helpers who answer them if they can.
This is the busy season. If you or a young one wants to write Santa
online, you'll find there are many mysterious ways to reach Saint
Nick.
</P>
<P>
   We'll list some of the Web sites here that offer free letters
from Santa. Your child can write a note to Santa, using the e-mail
address on the Web page, and receive an answer by e-mail. The sites
we will visit today offer this cyber-fast connection to Santa free.
There are also places on the Web that charge _ but no child should
have to pay to get a letter from Santa, so we'll ignore them, and
you probably should, too.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop for the day is a Web site maintained by a
commercial storefront on the Net called the Christmas Store. But
despite the commercial nature of the site, you won't pay to write a
letter to Santa using the link on the page at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .holidaytree.com/xmasnt.html. In fact, you might urge your child
to really pull out the stops and write the best possible letter.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small prize, $100, for the best letter to Santa
received at the site. While that amount might not change your
Christmas dramatically, it sure wouldn't hurt. As you'd expect,
there are also links to various products and services sold from the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas, of course, knows no nationality. So don't think it
odd that we're stopping next at the UK Online Pages at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .uk-online.com/christms
</P>
<P>
   /letter.htm. This site makes it easy, if a bit impersonal, to
send Santa a list of presents your child wants. Just fill in the
blanks, hit the button and the letter wings its way to the North
Pole.
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom has more than its share of Christmas letter
sites, and we'll visit an excellent one next. It's called Christmas
and Santa Letter and is located at http://www.north-pole.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   /index5.htm. Not only can your child use the link on this site
to write a letter to Santa, there also is a link that will let
anyone send some of the prettiest electronic Christmas cards you'll
find on the Web. There's no cost for that service, either, and the
whole family probably will enjoy this place. The electronic
Christmas cards come in all varieties, including religious themes
and funny ones, too.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Claus Online also offers a fine way to send e-mail to the
North Pole at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .santaclausonline.com/
</P>
<P>
   santapages/letter.html.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find a form to fill out on this page. Then, just a bit
after you press the button to send your e-mail to Santa, you'll get
a canned reply. While most of the letter is traditional in nature,
some plugs for the products on the commercial site are included at
the bottom. So some parents may wish to avoid this site if the
notion of blending the commercial with the sublime bothers them.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry. This is just a sampling of the places where
your child can write Santa. The selection is so broad you are sure
to be able to find the kind of site that appeals to your family.
Just use your favorite search engine and type in these search
terms: santa, online, letter. You'll get screenful after screenful
of sites that blend the old-fashioned spirit of the season with
this new-fangled Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
