<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-VPS06-COX     12-05 2017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-VPS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newcomers settling in at Delta's controls
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fred Reid doesn't know all the gory details behind the
management overhaul that brought him to Delta Air Lines _ nor does
he particularly care to.
</P>
<P>
   ``For reasons truly unknown to me, Delta got a guy named Leo,
and Leo called Fred, and here I am,'' said Reid, hired away from
Lufthansa last summer to become Delta's executive vice
president-marketing.
</P>
<P>
   While Reid isn't dwelling on Delta's past, he is among a quartet
of newcomers who'll play a big role in the future of Atlanta's
largest corporate employer.
</P>
<P>
   They are the four executive vice presidents brought in from
outside the company by Chief Executive Leo Mullin, who was hired
last year to replace longtime CEO Ronald Allen and reinvigorate
Delta's strategies and service image.
</P>
<P>
   The makeover culminated this fall with the hiring of Robert
Colman from General Electric as executive vice president-human
resources and the appointment of retired Air Force Gen. Malcolm
``Mac'' Armstrong as executive vice president-operations. It
started in April with the hiring of Warren Jenson, previously
finance chief at NBC, as executive vice president-chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   All four replaced Allen lieutenants eased out by Mullin, who has
kept only two holdovers in his top echelon: Chief Operating Officer
Maurice Worth and Vicki Escarra, executive vice president-customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Top management at Delta has turned over more completely and
quickly than I can remember at an airline that wasn't bankrupt,''
said Ray Neidl, airline analyst at ING Barings Furman Selz.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, the newcomers talked about the issues and
priorities facing them:
</P>
<P>
   Fred Reid: ``Our rightful place''
</P>
<P>
   Reid, whose domain includes route and pricing strategies,
international alliances and consumer marketing, believes Delta is
rapidly repairing service quality. The next task is to convince
skeptical customers of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key challenge is to find a way to communicate with our
passengers positively, yet realistically, that we are well on our
way to restoring our rightful place as one of the finer airlines in
the world,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has improved its industry rank in on-time performance and
mishandled baggage this year, he noted. ``By the middle of next
year, we will have put new interiors in all our planes and
radically upgraded our international business-class product.''
</P>
<P>
   To help push that message, Reid said, Delta's balloon-filled
``On Top of the World'' ad campaign may be brought down to Earth a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe sometime in 1999 we will go back to consumers with a
message saying, `OK, here's what we've done; here's what we've
accomplished in precise terms. We can always do better and will
constantly strive to do so.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reid, 48, is a smooth industry veteran who spent 22 years in
Europe. A San Francisco native and University of
California-Berkeley graduate, he went overseas for Pan Am and
American and then moved to Lufthansa, rising to chief operating
officer. At Delta, he replaced Robert Coggin.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's major strategic challenge at Delta lies in beefing up its
international alliance network, considered weak compared with
competing pacts such as United's five-way Star Alliance or
American's planned Oneworld team, to include British Airways and
others.
</P>
<P>
   While Delta has a solid partnership with Swissair and separate
deals with assorted other carriers, it's been jilted by a few
partners in recent years. ``Delta has occasionally been inattentive
in this area, and that's dead and gone,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate goal is broader ties with Air France, a partner
added last year. But Delta faces a fight for Air France's
affections from rival Continental, which also needs better European
connections.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Delta's weakest theater, the carrier soon will cement a
deal with China Southern but has only one other pact, with Korean
Air.
</P>
<P>
   Reid also takes charge of Delta's fledgling expansion in Latin
America. Early returns on new routes are mixed, and the Latin
economy is cooling, but Reid said Delta will stay the course.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Reid said Delta will continue its focus on the
Atlanta and Cincinnati hubs and on boosting market share in the
hotly contested Washington-New York-Boston corridor. The airline
has de-emphasized hubs in Dallas-Fort Worth and Salt Lake City.
``We are relatively weaker in the West and don't see that as a
critical issue,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Delta will ``aggressively pursue optimal presence
in all sales distribution channels,'' including the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Armstrong: Safety breeds success
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's first airline job was as safety chief at US Airways,
which hired the retired Air Force general in 1995 as it
re-emphasized safety after three crashes in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Armstrong was recruited by Delta as vice
president-safety and compliance, and in October Mullin named him to
succeed Harry Alger as operations chief.
</P>
<P>
   His purview includes daily flight operations and maintenance, as
well as hiring and training of flight crews and mechanics. Along
with Colman, he'll play a big role in relations with Delta's pilot
union, which is talking tough as contract negotiations loom in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   None of those broader duties alters his original priority, said
Armstrong, 56. ``Our first priority has been, is and will continue
to be safety,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're safe, everything else is easier. It eliminates
disruptions from injury or equipment damage, which means it's a lot
easier to be on time. If you're safe and on time, you have the
resources and energies left to take better care of the customer. So
a lot of good things flow from safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said Delta is boosting on-time rates by getting a
handle on operational snarls earlier in the day and reducing the
domino effect on its hub system.
</P>
<P>
   ``As early as you can, you have to figure out which flights have
to be canceled, then get the planes and crews where they need to be
to reset the airline as quickly as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that approach, we are able to recover from (severe
weather disruptions) in six hours as opposed to about 18 hours if
you just keep grinding away. In six hours you still inconvenience a
lot of people, but in 18 you inconvenience three times as many.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he's also pushing for better coordination with
marketing ``to build a schedule we can realistically handle with
the equipment we have.'' That may mean simply extending flight
times to solve chronic delays, but Armstrong said that's better
than promising an arrival time the airline can't meet.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, a Louisianian educated at Louisiana State University
and Auburn, doesn't consider himself an airline neophyte despite
his limited time in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been in the aviation business for 35 years,'' said
Armstrong, a combat pilot and commander of a 55,000-person air
group during his Air Force career. ``The management challenges are
basically the same whether military or civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Colman: Diluting the angst
</P>
<P>
   The mid-'90s saw Delta endure its first large-scale job cuts.
The turmoil hurt morale and tarnished the company's reputation as
an unusually stable employer.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of new culture will emerge remains unclear, but Colman
will help set the tone as human resources chief.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have a hand in everything from relaxed workplace policies
_ such as last week's lifting of a decades-old beard ban for most
workers _ to weightier matters such as benefits policies and labor
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real need to forge a greater trust and mutual
respect among all segments of the employee group,'' he said. ``They
are looking for better processes and much better communication from
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other major issue is to dilute as much as possible any
angst going into the pilot negotiations,'' Colman added. ``We've
got the best pilots in the industry, and we appreciate them. Having
said that, it's a two-way street, and I'm not sure they appreciate
what they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   (Since the interview, Delta has announced plans to rescind a 2
percent pilot pay cut negotiated in 1996 and boost pay for nonunion
workers as well.)
</P>
<P>
   Colman, 53 but a decade younger in appearance and demeanor, is a
New Jersey native who still vacations on the Jersey shore. He said
he belonged to four different unions while working his way through
school at Bates College in Maine and Vanderbilt University's law
school.
</P>
<P>
   But at Delta, where Colman replaced Robert Adams, he'll try to
keep unions from organizing beyond pilots. Activity has picked up
in the past few years, with two unions now courting flight
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They promise the stars, but unions are businesses that need
members to survive, and they're selling a product,'' he said. ``We
have our side of the story to tell, and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Colman began his career at Ford Motor Co. and then moved to
General Electric, winding up as a vice president at its jet engine
division in Cincinnati. By happy coincidence, he's an aviation
buff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those people who adore airplanes,'' he said. ``I
love to fly in them, be around them, go to the airport. So this is
a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Jenson: Finding the upside
</P>
<P>
   New finance chiefs are often hired for damage control _ with a
mandate to slash costs, juggle debt or scrounge up capital for a
troubled company.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson faces none of that at Delta. He and Mullin inherited a
strong profit rebound. Dropping fuel prices have enabled Delta to
boost spending on staffing and service while holding down overall
costs.
</P>
<P>
   But Jenson, 41, didn't come to Delta to coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I took the job was I thought there was a lot of
upside left at Delta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say Delta made a billion bucks last year, and that's
true. But you have to ask, `What should we be making, and what
should customer service look and feel like, and what kind of cost
disciplines should we have?''' Jenson said.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent much of his eight months at Delta rebuilding his
department _ hiring a new treasurer, controller and investor
relations chief _ and examining processes in other areas. He has
quickly developed a reputation as a bottom-liner with broad
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson said Delta learned the hard way under Allen that cost
controls can't be achieved at the expense of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last place a company should ever go is to anything visible
to the customer,'' he said. ``You look for things you don't need to
do anymore, things that are redundant and ways to do business
smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he was instrumental in imposing tighter rules on
waivers of ticket restrictions and change fees that were costing
Delta millions. The rules were relaxed slightly this fall in the
face of gripes from passengers who regard occasional waivers as a
payback for their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson said the policy has been misconstrued and was only a
small element of a broader effort to instill consistency in
ticket-handling processes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we undertook this, we talked to employees and
customers, and the No. 1 thing they told was they wanted
consistency,'' he said. ``This is a work in progress, and nobody
claims we've got it licked, but the goal is a uniform policy and
consistent application.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenson, who replaced Thomas Roeck, is a Utah native and Brigham
Young University graduate. Prior to his NBC job, he worked in
mergers and acquisitions for parent General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson said Delta has ``much greater rigor'' in preparing for
the next downturn than it did for the last one. He doesn't pretend
to know when it will come, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're preparing for all sorts of scenarios. Capacity-wise, we
have flexibility to grow, stay flat or contract if necessary. I
have no better crystal ball than you do as to the exact nature of
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
