<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFTS-KIDS06-COX     12-05 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-KIDS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gift of investment keeps on giving
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At 13, Justin Oberste already has started saving for
his long-term needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Powder Springs eighth-grader puts a third of his allowance
each week into a savings account. As soon as he gets together $100,
he moves the money into a growth stock mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   His father got him started with a cash gift that opened the
accounts three years ago. Between market appreciation and his own
contributions, he now has about $7,000 squirreled away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing is really important to me,'' Justin said. ``I know
I'll be able to get into college and get a good education. I'm just
glad my dad thought of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His story might be an inspiration to other parents and
grandparents this holiday season. Beyond all the toys and other
gifts, it is possible to give presents that will make a long-term
difference to young people.
</P>
<P>
   The gift of an investment may not be as welcomed as toys or as
exciting as something in basic green, but it has different kinds of
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of gift is going to last a lifetime,'' said Wendy
Rausch, a representative of the Stein Roe mutual fund group. ``It
grows along with the child, and it's a valuable educational tool,
teaching about money and investments and how to make them work for
the rest of their lives. I don't know that Barbie or G.I. Joe
necessarily does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some things to think about if you want to make gifts of
stock, mutual funds or the traditional U.S. savings bonds:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep a lid on transaction costs. If you're going to give $100
worth of stock, you don't want to get whacked with a sales
commission of, say, $25.
</P>
<P>
   You can look at no-load mutual funds, shares in companies that
sell directly to the public, or the very low cost Internet
brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stick with companies your kids can recognize. Don't expect
your child to show much interest in some obscure biotechnology
company, writes analyst Charles B. Carlson in his book, ``The
Individual Investor Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Industries known to kids include fast food, retailing, toys,
entertainment, some communications and technology companies, and
consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   _ Explain the gift. Author Neale S. Godfrey suggests you treat
this as an act of parenting, not just giving. You can explain you
are investing in your children's future, she advises, and you can
build in occasions to keep track of the growing value of the
child's investments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Select the method you prefer. One is to make an actual gift.
Under the provisions of the Georgia Transfer to Minors Act, you can
make yourself the account custodian. When your child turns 21, he
or she is the owner and can do anything with the money.
</P>
<P>
   A second method is to set up a joint account, or a separate
account you own but earmarked for your child. That way you can
maintain control of how the money is spent. For either method,
remember you'll need your child's Social Security number to open an
account.
</P>
<P>
   If stocks are your choice, direct investment plans are one way
to keep the costs down. About 500 companies now sell their shares
to the public, skipping the stockbroker middleman.
</P>
<P>
   You can find a list of companies with direct purchase plans on
the Internet at http://www.netstockdirect.com. You might also check
libraries or bookstores for Charles B. Carlson's DRIP Investor
newsletter or for his several books.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the shares is easy enough. Usually you call a toll-free
telephone number and ask for information. When it comes in the
mail, you simply fill out a form and write a check.
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks. A big one is some of the interesting
companies require high minimums to open an account. For McDonald's,
the opening investment must be at least $1,000. You could buy into
Procter &AMP; Gamble, Tandy or Wal-Mart for $250.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to shop carefully: Some of the companies want
direct investors but only big accounts. ``Some of them have
implemented onerous fees,'' said Carlson. ``It pays to make sure
you read what the company sends and find all the details.''
</P>
<P>
   A second possibility is to buy your shares through a discount
broker on the Internet. There are plenty of them, and fees can run
less than $10 per transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another method is to transfer to your child shares you
already own. Your broker can tell you about the costs involved.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund shares are also a good gift. To control costs, I
recommend no-load funds _ those that do not charge an upfront sales
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for investors' dollars is fierce these days,
which is why there are nearly 10,000 mutual funds in the
marketplace. Perhaps it's no surprise at least three of them
concentrate on kid-friendly stocks.
</P>
<P>
   They are Stein Roe Young Investor fund (1-800-338-2550), USAA
First Start Growth (1-800-382-8722) and IDS New Dimensions
(1-800-328-8300). All invest in large, growth-oriented companies.
Stein Roe and USAA have no upfront fee. At IDS, ask for ``B''
shares, which have a sales charge only if you sell them within six
years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Savings Bonds are the easiest to buy. Just go to your bank
and write a check. Series EE bonds currently pay 4.6 percent
interest. Inflation-adjusted bonds are paying 5.05 percent right
now. For details, go to http://www.publicdebt.treas.gov/sav/sav.htm
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback is the low payout. For long-term investments, you
may want to go for the higher returns of stocks, despite their
higher volatility.
</P>
<P>
   For the Oberste family, the choice was the Stein Roe fund.
Justin's father picked it, and Justin likes to check out the
periodic statements he gets in the mail. For him, they mean a
college education, probably at Arkansas State. ``My dad always
wanted me to go there,'' he said. ``He showed me the campus, and it
was just beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
