u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICE-GIFT06-COX     12-05 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-GIFT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Use tact when giving at the office
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Millions of dollars and a lot of thought goes into
gift-giving for friends and family, but people aren't quite sure
how to proceed when it comes to buying gifts for co-workers. How
much should you spend? What's too personal? What's over the top?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's federal guidelines on what's a bribe and what's a
gift, but there's really nothing in the protocol about office
gift-giving that I'm aware of,'' says John Slocum, professor of
management at Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't prevented office gift-giving from becoming a big
part of the $23 million incentives industry, according to Peter
Edmunds, publisher of Incentive magazine in Huntington Beach,
Calif. A survey by Gillette Co.'s Waterman Pen division found
workers give an average of eight holiday gifts and spend about $22
on co-workers and $28 for bosses or clients.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you buy a gift without appearing thoughtless or worse,
like a brown-noser?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a message behind everything you give,'' says Andrea
Claster, a Palm Beach Gardens, Fla.-based gifts consultant known as
the ``gift doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Know what you're trying to say with gifts because gifts do
speak for you.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is no rule about how much you should spend, be
careful about going over the top. A $450 Mont Blanc pen would only
look like you're currying favor. One-size-fits-all gifts like
fruitcakes or appointment books are also out. So is ``The One
Minute Manager'' for the boss and the Franklin planner for the
woman who sits next to you who frequently forgets project
deadlines. ``Word Perfect for Dummies'' for the guy who is still
using the hunt-and-peck system of typing is also a bad idea _
unless you don't mind the frosty reception you'll get at the next
staff meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gifts) can't be seen as a self-improvement gift or
criticism,'' explains career strategist Marilyn Moats Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should they draw undue attention or unsavory gossip. The
$100-plus imported silk ties former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky gave President Clinton probably set office gift-giving
back a hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's sensitive (about gift-giving now) because of the
Lewinsky thing,'' Kennedy says. ``After the Clinton-Lewinsky thing,
there's going to be very little gift-giving. The entire country saw
that as just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   So what works?
</P>
<P>
   If your boss is constantly fumbling for a business card, giving
him or her a nice little business card holder is a thoughtful
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful with fantasy gifts or gag gifts. They can be good
only ``if the person has a sense of humor,'' Kennedy adds.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say you can never go wrong with food, especially
homemade baked goods like cookies or cake. Meats are risky because
they could offend vegetarians or those who follow strict religious
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give everybody a tin of cookies, it's hard to find
fault with that,'' Kennedy notes.
</P>
<P>
   Gift certificates, electronics and clothing are also popular,
Edmunds says. Claster suggests a weather radio or windproof
umbrella for the busy traveling executive. Many of the items can be
found on the Internet, a '90s blessing for those who don't have
time to shop.
</P>
<P>
   The key to remember, Edmunds adds, is, ``don't attempt to use a
business gift as a bribe. ... As long as it's professional and done
in good taste, that's what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid any hint of impropriety, more companies are opting to
give to charities and avoiding employee gift exchanges altogether,
Slocum says. That way, he says, ``People don't get left out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the approach Kathy Collura and her co-workers at Hewitt
Associates in Atlanta take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of giving gifts, we adopt a family and that works out
beautifully, because we're able to give gifts to people who really
need them,'' Collura said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
