</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WATERMAIN-BREAKS-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHWAY CABLE PROJECT TESTS LAW ON DIGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ Until workers dug into two buried water mains
next to the Garden State Parkway on Tuesday, installation of a $488
million E-Z Pass system on New Jersey's toll roads had been going
just fine. But now, after about 300,000 people in Jersey City,
Hoboken and Lyndhurst spent most of last Tuesday without water, the
project has become a test for the state's 4-year-old law intended
to prevent excavators from digging into buried pipelines and
cables.
</P>
<P>
   The ruptures, especially one to a 72-inch-diameter pipe linking
Jersey City to its biggest reservoir, have left New Jersey highway
officials with misgivings about the law.
</P>
<P>
   They have halted installation of fiber-optic cables for E-Z Pass
along the upper stretches of the Garden State Parkway and the New
Jersey Turnpike. Before any more trenches are dug for the cables,
they want assurances from the state's Board of Public Utilities,
which enforces the law, that their routes are safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see how effective that law is and why it wasn't as
effective as it should be,'' said Edward Gross, executive director
of the New Jersey Turnpike Authority and head of a consortium of
toll-road officials overseeing creation of the E-Z Pass system. ``I
just want to ensure we're not going to hit anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for one segment of state government to challenge the
job performance of another so publicly. But Gross said the piercing
of the pipes raised the possibility of further interruptions along
the state's major highways.
</P>
<P>
   Before the installation work was stopped, about 100 miles of
cable had been laid since summer. Planning calls for 300 more miles
to be laid by next April along the Parkway and Turnpike, as well as
the Atlantic City Expressway and a portion of Interstate 95 in
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The financial stakes for the highway consortium are high because
some of the cable will be leased to corporations and the
telecommunications industry to help defray the expense of
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Board of Public Utilities now is to ensure
that all the paths of buried pipes and electrical lines along those
300 miles are clearly marked, as required by the state's 1994 law.
Jersey City's 72-inch main was not marked before it was pierced by
crews from J. Fletcher Creamer &AMP; Sons, of Hackensack, the company
installing the fiber-optic cables for the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   James Giuliano, head of the board's investigation into the
water-pipe disruptions, says the E-Z Pass system will require one
of the largest marking operations since New Jersey created the
system in 1994. Gov. Christie Whitman called for its creation after
a gas line, damaged weeks earlier by digging equipment, finally
broke, creating a huge fireball in Edison, devastating a
condominium complex and leaving hundreds injured and one dead.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano said on Friday that the board welcomed the consortium's
safety demands, adding that the law was rigidly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires excavating companies and landowners alike to
call a clearinghouse before they begin any construction-related
digging anywhere in the state, providing the exact location of
where they plan to dig. That information is then sent to all
companies with underground pipes in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies visit the site and mark the underground routes
of their pipes, wires or cables with color-coded 24-inch tall
stakes, flags on 2-foot wire staffs, and spray-painted strips on
soft surfaces and paint on hard surfaces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To find their buried lines, some of which are decades old, the
utilities use metal detectors, electronic sounding devices and
maps. In recent months, the board has used satellites that provide
longitude and latitude to map the routes of 1,100 miles of major
gas mains, Giuliano said. Electric and water companies have started
compiling the same data for their lines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials say they are proud of the system's safety
record. They say the number of times buried lines have been hit has
declined steadily, to 3,796 hits at 2.5 million marked sites in
1997 from 4,624 hits at 1.7 million marked sites in 1995.
Excavators, utilities and the clearinghouse have been fined $1.9
million under the 1994 law for a variety of violations, including
hits, incorrect markings, and failing to provide precise locations,
the board said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's water-main ruptures created the widest public
disruption since the system was created. In another major incident,
Newark International Airport was shut for 24 hours in January 1995
after a steel beam was driven through three major power lines,
knocking out the airport's electrical system.
</P>
<P>
   Three construction companies were fined $40,000 for violations
in that incident, including failing to preserve the markings that
Public Service Electric and Gas had made days earlier, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say Jersey City's 72-inch main was hit because of
falsified records. An employee of a marking company hired by United
Water Resources, which operates Jersey City's water system,
reported that he had marked the line, when in fact he had not,
officials said. He has been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano said he expected that the board would now require
United Water Resources to verify all markings reported by its
subcontractor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
