<HEADLINE>
HOFFA TO BECOME TEAMSTERS' CHIEF AS RIVAL CONCEDES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (js) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ James P. Hoffa won election Saturday to the
post his father held when his main opponent conceded defeat.
</P>
<P>
   With the concession of Tom Leedham, Hoffa, a labor lawyer from
Detroit, will take the helm of one of the nation's largest unions.
The victory marked a return of the Hoffa name to the head of a
union that federal officials had long called the most corrupt,
particularly when Hoffa's father, James R. Hoffa, led the
organization from 1957 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Leedham admitted defeat Saturday afternoon with only about 40
percent of the votes counted, but with Hoffa holding what appeared
to be a decisive lead. Hoffa had 88,851 votes, or 54 percent, of
those counted, while Leedham, head of the warehouse division, had
65,439, or 40 percent. A third candidate, John Metz, a St. Louis
teamsters leader, had 9,225 votes, or 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The returns have made it clear that our campaign for
rank-and-file power ran out of time,'' Leedham said in a statement.
``Hoffa Jr. campaigned for four years, spent $6 million and had a
famous name, but in six short months we came from nowhere to build
a grass-roots campaign for rank-and-file power.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said that Hoffa's lead was likely to expand because
Sunday will be dedicated to counting votes from the Midwest, which
is Hoffa's home turf and was his father's stronghold. About 420,000
votes were cast; counting is expected to be finished on Sunday or
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa won the race in his second try, having lost narrowly in
1996 to Ron Carey, the incumbent. That result was overturned and a
new election ordered when a federal monitor found that three Carey
aides had misappropriated more than $700,000 from the teamsters
treasury to help the Carey campaign. Carey was later barred from
the union and Leedham replaced him as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, a graduate of the University of Michigan Law School, ran
on a platform promising to reunite the badly splintered union and
to give more power back to state and local teamster organizations.
Much of his campaign support came from a group that Leedham
attacked as a corrupt old guard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 1552EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981205.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBYA-U.N.-800&AMP;ADD-NY     12-05 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-U.N.-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN SEEKS OUT GADHAFI ON LOCKERBIE SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, gambling that he could
persuade Col. Moammar Gadhafi to turn over two suspects wanted in
the bombing of a Pan Am jet in 1988, spent hours Saturday meeting
lower-level Libyan officials with no assurance he could see the
Libyan leader.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, Libyan officials said Annan had delayed by five
hours his departure from the Mediterranean port of Sirte, where
Gadhafi usually receives his few important foreign visitors. The
delay left open the possibility of a later meeting, after Gadhafi
initially rebuffed Annan and was reported by the official Libyan
news agency, Jana, to be ``in a camp in the desert.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan, whom aides describe as a born conciliator, flew to Sirte
at some political risk, saying he wanted to try to break the
decade-long deadlock in the Lockerbie case by persuading Gadhafi to
send the two suspects to the Netherlands for a trial by Scottish
judges. This was a compromise proposed in August by the American
and British governments after the Libyans balked at a trial in
either country.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when Annan arrived at Sirte, he was left talking with
Libya's foreign minister, Omar al-Montasser, and Libya's permanent
representative at the United Nations, Abu Zeid Omar Dorda.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who detoured from a trip between Tunisia and a meeting of
Persian Gulf leaders in Abu Dhabi to go to Libya despite the
skepticism of diplomats and U.N. officials in New York, could have
met either lower-level Libyan official at the secretary-general's
U.N. office. His trip to Libya was premised on the chance of
meeting Gadhafi, although there was no assurance in advance that
the Libyan leader would show up.
</P>
<P>
   Pan Am 103 was blown up over the town of Lockerbie in Scotland
on Dec. 21, 1988, killing 270 people, including 11 on the ground.
An investigation by British and American law enforcement and
intelligence agencies concluded that two Libyan agents had planted
an explosive on the plane disguised as a radio-cassette player.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyans are also accused of plotting the explosion that
destroyed a French jetliner over Niger in 1989, killing 171 people.
That case is also unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi is eager to see the end of sanctions, imposed on Libya
in 1992 and toughened in 1993. These sanctions have barred
international air travel to and from Libya as well as the sale of
arms and spare parts for aviation and the oil industry on which the
Libyan economy depends. Libyan assets have been frozen abroad and
diplomatic representation has been limited.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had to apply to the Security Council's Libyan sanctions
committee on Thursday for permission to fly to Libya from the
Tunisian resort island of Djerba.
</P>
<P>
   An American diplomat who has been working on the Libya issue in
the Security Council said Thursday that the Clinton administration
saw Annan's trip as a way to ``advance the hand-over of the
suspects,'' and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect his travel to Libya to achieve that end,''
said the diplomat, Nancy Soderberg. Several diplomats said that
Annan had gone to Libya with no room for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States and Britain have gone the extra mile,'' Ms.
Soderberg said. ``Libya has been given every opportunity to comply
with the Security Council resolutions. It's been almost 10 years
since the Pan Am 103 tragedy and the families of the victims have
waited long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Annan's trip, which he planned in close consultation with
British and American officials, Libya had been sending mixed
signals about its intentions, as Gadhafi tried to set conditions on
the release of suspects to protect his intelligence network and his
political position, Arab diplomats said. One of the suspects
belongs to a clan in Libya that is, at best, lukewarm in its
support of the government.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jana, Gadhafi, who has ruled Libya since a 1969
coup, did not have the power to turn over the two men, Abdel Basset
al-Megrahi and Lamin Khalifah Fhimah. The agency said that the
Libyan people, through 500 ``popular committees,'' would have to
decide the fate of the two, who were indicted by Britain and the
United States in 1991. The move seemed to imply that Gadhafi wanted
political cover.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Libyan state radio reported that the General
People's Congress, Libya's top legislative and executive body, had
been summoned for Tuesday. The body usually endorses major policy
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the Libyan government had been saying that it objected
to the prospect that the suspects, if convicted, would have to
serve jail sentences in Scotland. British officials last week said
they had assured the Libyans that they could send diplomats to
Scotland to monitor the prison conditions and that all Islamic
strictures would be followed.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects are now under loose government supervision in
Libya. They are unable to travel abroad because their passports
have been confiscated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Western diplomats said here last week that Libya was also
concerned that the United States would not agree to a lifting of
sanctions if the two men were sent to the Netherlands for trial,
but would instead move the finish line to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   These diplomats seemed to confirm Libyan suspicions by saying
that the sanctions would be suspended when the suspects were in
custody, but that a final lifting of the embargo would not take
place until Libya had met other goals, like ending support for
terrorism. American allegations that Libya has been behind attacks
on Americans led to bombing raids on Libya in 1986. Some Arab
diplomats say the attack on Pan Am 103, if Libyans were
responsible, was more than likely retaliation for the American
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   British and American officials say there is no hidden agenda,
and that Security Council resolutions demand general cooperation
from Libya before sanctions can be permanently rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has seen its sanctions erode slightly over the last year,
after the Organization of African Unity decided to ignore the
flight ban for its heads of government.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League, to Libya's annoyance, has refused to take the
same decision. Arab League nations have pressed Libya to turn over
the suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
