<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBENEZER-SIDE06-COX     12-05 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBENEZER-SIDE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congregation moves out, tourists move in
 &HT;    By Jennifer Ffrench-Parker
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Ebenezer Baptist Church's congregation moves out
of its historic sanctuary in February, it will leave everything
behind.
</P>
<P>
   The pews will stay, as will the pulpit at which the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. and his father, the Rev. Martin Luther King Sr.
preached. So will the stained-glass windows with the names of the
church families who donated them.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen in time, the 750-seat church, will become a living
museum.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Park Service will assume a 99-year lease the day the
congregation moves out and will immediately begin weekday tours of
the building.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service operates the Visitors Center at the Martin
Luther King Jr. National Historic Site, authorized by Congress in
1980 to preserve the Auburn Avenue neighborhood where King was
born, spent his boyhood years, preached, and is buried.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service conducts tours of the birth home and is
negotiating with the King family to buy the King Center for
Non-Violent Change and the tomb of the slain civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catroppa, the Park Service's superintendent, said his
rangers will do interpretative tours of Ebenezer church, which was
founded in 1886, and will tell visitors about the Kings and the
role of the black church in the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   The church will stay open for tours, even during a planned
$987,000 renovation that will replace the roof and repair the bell
tower. The work will be done over two years starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Catroppa doesn't want Ebenezer's Heritage Sanctuary to be
just a museum.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Park Service plans to keep the church open for
periodic ecumenical services and perhaps a monthly ``Sing at
Ebenezer'' program where choirs from different churches could
perform in the historic sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ebenezer is one of the most important churches _ period,''
said Catroppa. ``We don't want it be a museum. We are trying to
give it some life.''
</P>
<P>
   He would also like for the annual King Holiday service to
continue at the historic church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be appropriate,'' Catroppa said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer's senior pastor, the Rev. Joseph Roberts Jr., said the
church's offices will remain in the building until the second phase
of its $11 million construction program _ a social services
building _ is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The church's new sanctuary, built at a cost of $8 million, will
be dedicated March 21. A $3 million social services building is
planned just as soon as the church raises enough money to start
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said members can have having weddings and funerals in
the historic sanctuary, if they desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not giving up the old church,'' Roberts said. ``It's
just across the street and we can always walk over.''
</P>
<P>
   THROUGH THE YEARS
</P>
<P>
   In its 113 years, Ebenezer has had four senior pastors:
</P>
<P>
   _ 1886-1894: John Parker, founder
</P>
<P>
   _ 1894-1931: Adam Daniel Williams, father-in-law of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Sr.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1931-1975: The Rev. Martin Luther King Sr.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1975: The Rev. Joseph Roberts
</P>
<P>
   NOTABLE DATES:
</P>
<P>
   _ 1947: The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. ordained at Ebenezer.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1960: King Jr. becomes associate pastor at Ebenezer, sharing
duties with his father.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1968: The funeral of King Jr. was held at the church.
</P>
<P>
   _ June, 1974: Alberta Williams King, wife of King Sr. and mother
of King Jr., gunned down at Ebenezer while playing the organ at
Sunday services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
