<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBENEZER06-COX     12-05 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBENEZER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ebenezer Baptist prepares for big move
 &HT;    WITH EBENEZER-SIDE
 &HT;    By Jennifer Ffrench-Parker
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Atlanta church with deep historical roots is in its
last holiday season at its old homeplace.
</P>
<P>
   In about three months, the congregation of the Ebenezer Baptist
Church will move to a new sanctuary across Auburn Avenue to a new
$8 million facility.
</P>
<P>
   The move has been 10 years in the making for the church that
nurtured the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and was the spiritual
cradle of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brown, a member for more than 40 years, said he is a
little sad about leaving the old church, but that his excitement is
mounting as the congregation gets closer to relocating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a warm family place to grow up,'' said Brown, who went
to Ebenezer as a boy with his parents. ``All the members looked out
for you. You heard of `it takes a village to raise a child'? It
really was like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the church's board of trustees, Brown has been
overseeing the construction of the new sanctuary and has watched
the new building take shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving from the old to the new,'' he said. ``Yes, there
are some mixed feelings. But, on the other hand, if you don't
change, you will become stagnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction on Ebenezer's Horizon Sanctuary, the new church's
name, began in March 1997, and is scheduled for completion by
year's end. The installation of pews and other interior work should
begin in January.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joseph Roberts, senior pastor for 23 years, expects the
first service to be held sometime in February.
</P>
<P>
   The only firm date for now is the dedication service for the
sanctuary, set for March 21, which coincides with the church's
113th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is excited about finally having a place large enough to
accommodate all the people drawn to the church by its rich history
and its connection to the King family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents for me progression,'' he said. ``It's a place
where we might be more useful in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic church, built in 1913 and 1922, was the home church
of the young Martin, whose father, Martin Sr., was pastor from
1931-1975. Martin Jr. was co-pastor with his father from 1960-68.
</P>
<P>
   Built to seat 750 people, the sanctuary annually hosts about
750,000 visitors a year for services.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said there was always a problem finding seats and
parking for everyone, even with two services. That won't be an
immediate problem in the new church, which will seat 1,750.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we will be able to invite people in,'' said Roberts, who
in 1975 took over a 1,000-member church with a budget of $150,000.
Today, the church's budget is $1.6 million and membership has more
than doubled to 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The new church, which is being built by Russell-Beers
Construction, has a strong Afrocentric theme.
</P>
<P>
   It is circular, a design influenced by an African hut. Its eight
stained-glass windows, which will be installed after the
congregation moves in, will depict the story of King and the civil
rights movement. The church calls them ``teaching windows.'' Brown
said the pews will have African and Christian symbols etched into
them.
</P>
<P>
   With the completion of the Horizon sanctuary, the church plans
to launch fund-raising to build a $3 million community service
center that will house church offices and 30 social services
ministries including a food co-op, a medical center and its soup
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   For church secretary Beverly Miles, it won't be too painful to
make the move from the old to the new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually it will be quite easy,'' laughed Miles, who joined
the church in 1979 and has been secretary since 1993. ``The new
place has such a very cozy feel to it, it won't be a problem for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And if she gets nostalgic for the Heritage Sanctuary, as the
historic church is now known, she won't have far to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will just walk across the street,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
