<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES06-COX     12-05 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves stronger all around
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This has been no mere service call. If the Atlanta
Braves were a house, the furniture would have been rearranged in
every room.
</P>
<P>
   In the $700 million thrown around the majors during this
free-agent season, others have spent plenty more and bigger names
have moved. But no club has done what the Braves have done,
reworking every clubhouse aspect from the coaching staff to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Denny Neagle removes a tooth from the rotation,
but everywhere else the Braves have become stronger. Bret Boone
tightens the infield defensively and lends offensive pop at second
base unseen since Davey Johnson passed through town. Brian Jordan
and Otis Nixon elevate the outfield. Questions might exist about
rookie left-hander Bruce Chen's readiness for the majors or the
absence of a big-name closer, but the pitching staff probably has
never been deeper.
</P>
<P>
   All of that on a club coming off a team-record 106-win season.
General manager John Schuerholz, asked if he is finished with the
roster, replied that he isn't. ``I'm not going to paint myself into
any corners.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Braves have an existing budget problem. With 18
players now under contract for 1999, the payroll already has
reached $72.7 million. The club has targeted a $65 million to $68
million budget, meaning that something must give. Left fielder Ryan
Klesko, who will earn $4.75 million next season and another $12.25
million before his contract expires in 2001, remains the prime
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the team has a deep interest in how
Klesko, whose season unraveled after a June appendectomy, might
profit from working with new hitting coach Don Baylor. Nixon could
well be batting leadoff and playing left field on opening day, but
what if Klesko becomes a new man in spring training? Another
option.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, a Braves team that last season scored more runs and
fielded more cleanly than any in franchise history has made itself
better. If 1998 taught the team anything, merely being better can
become meaningless come October. However, criticisms that the
Braves are too pitching-heavy, that they lack depth, that they have
limited offensive resources beyond the home run are far less valid
than the night the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   Infield
</P>
<P>
   Boone becomes the first Gold Glove second baseman to wear an
Atlanta uniform since Felix Millan in 1972. He comes off a 24-homer
season. Johnson and Rogers Hornsby are the only previous Braves
second basemen to reach 20. Retaining Ozzie Guillen was critical
for Walt Weiss' legs at shortstop, where the team might not be
acrobatic but remains solid. Corner men Chipper Jones and Andres
Galarraga generated 228 RBIs, the most by any third base/first base
combination in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Outfield
</P>
<P>
   Jordan changes the dynamic in right field, where Michael
Tucker's spotty offense had become a liability. Jordan hit .351
against left-handed pitching last year and can bat almost anywhere
in the order, and his strong arm will be put to good use in one of
the deepest right fields in the majors. Durability remains the only
question. Andruw Jones improved by the month last summer and
deservedly won a Gold Glove in just his first season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Rotation
</P>
<P>
   Chen, at 21 only two months older than Andruw Jones, is destined
for some rough treatment, on his way to the majors after throwing
just 24 innings at the Class AAA level. Kevin Millwood also allowed
more hits (175) than innings pitched (174.1) last year. But the
thinking to deal Neagle was sound for three reasons: Glavine,
Maddux and Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen
</P>
<P>
   Braves relievers had a 3.83 ERA last year, fifth-best in the
National League, but the core that evolved from that group _ Kerry
Ligtenberg, John Rocker and Rudy Seanez _ had a 2.57 ERA with 171
strikeouts in 147 innings. Five pitchers are up for the remaining
three spots: newcomer Mike Remlinger; Odalis Perez; Russ Springer;
Mark Wohlers, who is intent on a comeback; and Mike Cather, coming
off corrective rib surgery. For the first time, the Braves could
have three lefties in the bullpen, Remlinger, Perez and Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Bench
</P>
<P>
   Nixon and Gerald Williams, a pleasant surprise last year, would
be starting for a host of teams, but here merely fill out the
outfield. Eddie Perez, coming off a .336 season, has been tied down
with a two-year contract to back up two-time All-Star catcher Javy
Lopez. Guillen and Keith Lockhart, coming off rotator cuff surgery,
are slotted for the infield reserve slots, meaning an end of the
line for Tony Graffanino.
</P>
<P>
   It all means that the Braves head to spring training with only
the 25th spot on the roster unfilled. When spring training
convenes, only nine Braves will remain from the franchise's last
World Series appearance three short seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   1999 BRAVES PAYROLL
</P>
