<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-DETENTION-CENTE     12-05 1925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-DETENTION-CENTER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youth detention centers face day in court
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALTON, Ga. _ J.A.S. was 13 years old the first time he was sent
to the state's regional youth detention center here, charged with
simple battery and forgery. He had gotten into a fight with his
father and written a $100 check on his parents' account.
</P>
<P>
   What he found at the center, a one-story building on the eastern
edge of this city known for its carpet mills, ``was pretty
frightening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The single-person cells sometimes had as many as five boys
stuffed into them. Often, no more than two guards oversaw the 60 or
more youngsters in a facility built to house 30. He says he was
among those subjected to outdoor mass strip searches and that he
witnessed physical abuse of other youths.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, the tall, muscular youth was sent to
the Dalton RYDC four more times, usually for relatively minor
offenses such as simple assault and probation violation. The
conditions never changed, he said in a recent interview. The
facility was continually overcrowded and understaffed. Education
and health care were virtually nonexistent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   J.A.S., now 18, is one of five ``named'' plaintiffs, identified
only by initials because of their age, in a class action lawsuit
against the state Department of Juvenile Justice and the Dalton
RYDC that goes to trial Monday in U.S. District Court in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that the facility, which serves nine counties
in northwest Georgia, is ``grossly overcrowded, unsanitary and
dilapidated'' and violates the constitutional rights of every youth
locked up there.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the suit believe a favorable federal court ruling
will force the department to improve conditions not only at Dalton,
but in the 20 other regional detention centers throughout the
state. Advocates for children have long maintained there are
systemwide problems, but have been unable to document them because
of confidentiality restrictions involving juvenile offenders. A
Department of Justice investigation conducted in 1997-98 was the
first time the entire system had been closely examined by an
outside agency.
</P>
<P>
   The federal report on that investigation, released this year,
was highly critical of the entire system, citing ``a pattern of
egregious conditions violating the federal rights of youths'' at
Georgia juvenile facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation found the department had violated the
constitutional rights of children by confining them in a system
that was abusive, dangerous and overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   The state agreed to spend $65 million for improvements over the
next 2 1/2 years and to allow federal monitors to supervise its
progress.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the class action lawsuit want the court to go
farther and require the state to make specific improvements in
areas such as health care, mental health screening and treatment,
education and protection of the incarcerated youths. They believe
only a court verdict will ensure that changes are made.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Boardman Burnette, an attorney in the Atlanta firm of
Cullen &AMP; Miller, which is handling the case for the plaintiffs,
said the suit is seeking ``something with teeth; something that is
enforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The state can make promises (to improve conditions) until it
is blue in the face,'' she said, ``but we want something so if they
don't follow up the court can step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the youths say they plan to present graphic
testimony from J.A.S. and three other plaintiffs who have been
confined at the Dalton RYDC. Among them is C.N.H., who was 15 when
the suit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, C.N.H. came from a family with a
history of mental illness. She was sexually abused as a child and
had a history of drug and alcohol abuse. The suit alleges that
C.N.H. was not given any psychological screening when she was
admitted to the RYDC. It also claims that during another
confinement at the facility, she suffered from pneumonia but had to
wait two weeks to get treatment, and later suffered severe
nosebleeds but never saw a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   J.A.S. also said he never saw a doctor at the Dalton RYDC. Even
getting to see a nurse required patience. ``You had to put in a
request one day and you might get to see her the next day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Education at the center usually consisted of ``two videos and a
sixth-grade math book,'' J.A.S. said. ``And they were always the
same videos: one about drugs and the other some nature video.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials would not comment on specific allegations in the
Dalton RYDC suit. But David Anderson Hooker, who defended the
state's juvenile justice system when he was with the attorney
general's office, said conditions in Dalton ``were not generally
bad. For a lot of reasons, Dalton was one of the better-managed
facilities and better-maintained facilities in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   When the suit was filed in March 1996, the Dalton center was the
only RYDC in the state accredited by the American Correctional
Association for meeting minimum standards for incarceration and
treatment of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations of those backing the suit are unrealistic, said
Hooker, who will be the lead defense attorney for the state,
although he now is in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between being constitutionally adequate
and what is ideal,'' he said. ``Those financing the case have gone
beyond constitutionally adequate to trying to reach what is
ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit's long road to trial has been unusual for a class
action suit. Instead of being pushed and financed by a nonprofit
public interest group with minimal local ties, as is generally the
case, the money and zeal for this suit come largely from business
and political leaders in Dalton and surrounding Whitfield County.
Many of them are closely linked to the Dalton RYDC and the juvenile
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Maples Blaylock, a Juvenile Court judge in Whitfield
County and a member of the Dalton RYDC advisory board, served as a
court-appointed guardian for C.N.H. in the girl's dealings with the
court. Blaylock declined to comment about the suit for this story,
citing ethical concerns.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suit's major backers is Debby Peppers, a former
Whitfield County commissioner and one-time member of the Dalton
RYDC advisory board. Peppers also has done charity work for the
Juvenile Court and served as a court-appointed guardian for
children in their dealings with the court. She said it was during
the year she spent on the center's advisory board in 1990 that she
first heard stories about problems at Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what the attitude was up there and how they were doing
things,'' Peppers said. But it was not until she began talking to
other advocates for children that she said she realized the extent
of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Peppers said she heard about children not being able to get
their medication on a regular basis while confined. She also heard
allegations about lack of schooling, frequent physical abuse and
group punishment for infraction of rules. On occasion, she said,
the complaints came from people who worked at the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people had a little knowledge about what was going
on,'' said J. Thomas Minor IV, a Dalton real estate attorney and
children's advocate. ``As we got together and talked about it, we
saw that it was a much bigger problem.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30 members of the community decided to form a political
action committee rather than a nonprofit group so they could
support candidates and initiatives they believed were responsive to
the needs of children, Minor said. The PAC, known as Voice of the
Children, has been the driving force behind the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Minor and Peppers said PAC members believed a class action
lawsuit would push the state into making some quick changes, first
at the Dalton RYDC and then in other facilities around the state.
</P>
<P>
   RYDCs are designed as short-term detention facilities for
juveniles awaiting court hearings or transfer to long-term
detention centers. But some youngsters have been detained at the
Dalton RYDC for up to 18 months; and those incarcerated in RYDCs
can include juveniles awaiting hearings in superior court for
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Voice of the Children members thought the suit would be settled
within a year, Minor said. Instead, it has gone on for more than 2
1/2 years, and expenses now exceed $50,000. Lawyers handling the
case have not billed the PAC for their fees but are seeking
reimbursement from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Peppers and Minor said the suit has produced some cosmetic
changes at the facility, such as new uniforms for the boys and a
new paint job inside the building, but not the long-term, major
improvements it is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker and state officials say improvements have been made, and
have nothing to do with the litigation. Those changes were in the
works before the suit, and before the Department of Justice
investigation and subsequent memorandum of agreement between
federal officials and the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memorandum of agreement really reflects an acceleration of
plans that had already been developed,'' Hooker said.
</P>
<P>
   Shrouded by trees on three sides, the low-slung Dalton RYDC
building has the same utilitarian, cement block and brick-and-tile
hardness as most detention facilities. The 8-by-10 cells are
intended for one person. Each has a built-in cement slab for
bedding, an open, stainless-steel toilet and sink, and recessed
light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Youths here range in age from 11 to 17. Boys wear dark green
uniforms; the girls, green and white stripes. The boys' wing, which
was built to house 22, is separated from the girls' wing by several
locked steel doors, the dining area, and a classroom jammed with
books and computers. A portion of the dining area has been
appropriated for a temporary classroom until a new one is built.
</P>
<P>
   A psychologist has provided individual counseling every Friday
for about a year, according to Bobby Hughes, interim director of
the Dalton RYDC. A licensed clinical social worker has counseled
youths two days a week for almost a year. Drug and alcohol
counseling sessions are now offered once a week. The center has had
a full-time nurse for about three years, and a doctor visits every
Thursday. A full-time psychological nurse is expected to be hired
by July. And, although it's still over capacity, the average daily
population last year was under 50, according to Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with 50 kids, it's still manageable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The center also is trying to incorporate vocational training,
using a greenhouse donated by local Girl Scouts and businesses. A
pet therapy program is in the works, as is increased time for
inmates on the center's computers, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep the kids out of their rooms and keep them busy,''
Hughes said. ``That's why we don't have a lot of incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker said he believes ``the state should be admonished to
always try to improve the services they are providing. But as long
as they are operating above the standards provided by the
Constitution and state regulations, that admonishment should come
in the form of advocacy, not a federal lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peppers said she believes there are still serious problems
at the facility _ and Voice of the Children will fight on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't quit,'' she said. ``Who else will speak for these
children?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
