<DOCNO> NYT19981205.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURDUCKEN06-COX     12-05 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURDUCKEN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The stuff Thanksgiving is made of in Cajun country tasty times
three
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ For anyone who thinks Louisiana is a part of the
United States, here's some evidence to the contrary:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mardi Gras is an official state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't buy groceries; you ``make'' them. As in, ``So I was
makin' groceries at Schwegmann's last week ...''
</P>
<P>
   _ The accordian is cool here.
</P>
<P>
   But as a recent emigre to New Orleans from Atlanta, I find
nothing more foreign than the holiday dish Louisianans call
turducken. While the rest of America eats a regular roast turkey at
Thanksgiving and Christmas, here in the land of, ``There's no such
thing as too rich or too much,'' they eat their turkey stuffed with
a duck, which is in turn stuffed with a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Tur(key)-Duck-(Chick)en. Get it?
</P>
<P>
   I discovered this three-in-one oddity a few months ago, after
living here less than a year. I was making plans to host my first
Thanksgiving for my family _ I am a newlywed with a new house, so I
convinced everyone to come down from New York City for turkey on
the Bayou.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the meal had to incorporate Louisiana cooking, and it had
to be very authentic and local. My family _ particularly my mother
and brother _ is insatiable in its desire to do as the Romans when
in Rome (Mom wore a sari while in India and my brother is not
unfamiliar with the worm at the bottom of a tequila bottle). Using
family recipes and simply transporting traditions from Mom's house
to mine would not do.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention my new mother-in-law also would be coming? Not
only did my meal have to be authentic, it had to be delicious and
well-executed. Sure, Matt's mom is terribly sweet and
nonjudgemental, but come on, it's my mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   First, I explored the deep-fried turkey option. This is where a
turkey is injected with spices and then dunked in hot oil and fried
crispy. I asked around to find out who made good ones. There is no
such thing as a Louisianan who can't cook or who doesn't have an
opinion on who makes what the best. Fights have been known to break
out among men on oil rigs and in fishing camps over which of them
makes the best crawfish etouffee or chicken gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   A cab driver taking me to the airport one morning pointed to an
oily-looking tire ``shop'' and promised that come November a woman
would set up a sign next to a pile of whitewalls and start selling
the best deep-fried turkeys in town. Other people swore by
Popeye's; the fried chicken chain deep-fries turkeys on special
order around the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   But a reheated deep-fried turkey? That sounded like reheated
french fries. So I looked into making one. I went on the Internet
and found a Web site with step-by-step instructions. It was simple
enough, as long as you had a stainless steel pot big enough to fit
a small child, a propane tank, an aesbestos suit and a yard made of
concrete. Apparently, many houses burn to the ground in New Orleans
when novices try to deep-fry turkeys in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   A new tradition
</P>
<P>
   I looked at the wooden deck that surrounds our wooden,
120-year-old house, and thought of how much my brother and husband
like to ``bond'' (Read: Drink) when they get together, and decided
a deep-fried turkey was not for us.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the word ``turducken'' entered my vocabulary. Unlike
the deep-fried turkey, which is fairly well-known around the
country, no one I talked to outside of Louisiana had heard of this
three-bird culinary feat.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, you can buy it all trussed up and ready to go, but you
cook it yourself, which means it would taste fresher than the
fried-ahead bird. And it cooks in the oven, not in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   I drove over the Mississippi River to Gretna, a suburb on the
West Bank, to a place I'd heard was famous for turduckens. Before I
even got inside the Gourmet Butcher Block, I was wrapped in the
smells of green onions, sausage and Cajun spices.
</P>
<P>
   Owners Glenn and Leah Mistich, both Cajun country natives, are
the king and queen of the New Orleans turducken market. They
debone, stuff and sew up 6,000 turkeys each year, mostly in
November and December. They've sent them to homesick Louisianans in
every state and as far away as South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Leah's family claims to have invented the turducken about 15
years ago. She says a customer came into her family's butcher shop
in Maurice, La. and asked what he could do with a wild duck he'd
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Prudhomme, patriarch of Louisiana cooking, lays some claim
to the dish as well.
</P>
<P>
   All I know is you can buy them at several shops around Louisiana
or even order one off the Internet, so let's just say it's in the
public domain.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble a turducken, Glenn Mistich starts by laying out a
limp turkey, deboned save for the legs and wings. He sprinkles it
with spices and spreads scoops of homemade sausage dressing all
over the cavity. Next he lays on a boneless duck, spices it, and
spoons in more dressing. Finally comes the floppy chicken, more
spices and more dressing _ this time, a traditional cornbread type.
He rolls the birds one over the other, and then deftly stitches up
the turkey. All I had to do was take it home and cook it for
several hours. I was sold.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Before I placed an order, I e-mailed a local food expert, Tom
Fitzmorris, and asked him what he thought of turduckens and where
was the best place to get one. He wrote back and asked ominously:
Why would you want one?
</P>
<P>
   ``The turducken is a gross Cajun exaggeration on an ancient
French dish called a ballotine, in which a chicken is stuffed with
a quail, which is then stuffed with an even smaller wild bird,'' he
wrote. ``My problem with (the turducken) is that it all becomes a
hodgepodge, usually tasting more like stuffing than any kind of
bird. You can eat all of my share.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I chickened out. I compromised and went to my local
grocer, Langenstein's, a place I trust completely, and asked if
they made a turducken. They do, but they stuff the turkey with just
one kind of dressing and with a duck and chicken breast, not the
whole birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cooks better that way,'' the lady behind the counter said.
I decided this was a turducken I could trust for my first
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, I pulled a perfectly browned turducken out of
the oven. Somehow it had survived four hours of repeated stabs with
the meat thermometer and a near-death-by-drowning from my manic
basting. My stepfather, following Langenstein's instructions,
removed the legs and wings and carved straight across the bird's
deboned breast like it was a leg of lamb. Inside was succulent,
white turkey meat. Hiding sort of at the bottom was a thin layer of
rich, moist duck breast and an even thinner layer of oyster
dressing. The chicken was nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   It may not have been the triple delight we were all hoping for,
but it was, by all accounts, delicious.
</P>
<P>
   I think my mom summed it up best: ``I don't know where the
stuffing was, or the chicken, but the duck and the turkey were
delicious, fabulous. I am having one sent to New York next year.''
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I am ready to graduate to the real thing: My next
turducken is going to come from Glenn and Leah Mistich. I'll let
you know next year how it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Turducken Web site:
http://www.gumbopages.com/food/poultry/turducken.html
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark is a regional reporter for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution based in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
