A4710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH06-COX     12-05 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Committee to consider impeachment articles
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Few members of Congress have disputed that
President Clinton lied about his sexual affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky, the question is what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   That question will be put to the test this week when the House
Judiciary Committee weighs articles of impeachment against
President Clinton for the way he concealed his relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   For only the third time in the nation's history, the committee
will debate articles of impeachment against a president. In this
case, the articles will allege that Clinton committed perjury,
obstructed justice and abused his presidential powers.
</P>
<P>
   The historic debate unfolds this week with Republicans
portraying the president as a liar not fit for office and Democrats
attacking the GOP as the party that would stop at nothing to remove
the president.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom of law, the case about the president would be
clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   Did or did he not lie under oath about having a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   But in the courtroom of politics, mitigating factors such as
what is best for the country will make the outcome less certain.
Which side wins this battle of wills has yet to be seen. What is
certain is both political parties are engaged in a public relations
war to win the public over.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their obsession to remove the president from office, House
Republicans are willing to close their eyes to the clear wishes of
almost three-quarters of the American public, which does not want
to remove the president over a consensual affair,'' said Jim
Jordan, spokesperson for the Democratic committee members.
</P>
<P>
   ``House Republicans are moving concertedly toward a several
month trial in the Senate, which would paralyze all three branches
of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde said Friday that he is
tired of the way the White House and committee Democrats are
twisting the facts in the case against Clinton. Hyde said he wanted
to assure the public and the Democrats that the GOP would not be
``intimidated by rhetoric or name-calling, and we will complete our
duty in accordance with the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House press agents have dramatically stepped up
their attacks on the House Judiciary Committee just as it prepares
to begin deliberations on articles of impeachment,'' Hyde said.
``This is certainly unfortunate, but it sadly comes as no surprise.
From the very beginning of the impeachment inquiry, those who would
defend the President at all costs have preferred to attack the
process rather than address the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The week kicks off with Republicans meeting with committee
staffers on Monday to approve drafts of articles of impeachment
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is expected to present ``a vigorous defense'' of
the president starting on Tuesday. The defense is expected to be a
highly-charged condemnation of the tactics used by Republicans and
independent counsel Kenneth Starr to remove the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The White House lawyers will attempt to prove that the president
did not commit perjury in the legal sense of the word, but rather
misled the American people in an effort to protect his family and
the public from finding out about his affair.
</P>
<P>
   When the White House finishes, Abbe Lowell, the Democratic
counsel on the committee, will present his findings and closing
remarks. David Schippers, the chief counsel to committee
Republicans, will present his findings after that.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on articles of impeachment are expected to begin
Thursday. The committee will likely approve articles of impeachment
on a party-line vote. Given the 21 to 16 Republican majority on the
panel, Democrats will not be able to do much to stop that.
</P>
<P>
   If articles of impeachment pass the committee, the attention
turns to Georgia Republican Newt Gingrich. As the outgoing Speaker
of the House, Gingrich will call House members back to Capitol Hill
for a vote on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In the current Congress, which expires Jan. 3, House Republicans
outnumber Democrats 228-206. There is also one independent who
usually votes with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   At least three Democrats are expected to vote for impeachment:
Virgil Goode of Virginia; Ralph Hall of Texas; and Gene Taylor of
Mississippi. Hall was one of four Texas Democrats to support
opening the impeachment inquiry. The other three are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   A simple majority _ 218 votes _ is enough to impeach Clinton,
creating the spectacle of a Senate trial. If the House passes
articles of impeachment, the Senate will be forced to hold a trial.
Under the rules of the Senate, that trial would begin at 1 p.m. the
day after the articles are delivered and continue in session until
a decision is rendered. Chief Justice William Rehnquist would
preside.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) gave a strong
hint about what he thinks about that prospect, telling reporters on
Thursday that ``We're not making any plans or preparations at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   House members say the House vote is too close to call. They say
that perjury will probably be the only article of impeachment that
stands a chance of passage. The likely alternative to impeachment
is censure.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King (R-N.Y.) continued his quest to win Republican
support for a censure resolution that would condemn and fine
Clinton for his actions. But Republicans were reluctant to put
their names on the line by publicly endorsing the proposal, which
was strongly opposed by Majority Whip Tom Delay (R-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
