<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TOOK WEEKS, BUT WINNER GETS A PARTY  
 NO CONCESSION YET FROM OPPONENT  
 MAKING IT ONTO THE BALLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would be more than 10 days before the
certification of a winner in the race for state attorney general.
But that did not stop nearly 2,000 supporters of Eliot Spitzer from
gathering at the Waldorf-Astoria last week for a ``victory party.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, the outcome of the Nov. 3 contest was far from clear.
On election night, Spitzer, the Democratic challenger, emerged with
a lead of 18,000 votes over the Republican incumbent, Dennis Vacco.
But with more than 200,000 paper ballots to tally _ and court
challenges by Vacco _ the final count was delayed for weeks.
Spitzer's lead continued to hold and, two weeks ago, the Democratic
candidate declared victory at a small news conference.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly all the paper ballots now counted, Spitzer's lead
has grown, leaving him with roughly 24,500 votes more than Vacco,
out of more than 4 million votes cast. The state Board of Elections
will make its report on the vote at a state Supreme Court hearing
on Monday and will certify the results the following week.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, supporters of Spitzer harbored no doubts about the
election's outcome. And the party, with its red, white and blue
balloons, was a dramatic contrast to the sober news conference
where Spitzer declared victory, having instead the feel of a
rousing valedictory.
</P>
<P>
   It also seemed to draw the firmament of Democratic political
power in New York, attracting virtually every prominent party
figure, from former Mayors Edward Koch and David Dinkins to
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, Senator-elect Charles Schumer and
City Council Speaker Peter Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Attorney General Robert Abrams stood beside
Geraldine Ferraro, his opponent in a Senate race six years ago. And
state Sen. Catherine Abate, one of Spitzer's opponents during the
Democratic primary, also stood nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a come-from-behind victory,'' Spitzer shouted to the
cheering audience. ``This has been one long, tough month.''
</P>
<P>
   But Still No Concession
</P>
<P>
   While the Spitzer supporters were celebrating, lawyers for Vacco
continued to pore over voting records in the offices of the Board
of Elections in New York City last week. Although the board's
figures show Spitzer's lead has grown, Vacco _ far from conceding _
has dedicated himself to determining whether there was a sufficient
level of voter fraud to serve as grounds for a federal suit to seek
a new election.
</P>
<P>
   The Vacco campaign, which has made claims in state Supreme Court
of voting irregularities, declined to discuss any such findings in
court last Monday and has not discussed the matter in much detail
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reviewing data and checking lists against other lists,''
said Thomas Spargo, the lawyer for Vacco's campaign. ``We've found
a pattern of some registrations that are highly questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Spargo said, the campaign found ``a large number''
of people registered in a single apartment. ``We've found some
patterns that are extraordinary,'' he said. ``We're sifting through
and trying to make a determination about what to do with our
findings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, Vacco's lawyers have made several charges
of election irregularities. They first said that 37,000 votes had
appeared without explanation after the unofficial Election Day
tally. Later, they said they had found a 7,000-vote error in the
results in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Spargo said that the Vacco campaign had obtained
material indicating that 1,000 people had voted in the names of
people for whom death benefits were being paid by the Social
Security Administration. But the campaign later backed off that
claim and has not produced any names in court.
</P>
<P>
   With each charge, the Vacco campaign asked the court for
additional time to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   What the campaign would do with its findings about registration
irregularities was not clear, although Spargo said the campaign
would have to make a decision soon. The campaign dispatched dozens
of lawyers and other representatives last week to election offices
in each of the city's boroughs _ except Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Spargo said that Staten Island, the city's least populous
borough, was not included, because ``there were not as large a
number of votes as in other boroughs.'' But it also happens to be
the only borough that Vacco won.
</P>
<P>
   Making It Onto the Ballot
</P>
<P>
   The State Board of Elections also said last week that the
Working Families Party appeared to have drawn enough votes to earn
a place on the ballot in the next statewide election.
</P>
<P>
   The party represents an alliance of labor unions, politicians
and the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now, or
ACORN, an advocacy group with low-income members. It won that
status by obtaining more than 50,000 votes on its line in the Nov.
3 election for Vallone, who was also the Democratic candidate for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   The board said the party received about 50,600 votes on its
line. The party, which is seeking to appeal to union members and
immigrants as well as middle-class and working-poor New Yorkers,
was also supported by former Mayor David Dinkins, and two mayoral
candidates from last year: Ruth Messinger and Sal Albanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will focus on issues that affect working-class families and
run campaigns around those issues,'' he said, saying that the party
would concentrate on raising the minimum wage, increased access to
health care and campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that a progressive agenda is not ignored
in Albany, the City Council and the county legislatures across the
state,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
