<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECTIONS _ TAIPEI, Taiwan _ For weeks, Chinese leaders
have fidgeted just over the horizon as democratic Taiwan neared
bellwether elections that would test whether Taiwanese are aching
for full independence from the Chinese mainland. On Saturday, to
the relief of Beijing and likely Washington as well, millions of
Taiwanese delivered a loud mandate for caution. With a turnout of
over 67 percent, the voters signaled in mayoral and parliamentary
results that they don't want to risk confronting China's threat to
``use force'' in case Taiwan declares independence.
(Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service 750) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-HIDE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ How is it possible for wanted
killer James Lawson or any fugitive to evade police for three
months? He assumed a new name, got a new job and moved in with a
new girlfriend. If you want to get away, is it that simple? We talk
with police in Butler and Warren counties, highway patrol about the
ways people can hide and what it takes for the cops to find them.
(Tresslar, Keilman, Budd, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TURDUCKEN _ NEW ORLEANS _ Postcard from New Orleans about this
holiday delicacy called ''turducken'' _ it's a duck inside of a
chicken inside of a turkey. No one outside of Louisiana has ever
heard of this thing, apparently some bastardization of a French
dish. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CIGARETTE-ADS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Cinema,'' a two-minute
trailer for a thriller about a killer epidemic that wipes out a
population the size of Manhattan, may be getting the anti-smoking
message across to teens. Apparently it has passed the cool test.
(Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EBENEZER _ ATLANTA _ The congregation of the Historic Ebenezer
Church is getting ready to move into its new $8-million-dollar
sanctuary across the street. When they leave the old building, the
U.S Park Service assumes a 99-year lease of the building. It plans
a $900,000 renovation of the building and will begin offering tours
of the church immediately. (Ffrench-Parker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/EBENEZER-SIDE _ ATLANTA _ The U.S. Park Service plans nearly a
million dollars in renovations to the historic Ebenezer Baptist
Church that it will take a 99-year-lease on when the congregation
moves across the street to a new $8 million home. (Ffrench-Parker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-DETENTION-CENTER _ DALTON, Ga. _ J.A.S. was 13 years old
the first time he was sent to the Regional Youth Detention Center.
He says the single-person cells sometimes held as many as five
boys; that there were too few staff members; and that the center
was at often more than double its capacity of 30. There were
outdoor mass strip searches and frequent rumors of physical and
sexual assaults. Over the next five years, J.A.S. would be sent to
the facility four more times for minor offenses. The condition of
the RYDC never changed, he said. Now, J.A.S. is one of the
plaintiffs in a federal class-action suit against the state
Department of Juvenile Justice and the Dalton RYDC that goes to
trial Monday in Rome, Ga. The suit charges that the facility is
``grossly overcrowded, unsanitary and dilapidated.'' (Martz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RALLY _ WASHINGTON _ A ``soccer mom'' from Ohio, a
Louisiana small business owner, and a nurse from Georgia were among
those who rallied at the U.S. Capitol Saturday to challenge the
notion that Americans are bored by presidential scandal. Summoned
only by a message on a pro-impeachment Internet site, they are
among the minority that has been spurred into activism by the
Clinton controversy. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., a stalwart for
impeachment, told the gathering that the nation is at a crossroads.
(Malone, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
