<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RALLY05-COX-2NDLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RALLY AT CAPITOL URGES IMPEACHMENT
 &HT;    Eds: Retops with anecdotal lede.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Doloras(cq) Post sat on a stone ledge near the U.S.
Capitol on Saturday, holding a poster that she and her husband of
57 years had made. ``Impeach, Impeach, Impeach,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-written sign wasn't very professional-looking, but then
this was the first political protest that the couple, who live in
Falls Church, Va., had ever attended.
</P>
<P>
   Other Americans may say they are bored by national scandal, but
not an impassioned group who rallied at the U.S. Capitol on
Saturday for the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They cheered as Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., perhaps the leading
supporter of impeaching Clinton, told them to stiffen the spines of
wavering Republicans looking for a way out of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two weeks will determine the future of Americans,
make no mistake about it,'' Barr said. Clinton's attorneys are
scheduled to begin presenting his defense to the House Judiciary
Committee on Tuesday, with a vote on sending articles of
impeachment to the floor possible by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the real Americans _ you _ want a constitutional
strategy, not an exit strategy,'' Barr said to the gathering of
several hundred people who traveled here on a few days' notice
after the event was announced by Free Republic, an Internet site
(http://www.FreeRepublic.com). In the past two years, the site has
developed into a cyberspace meeting place for Clinton critics.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was dotted with protest signs such as ``It's the
perjury stupid!'' and ``Impeach the Creep.'' A Jack Russell terrier
wore a sign reading ``Impeach Buddy,'' the president's dog.
</P>
<P>
   However, on this unseasonably balmy day, it was a self-described
``soccer mom,'' Jennifer McCorkel of Chillicothe, Ohio, who most
energized the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkel, a mother of three, said she had been spurred into
action by polls that gave Clinton 69 percent approval ratings
despite his admitted affair with a White House intern and his
misleading statements. For the first time ever, she said, she
became a political activist, setting up a rally in her hometown and
later in the Ohio capital of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an American citizen who understands the elementary civics
lessons that my fourth-grade teacher taught me, that nobody is
above the law,'' McCorkel said. She called herself ``completely
astounded and disgusted'' at polls that show a majority of women
continue to support Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkel was one of several people at the rally who said they
were new to protests and politics but have been drawn into action
by the Clinton scandal and the Internet site, started by Fresno,
Calif., software developer Jim Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The site made an activist out of Sheila Lee. Lee, who with her
husband owns a local magazine in Covington, La., said she regretted
missing a Free Republic rally on Halloween that attracted several
thousand people near the Washington monument.
</P>
<P>
   So for Saturday's rally, Lee drove 25 hours to spend her 55th
birthday at the Capitol rally.
</P>
<P>
   Another newcomer to politics, Michelle Hellgeth, a nurse from
Marietta, Ga., has gone even farther. Working on a computer in her
bedroom just nine weeks ago, she organized an impeachment rally for
Monday across from the White House in Lafayette Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never spoken out in my life,'' she said. She said that
she was doing it for her three grown children because ``I think
that moral values are so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellgeth has lined up nearly a dozen speakers, including
McCorkel and Barr, for Monday's event.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
