<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DOKOUDOVSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VLADIMIR DOKOUDOVSKY, 79, BALLET DANCER, TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vladimir Dokoudovsky, a founding member of Ballet
Theater, a principal dancer with the Ballets Russes troupes of the
1930s and '40s and an influential teacher in New York, died on
Wednesday at St. Clare's Hospital in Manhattan. He was 79 and lived
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, said his wife, Patricia.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Mordkin Ballet, a forerunner of American
Ballet Theater, Dokoudovsky was among the dancers who in 1940
formed the nucleus for the first New York season of Ballet Theater,
as that company was originally called.
</P>
<P>
   He was best known for his appearances with the two organizations
that tried to preserve the heritage of Diaghilev's innovative
Ballets Russes: Col. W. de Basil's Ballets Russes and the Ballet
Russe de Monte Carlo. He danced with the Monte Carlo company in
1938, and with the colonel's group from 1942 to 1952, interrupting
his tenure there to return to the Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo as a
guest artist in 1950 and 1951. He also choreographed ``Les Femmes
d'Alger,'' inspired by a Delacroix painting, for de Basil in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Monte Carlo of Russian and Italian parents, Dokoudovsky
received his early training from Olga Preobrajenska in Paris and
made his debut with the Monte Carlo Opera Ballet in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   Although noted for his wide range of classical and character
parts, Dokoudovsky specialized in the works of such Ballets Russes
choreographers as Michel Fokine, Leonide Massine and David Lichine.
He was especially associated with Fokine's choreography, displaying
his versatility in such roles as the barbaric Warrior in ``Prince
Igor,'' the sensuous Golden Slave in ``Scheherazade'' and the
nimble Harlequin in ``Carnaval,'' as well as in the title roles of
``Petrouchka'' and ``Paganini.'' In recent years, Dokoudovsky
revived Ballets Russes productions for several regional companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, he started teaching in New York schools,
including Ballet Arts and the American Ballet Theater School. He
opened his own New York Conservatory of Dance in 1977. A popular
teacher, he was also a highly demanding one and his authoritative
presence led several generations of students to nickname
Dokoudovsky ``the Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a sister, Tatiana
Dokoudovska of Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 1823EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
