<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winter meetings make comeback
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It used to be sort of fun when baseball would pick an
idle winter weekend, fly in the owners and general managers to some
hotel and talk baseball so loudly for so long that the nation
couldn't help but listen.
</P>
<P>
   The winter meetings were devised in part to get baseball back
out on the front page during the offseason, and the trades and
free-agent signings got the game's blood flowing again. Then the
locusts came in '92, and baseball called the whole thing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winter meetings are a tough place, with the agents knowing
the general managers are back there,'' Braves general manager John
Schuerholz said. ``They really get in the way. They really create
an atmosphere that's more bothersome and time-consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after a five-year hiatus, the majors will hold its
first full winter meetings this weekend at Nashville's sprawling
Opryland Hotel. The concept has lost some of its appeal. A number
of owners are not attending, and there is some concern that, having
spent more than $700 million on free agents just since the season
ended, the clubs have lost the mood for dealing.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, Kevin Brown is out there for the taking,
and while the finalists are down to Los Angeles, St. Louis,
Colorado and San Diego, Scott Boras, Brown's agent, would love
nothing more than to flit from hotel room to hotel room while
hiking the bidding. Boras did so in the 1992 meetings in Louisville
when he played the New York Yankees against the Braves for Greg
Maddux. But the bigger money made dealing more difficult, and the
1992 meetings that saw both Maddux and Barry Bonds change teams
altered the landscape. In a near frenzy, teams spent almost
$258million on 34 players in just 48 hours. In an awful conclusion,
Florida Marlins president Carl Barger suffered a fatal heart attack
in the lobby as the meetings were breaking up. Next year came the
moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   After the huge contracts already granted, Nashville's meetings
will be mellower. Roger Clemens' trade demand will stir the most
interest, and the Blue Jays already are pushing Houston for second
baseman Craig Biggio so Clemens can return to his native state.
Montreal's Rondell White is on the block, too.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect much from the Braves. Schuerholz already pulled
off the Bret Boone trade at the more sedate GM meetings, and the
acquisition of free agents Brian Jordan and Otis Nixon have filled
the team's remaining needs. Unless, that is, someone wants to talk
about Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
