A4768 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LENNOX06-COX     12-05 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LENNOX06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis fights for recognition
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He was born in England, grew up in Canada, maintains a
residence in Jamaica and trains in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All Lennox Lewis needs is for somebody, somewhere, to embrace
him.
</P>
<P>
   After 35 pro bouts, Lewis, 33, has won only one title belt and
zero support as the reigning heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really concerned about the criticism I've received,''
he said. ``I'm just looking forward to my chance to prove everybody
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That it has taken until now _ or until March 13, when Lewis
meets consensus champion Evander Holyfield in New York City _ is
the biggest impediment to Lewis gaining credibility. He is 34-1
with 27 knockouts, a powerful right hand, tremendous size (6 feet
7, 243 pounds) and an Olympic gold medal. But he has never fought
Holyfield, Riddick Bowe, Mike Tyson, Michael Moorer or George
Foreman, who have held the three main titles (WBA, WBC and IBF) for
most of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been an extended yawn over Lewis' accomplishments
and a microscopic fan base. The latest defense of his WBC crown,
against Croatian Zeljko Mavrovic, was held in a tent at a Native
American casino in Connecticut. Only a few thousand fans paid their
way in.
</P>
<P>
   One week earlier, Holyfield sold out the Georgia Dome. The fact
Holyfield has fought Bowe three times, Tyson and Moorer twice, and
Foreman and Larry Holmes largely explains his popularity and
credibility, which are partners in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis accuses Holyfield _ and others _ of ducking him, not the
other way around. ``I think (Holyfield) made a mistake by waiting
this long to fight me,'' he said. His manager, Frank Maloney, said,
``He's always wanted the recognition as the best heavyweight. After
this fight, people will say, `That's Lennox Lewis. He beat Evander
Holyfield.'''
</P>
<P>
   For now, all Lewis' supporters can say is he beat Tommy
Morrison, Razor Ruddock, Tony Tucker, Frank Bruno, Henry Akinwande
or Andrew Golota. He lost to Oliver McCall and avenged that only
when the substance-abused McCall suffered a nervous breakdown in
the ring. His narrow decision over Ray Mercer was disputed.
Holyfield denies avoiding Lewis but says his upcoming opponent's
reputation is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't judge him by the fact people didn't fight him,'' he
said. ``I'm fortunate because every time somebody didn't fight him,
it seemed like they fought me.''
</P>
<P>
   A recap of Lewis' non-opponents:
</P>
<P>
   _ Holyfield. He and Lewis were close to a deal last year but it
fell apart when the HBO cable network declined to put up sufficient
funds for the fighters' purses. Others blame promoter Don King for
sabotaging the talks by coming to an agreement with Lewis
($10million) before seeing what Holyfield would seek ($20million),
or Lewis for not lowering his demands. Holyfield also sought out
Lewis prior to Holyfield's first fight against Tyson in 1996 but
was rejected by the Lewis camp.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bowe. Lewis was a mandatory WBC challenger after Bowe's win
over Holyfield in 1992. But Bowe renounced that portion of the
title _ throwing the belt in a garbage can _ because he wanted to
make a few easy defenses first. The belt was presented to Lewis,
the first of two times he would claim a title without fighting a
champion. A second attempt to match Bowe and Lewis fell apart in
1993 when Bowe decided to give Holyfield a rematch. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tyson. Lewis was a WBC mandatory challenger again after Tyson
defeated Frank Bruno in 1996. But Tyson and his former promoter,
King, chose a perceived easier and richer fight against Holyfield.
Tyson not only was stripped of the WBC belt before the Holyfield
fight, he had to pay Lewis $4million to settle a lawsuit. King now
admits: ``Evander shocked the world when he beat Tyson. He shocked
me, and I didn't know I was in the world.'' Lewis went on to win a
rematch with No.2 ranked McCall for the vacant title.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moorer. When Moorer upset Holyfield, he thought a defense
against Foreman would be more lucrative and easier than against
Lewis. He was right on the first count, wrong on the second.
</P>
<P>
   _ Foreman. After Foreman floored Moorer, he declined to fight
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer, believes Lewis' reputation for
avoiding difficult fights is unjustified, but he likes his
fighter's chances in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lewis) was an Olympic champion, and that's enough for me,''
Turner said. ``But from what I see, he doesn't have the tools to
beat Evander at his best. He's not as quick. He's not as tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis impressed more people as an amateur. After moving with his
mother and brother from London to Toronto in 1977, he went 75-7 in
the Canadian amateurs, the last win coming by knockout over an
American named Bowe to win Olympic gold in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   His development is widely believed to have been impeded by
former trainer Pepe Correa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been inconsistent at times, just like Evander,'' said
trainer Emanuel Steward, who is now in Lewis' corner. ``Lennox
should do well because of his physical strength, but I'm not sure
how they match up style-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield believes Lewis will wilt under pressure, saying, ``He
tries to knock you out, but he's never had a guy who can put
pressure on him. I'll hit him when I want to hit him. Pressure
makes people change. It's either gonna make him better or it's
gonna make him fold up like everybody else. I'm either gonna knock
him out good or I'm gonna knock him out bad. Either way, I'm gonna
knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's little surprise that Lewis believes otherwise. Holyfield,
he said, ``hasn't seen anything like me. When he gets hit and
realizes the power I have, things can happen mentally to a person
in the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   THE LENNOX LEWIS FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 33.
</P>
<P>
   Born: London.
</P>
<P>
   Residences: Jamaica, Toronto, London.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Single, no children.
</P>
<P>
   Title: WBC champion.
</P>
<P>
   Record: 34-1 (27 KOs)
</P>
<P>
   Pro highlights: KO over Donovan ``Razor'' Ruddock in 1992;
decision over Ray Mercer in 1996; TKO over Oliver McCall in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pro lowlight: TKO loss to McCall in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I'm going to step into the ring with one belt and out
with three.''
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS VS. HOLYFIELD
</P>
<P>
   When: March 13.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Madison Square Garden, New York City.
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Holyfield's WBA and IBF heavyweight titles, Lewis' WBC
title.
</P>
<P>
   Purses: Holyfield $20 million, Lewis $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Holyfield 36-3 (25 KOs), Lewis 34-1 (27 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
