<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FEATURE06-COX     12-05 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FEATURE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safeties hit and miss
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When he was NFC defensive rookie of the year in 1995,
Orlando Thomas started all 16 games, led the league with nine
interceptions and returned one for a touchdown. In the 41 games he
has played since that impressive debut, the Minnesota Vikings' free
safety has eight interceptions _ only one this year _ and no
scores.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation for the dropoff, Thomas said two weeks ago, is
no explanation at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years later, I'd like to think I'm a smarter player
now,'' Thomas said as he studied videotape of the Green Bay
Packers' passing attack. ``But other than that, not a whole lot has
changed, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a significant change has occurred the past few
seasons, not so much to Thomas but to the position he plays. Think
of the traditional NFL free safety, and the mind conjures up images
of Hall of Famers Larry Wilson, Paul Krause and Emlen Tunnell.
Those men, who combined for 212 interceptions, played deep in the
secondary. They were defensive ``center fielders'' with superior
range, who moved well to the ball and benefited from overthrows by
scatter-armed quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But free safety has evolved as much into a run-support role as
pass defender during the past two years. Most secondary coaches
concede that it is getting increasingly difficult to locate free
safeties with strong ``ball'' skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an instinctive position,'' Vikings defensive coordinator
Foge Fazio said. ``We get guys whose instinct is to make the big
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend has left the NFL with a terrific group of impressive,
young strong safeties, including Lawyer Milloy (New England),
Robert Griffith (Minnesota), Rodney Harrison (San Diego) and John
Lynch (Tampa Bay). The quality at free safety, though, makes it
difficult to identify anyone enjoying an All-Pro season.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 through 1996, free safeties either led the league or
tied for the NFL lead in interceptions, but they didn't last year
and won't this season.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 starting free safeties in the NFL have 38 interceptions.
Sammy Knight of New Orleans is the only player with more than four.
Thirteen of the starters have none.
</P>
<P>
   Brock Marion, who played the first five seasons of his six-year
career with Dallas and now starts in Miami, hasn't had an
interception since the final game of 1995. That's a stretch of 38
games, during which he earned $4.76 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time you needed to have the (fortitude) of those
guys who pulled off the Brink's robbery,'' said Krause, the career
interception leader, who often was criticized for a passive style.
</P>
<P>
   Several coordinators said that some free safeties, including
Eugene Robinson of Atlanta, have lost range during the years.
Others said that catching skills have slipped at the position.
Fazio, secondary coach Bill Bradley of Buffalo and Colts assistant
head coach George Catavolos agreed that pass offenses have dictated
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``More offenses read (the secondary) from high to low now and
they are attacking the outside,'' Catavolos said. ``When everyone
played `cover two' (with two safeties deep), it was different. Now
you're seeing more `cover three' on third down, and teams are
bringing the free safety down to help against the run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
