<HEADER>
A4770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-AUGUSTA06-COX     12-05 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-AUGUSTA06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old master has a new look
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since mid-October, members and guests at the Augusta
National Golf Club have been playing a course yet untouched by
anyone in a Masters tournament.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Golden Bear tracks on the four holes that were
reworked this summer. There are no imprints from where a Tiger
Woods drive of gargantuan proportions has returned to earth. There
have been no azaleas in bloom yet on No. 2, No. 11, No. 15 and No.
17 since they were tweaked by architect Tom Fazio in June, mostly
to bring accuracy more into play heading into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly a reconstruction, it was nonetheless the most
extensive project the club has undertaken since it changed the
greens from Bermuda to bent grass in 1980. At a place where things
change less frequently than Haley's Comet passes over Washington
Road, it's a moderately big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta National members are used to seeing the course in less
than pristine condition when closed during the summer months, but
they are not accustomed to observing huge areas of bare clay and
earthmovers.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, the changes:
</P>
<P>
   _ The par-5 No. 2 hole was lengthened by 25 yards with a new
back tee to 575 yards and a stone wall next to the tee box. Also,
the fairway bunker was shifted right to widen slightly the driving
area.
</P>
<P>
   _ The green at the par-4, 455-yard 11th hole was raised
approximately 2 feet, creating a new, back-left pin position, and
the pond was raised about a foot to accommodate flood control in
Rae's Creek, which was widened by about half its former size. Two
bunkers were removed and a new bunker placed in the right-center.
</P>
<P>
   _ The par-5, 500-yard 15th hole's fairway mounds to the right
side were reduced by about 85 percent, reducing the slingshot
effect for drives that land there. About 20 pine trees were planted
to the right side of the fairway, increasing the accuracy factor.
Also, a mound on the right side of the green was removed, with six
pine trees planted there.
</P>
<P>
   _ The par-4 17th hole was lengthened from 400 to 425 yards. The
pine clusters from the 15th hole come into play to the right of the
17th fairway.
</P>
<P>
   The changes take the previous yardage from 6,925 yards to 6,985
yards (3,500 in; 3,485 out).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these changes we've made will hold up for the
foreseeable future,'' Augusta National chairman Hootie Johnson
said. ``We're comfortable with our golf course. The record that
Tiger broke (17-under par) stood for 32 years. I think we have a
pretty challenging golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Former state amateur champion Danny Yates, an Augusta National
member, has played the reworked course a few times since the
project and said, ``I definitely think it's going to make it more
challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the 15th hole has the greatest potential for effect.
Modern players have blasted drives there with little fear of
second-shot difficulties, but the added trees on the right have
tightened the driving area. With the mounds all but gone and its
accompanying slingshot effect that could add 40 yards to a drive,
the second shot could be a few clubs longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty big difference because you can't just hit it
over there to the right and just bomb it,'' Yates said. ``In fact,
I hit it over there and I just pitched it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The back tee at the dogleg-left second hole will affect mostly
tournament play, but everyone must be more mindful of the right
fairway bunker. Six-time champion Jack Nicklaus' recommendations on
alterations to Augusta National apparently were not as popular as
Fazio's.
</P>
<P>
   Of No. 2, Nicklaus told the Augusta Chronicle earlier this year,
``I wouldn't mind at all if they just blew that hole up. It's a
hole that plays illogical to me. It requires a duck-hook second
shot from an uneven lie to a green that only accepts fades. How
much sense does that make?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
