<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFCNOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decision time, by George
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Raiders, who got more mileage from backup
quarterback Donald Hollas than anyone could have anticipated, face
a tough decision soon on Jeff George. The former Falcon can void
his contract just by being on the roster at the end of the season
and force the Raiders to buy back an additional three years for a
signing bonus of at least $5 million. The problem is that George
has started and finished only four games in '98 because of a severe
groin injury, and that hasn't provided coach Jon Gruden a fair
gauge on how the QB fits into his offense. Gruden, owner Al Davis
and personnel chief Ken Herock love George's arm, but the Gruden
offense is predicated on getting the ball out quickly and George
has a penchant for holding it too long and taking too many sacks. A
clarification on George's injury: It was a tear, not a strain, and
the reported ``aggravation'' to the original tear, suffered Nov. 8
in the first series against Baltimore, was actually a new injury
just above the old one. ``Basically, he was starting the (healing)
process from scratch,'' Oakland quarterbacks coach Gary Stevens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Replay redux
</P>
<P>
   The addition of the new Cleveland Browns in 1999 _ and franchise
president Carmen Policy _ increases the odds that instant replay
will return. But not for the reasons espoused on last week's CBS
pregame show. Insider Michael Lombardi erroneously reported that
replay still would need only 23 votes to pass. But with the Browns
re-entering the league, the magic number for approval increases to
24. Where the value of Policy comes in is his ability to influence
other votes. Buffalo Bills owner Ralph Wilson, a steadfast replay
opponent, announced he'll support it.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly wagers
</P>
<P>
   The questionable pass-interference call at the end of last
week's Buffalo-New England game, and subsequent two-point
conversion when Bills coach Wade Phillips didn't get his team back
on the field, had little bearing in Las Vegas. The point spread in
some parts of the country, including Atlanta, was either 3 or 3 1/2
points. The two-pointer allowed the Pats to win by four. But Caesar
Robaina, a spokesman for the Las Vegas Sports Consultants _ which
sets the line for most of that city's casinos _ said there was
little action on the game. Because of the finger injury to Drew
Bledsoe, the game was off the board until late Friday afternoon.
Then, it opened with the Pats favored by 1 1/2 and went to 2 points
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bad blood
</P>
<P>
   The league office already has served notice to Kansas City coach
Marty Schottenheimer and Denver counterpart Mike Shanahan that a
repeat performance of the debacle three weeks ago will result in
stiff sanctions. Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe has declared
publicly that he will attempt to strike a truce with Chiefs
linebacker Derrick Thomas in pregame warmups. Not surprisingly,
he's told teammates he hopes to verbally get under Thomas' skin
again during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals bungles
</P>
<P>
   Because he won't spend big on free agents, Cincy owner Mike
Brown has to take more chances on dubious-character picks in the
draft than almost anyone else. The Bengals seem to have reformed
tailback Corey Dillon, but their luck ran out last week on safety
Tremain Mack. The former fourth-rounder ('97), who has been
convicted four times for DUI, was sent to jail through January for
violating parole.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Miami receiver and former No. 1 pick Yatil Green, out two
seasons in a row with knee surgeries, has begun jogging. ... If
coach Pete Carroll is axed in New England, look for Packers
offensive coordinator Sherm Lewis to be a candidate. ... The
University of Hawaii is interested in June Jones if he's not
retained by the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
