 &HT;    Grass getting Green-er
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pool of available veteran quarterbacks, which only
a month ago appeared dismal, has improved dramatically. By starting
10 of 12 games, Randall Cunningham has voided the second year of
his Minnesota Vikings contract. While coach Dennis Green would love
to keep both Cunningham and Brad Johnson, finances might dictate
that one of them goes. An unrestricted free agent who created a
market for himself is Washington's Trent Green. Since the Redskins'
bye week on Oct. 25, Green has thrown 11 touchdown passes and just
one interception and owns a 92.2 passer rating in five games.
Unless the Saints re-sign Kerry Collins, he'll attract suitors as
well. Add to that the quarterbacks who figure to be released after
June 1 _ Scott Mitchell (Detroit), Gus Frerotte (Redskins), Warren
Moon (Seattle) and Jeff Blake (Cincinnati) _ and there's the
potential for a real quarterback carousel again.
</P>
<P>
   Packers search
</P>
<P>
   The list of possible replacements for Mike Holmgren being
compiled by Green Bay GM Ron Wolf could include Jets assistant head
coach Bill Belichick and Vikings offensive coordinator Brian
Billick. Eagles coach Ray Rhodes remains a solid possibility as
well. Billick would be compelling because he'd serve a dual purpose
_ keeping an offensive-minded coach in charge while weakening a
division foe. Wolf's mentor was Al Davis, remember, and the Raiders
owner was notorious for interviewing assistants from every other
division team when he had a vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Bearly hanging on
</P>
<P>
   Chicago coach Dave Wannstedt hasn't discussed his job situation
with Bears president Michael McCaskey in more than a month and
doesn't quite know how to perceive the lack of dialogue. The last
time the men talked, McCaskey congratulated Wannstedt for holding
the team together, but that was before QB Erik Kramer went on the
shelf and the club stopped playing competitivelySteve
StenstromMoses Moreno. Vice president Mark Hatley Rod GravesYoung
updateBryant YoungKen NortonMichael Dillingham
</P>
<P>
   Etc.Vinny CerratoEddie DeBartoloJerry RichardsonDom CapersFred
LaneJim HaslettTom Modrakand then Capers going back to Pittsburgh
to take Haslett's job. ... After the loss at Philadelphia on
Thursday night, not even the $7.5 million it will take to buy out
Dick Vermeil Duce StaleyCharlie Garner
</P>
