<HEADER>
A4775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE-MANNI     12-05 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE-MANNING06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manning's maturing on the job
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ With 2:49 remaining in the game against the New
York Jets three weeks ago, Peyton Manning hoisted the weight of the
world from his right shoulder and tossed it to Indianapolis Colts
teammate Marshall Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by a fourth-and-15 and a fast-closing linebacker at
the Colts' 33-yard line, elusive tailback Faulk feinted past the
would-be tackler and turned a short dump-off into an 18-yard gain.
The play moved the sticks and resuscitated a floundering series.
Faulk kept alive a sequence in which Manning overcame three
penalties, drove the Colts 100 yards in all and threw a winning TD
pass to tight end Marcus Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   And Manning advanced another link along the evolutionary chain
that promises to make him a premier player soon at the NFL's
highest-profile position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we all sort of consider that (play) a defining moment,''
said former University of Georgia standout Adam Meadows, the right
tackle for the Colts. ``That was one where you thought to yourself,
`Well, he's taken another big step now.' It was the latest in the
series of revelations.''
</P>
<P>
   What the rookie quarterback realized in his initial
fourth-quarter comeback was that even guys earning $6million a year
and carrying the label of Franchise Savior can't make every play by
themselves. It is a lesson the former University of Tennessee star
will carry into this afternoon's game against the Atlanta Falcons
at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Colts quarterbacks coach Bruce Arians noted that just a few
weeks earlier, Manning probably would have considered the
fourth-and-15 situation and convinced himself he had to throw the
ball to the down-marker to have a shot at converting. On the play
to Faulk, the tailback was Manning's third _ and as it turned out,
his best _ option, given the coverage New York was playing.
</P>
<P>
   Even quarterbacks with Manning's impressive heritage aren't
supposed to make those kinds of adjustments in only their 10th NFL
start, coach Jim Mora acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, that comes from experience and starting to be more
comfortable,'' Manning said after a midweek practice. ``The natural
reaction is to feel you have to throw it the length of the yardage
you need. But, hey, guys wouldn't be in this league if they all
couldn't make plays. You have to let the people around you do what
they do best. That helps you, and it helps you make better
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   By definition, such epiphanies are not planned in advance. And
quantum leaps typically are more serendipitous than scripted.
Still, those singular moments are a byproduct of preparation. And
in Manning, the Colts have a guy who lives the Boy Scout creed.
</P>
<P>
   A quarterback makes progress in the league by building
incrementally, preparing in the classroom and then stacking
successful physical plays on top of that mental foundation. That's
a blueprint Manning followed even at Isidore Newman High School in
New Orleans, and his debut season in the NFL indicates no need for
revision.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: While he would love to have attended Saturday
night's SEC title game, there's no way Manning would have asked to
be excused from team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   With four games remaining, the first overall selection in this
year's draft is on pace to demolish every rookie passing record.
Manning needs 38 attempts, 25 completions and 24 yards to put his
name atop those categories. Four more touchdown passes will wipe
out Charlie Conerly's rookie mark.
</P>
<P>
   Manning probably would trade in those gaudy individual numbers
for a few more victories, and he conceded that Sunday nights,
Mondays and Tuesdays are ``miserable'' after defeats. Despite a
2-10 record, though, the Indianapolis offense is becoming one of
the league's better units.
</P>
<P>
   The very presence of Manning puts the Colts a leg up on other
rebuilding franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a team in this league that doesn't want the
quarterback who can take you to a Super Bowl,'' Mora said, ``and
we've got one. Peyton is way beyond what I thought he could be this
year. I've never seen the guy flustered. Sure, he gets frustrated
when things don't go well or he doesn't perform the way he thinks
he should. But he's never let it affect his performance. His game
last week (at Baltimore) was something. Even in a loss, you
thought, 'Man, that was something for a rookie.' And then, 'Hey,
that was a great game for anybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond throwing for 357 yards and three touchdowns, Manning was
on top of the game mentally. For most of the Colts' 67 plays, he
called two options in the huddle and then, after getting a pre-snap
read on safeties and linebackers, checked to one or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Joe Namath once noted that in his third or fourth
season with the Jets, he broke the huddle, came to the line of
scrimmage and immediately recognized every defensive scheme. ``It
was like someone suddenly lifted a curtain,'' Namath said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's game, Manning said, was like that for him. The
difference is, it was one of only a couple times this year that it
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Steve Young probably feel that way every week,'' he
said. ``Part of the thing with me was, I was playing too fast. It
might seem contradictory, but you almost have to slow yourself down
to be successful in this league. I'm getting there, but it's not
all the way yet. At the beginning of the season, I was probably
playing at maybe 100 mph. Now I might have it down to 75 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the speed, Manning is miles ahead of the NFL's usual
learning curve and the Colts will bear his imprint for years to
come. Like all three sons of Archie and Olivia, he is
characteristically unpretentious yet commanding. On those occasions
when he's had to light into a teammate, the deed has been carried
out in private. And there is no denying the respect of those around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that was important to me was earning that
respect of my teammates,'' Manning said. ``And then second was
getting the respect of opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished the first, in part, by grabbing a locker stall
right in the middle of the offensive linemen. Asked last week about
that move, Manning admitted the ``I'm-one-of-the-guys'' symbolism
attached to it. On the field, even the skeptics among opponents now
have few doubts about his star potential.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan claimed last week that the
secondary would be ``licking our chops'' against Manning. The
Baltimore corners who felt that way last week were left with their
tongues hanging by game's end.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens cornerback Rod Woodson said, ``There (is) an elite bunch
of guys who have that something special to them. He's one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
