<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dierdorf may be headed out of Monday Night Football booth
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The rumor that Dan Dierdorf might be replaced soon in
the Monday Night Football booth could become fact. Mike Ornstein,
who represents Sterling Sharpe, has been negotiating for a deal
that would team the former Green Bay wideout with Boomer Esiason
and Al Michaels. ... Look for the Jets to sign Vinny Testaverde to
an extension before the end of the season. Agent Michael Azzarelli
met Friday with Bill Parcells and cap specialist Mike Tannenbaum,
and they're getting closer on the numbers. ... Agent Tank Black of
Columbia, S.C., has jumped out in the recruiting wars, landing
several prime prospects already. He has the inside edge on LSU
tailback Kevin Faulk and Florida linebacker Jevon Kearse. ...
Atlanta guard Calvin Collins probably will need elbow surgery after
the season. ... Oregon quarterback Akili Smith now looks like a
solid first-round prospect for the '99 draft. ... Some NFL teams
now are beginning to eye UCLA coach Bob Toledo. ... Several
Redskins officials fear that safety Jesse Campbell might not be
able to come back from surgery that left his knee mostly
bone-on-bone.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   Owners Ralph Wilson of Buffalo and Detroit's William Clay Ford
complained about calls that director of officiating Jerry Seeman
conceded were erroneous. For stating the obvious, that the
officials are worse than ever, they were fined $50,000 by Paul
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Two-minute drill
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Dallas Cowboys tailback Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Topic: The NFL record for career rushing touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Background: Just one season after some observers insisted his
career was in decline, Smith has spent much of 1998 achieving new
milestones. Earlier this season he passed Tony Dorsett as the top
rusher in franchise history and moved past Jim Brown for the No. 5
spot in career rushing yards. He is on pace for his best season
since 1995, and his next rushing touchdown will give him 124 and
break Marcus Allen's league record.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Of your 123 rushing scores, 79 have been between 1 and 4
yards. So would you prefer to break the record on a 1-yard blast or
a 50-yard romp?
</P>
<P>
   A: To do it in style, with a long run, would be nice. But that's
not really my style. Most of those touchdowns have been me running
through somebody. So if I score on a 1-yard run, where there's some
bodies scattered, that's OK with me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You save the game balls from your touchdowns. Can you
remember the first one, and what's the plan for all those
footballs?
</P>
<P>
   A: My first (touchdown) was on a 2-yard run against Washington
in 1990. I think it was about the third game of the year. I have
that ball and every other one. They're my rainy day insurance.
They're worth something if I decide to sell them. Maybe I'll keep
No. 124 and sell the rest to collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will be the significance of the record for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: To score this many times, to me, it means I was out there
every week. I played hurt. I ran hard. I knew where the end zone
was and did what it took to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Spotlight on...
</P>
<P>
   Veteran: In its last six games against Green Bay, all losses,
Tampa Bay has averaged 9 points and quarterback Trent Dilfer has a
microscopic passer rating of 44.9. The Bucs desperately need a
victory Monday night to retain flickering playoff hopes, and Dilfer
must get them some points.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie: Fourth-rounder Jason Fabini has started every game for
the Jets, and despite five false-start penalties the first five
games, has solidified the right tackle spot for coach Bill
Parcells. A good run blocker, he'll be tested by Seattle
speed-rushers Chad Brown and Michael Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent: Injuries to wide receivers Robert Brooks (hamstring)
and Antonio Freeman (jaw) could provide Bill Schroeder an even more
prominent role in the Green Bay offense. The former World League
player entered the year with two career catches but already has 30
grabs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: A year ago Carolina owner Jerry Richardson suggested
coach Dom Capers had a lifetime contract. But a 2-10 record and
Capers' public role in free-agent additions of expensive busts such
as defensive end Sean Gilbert and cornerback Doug Evans could
seriously weaken the coach's job security.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
