<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE-REDWINGS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wings keep their cool
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So much for foreshadowing.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Detroit Red Wings were a franchise in need of
two things _ a winning streak and an airplane. It was bad enough
that the two-time champions fell 6-2 in Calgary for their sixth
loss in eight games _ their worst skid since Scotty Bowman's first
month as coach in 1993. But the team's airplane was grounded when a
fuel truck collided with the fuselage, ripping open a hole that
forced the Wings to bus four hours to their next game in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Detroit was not on the brink of a collapse,
but a rejuvenation. A 6-2 win over the Oilers started a five-game
win steak in which the Wings outscored opponents 26-8. Included
were a seven-goal third period in Vancouver, four wins by rookie
goalie Norm (It's A) Maracle and a performance against San Jose
impressive enough that Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said, ``Until
somebody takes the Stanley Cup away from the Red Wings, there's
nobody close. They're the best team in the league by 10 miles. I
mean, is there any other team that can play four lines and have
their starting goalie out for a period of time and it doesn't
bother them at all?''
</P>
<P>
   What plagued the Wings during an 8-8 start is the type of
post-title malaise general manager Ken Holland expected. As strange
as it sounds, Holland believes they would have been more
susceptible to emotional problems last season if not for two
incidents that helped unify and motivate the team:
</P>
<P>
   _ A limo crash shortly after the 1996-97 Stanley Cup finals that
ended the career and nearly the life of defenseman Vladimir
Konstantinov.
</P>
<P>
   _ The near season-long holdout of Sergei Federov.
</P>
<P>
   With Bowman pondering retirement, Detroit started this season
4-1 with assistants Barry Smith and Dave Lewis running the team.
But when Bowman returned, the Wings won only four of their next 11.
</P>
<P>
   Did Bowman's return cause players to relax again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Good question. I don't know,'' Holland said. ``We talked in
training camp about potential problems we might have this year.
There had been such pressure for so many years here to deliver that
Cup, and when we finally won it, I thought there might be a letdown
last year. But the accident happened, Federov held out and
everybody pulled together. This year we went through what I thought
might happen last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the slump had to do with Scotty coming back or
it was just part of the process we expected. This team has played
so many big games ... the last three or four years. It's pretty
difficult for a coach to walk in and say it's a big game when it's
only November. It's not a big game. The flip side is, the team we
play every night, it's their big game. It's their benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does anybody in Hockeytown seem overly concerned that
Detroit has dropped both meetings with the Dallas Stars, who, with
the addition of Brett Hull, believe they can make it past the Wings
in the Western Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could've played better against them and we weren't as
emotional as I thought we should be,'' Lewis said. ``I don't want
to make excuses. ...But it's not like we have little X's (on the
calendar) on those days that we play them. Calgary beat us twice,
too. Toronto beat us twice. We can't just worry about Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings, trying to become the sixth team to win three straight
Cups, had periods of domination during their five-game streak. In a
6-2 win at Edmonton, they scored three times in the first 16
minutes. Against Vancouver, they trailed 1-0 after two periods
before reeling off seven straight goals.
</P>
<P>
   Maracle, who has replaced injured Chris Osgood, said of the
team's mood after the second period against Vancouver, ``The guys
were just hanging out, talking. We're losing at the end of the
second period and they're not even worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too early for worries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
