<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bouncing a Czech
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last thing NHL commissioner Gary Bettman wanted
reported last week was the cash-poor Pittsburgh Penguins satisfying
their payroll with the $2.5million they received from the cash-rich
Rangers as part of the Petr Nedved trade. Bettman balked at
approving the trade to begin with and relented only because the
Rangers included a quality player in the deal, Alexei Kovalev. From
that point, the league's stance became, ``Well, it's the Penguins'
money, they can do what they want with it.'' But the perception was
a team sold one star player so it could pay the other ones.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has become enough of a PR problem for Bettman, what
with the bankruptcy status, feuding co-owners (Roger Marino and
Howard Baldwin) and the inability of Mario Lemieux to collect
several million dollars in deferred salary. And, yes, it could get
worse. The French company Societe Generale has agreed to lend the
Penguins $20 million, but a U.S. bankruptcy judge has yet to
approve the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Water boys
</P>
<P>
   In its aim to make a buck, the NHL may have cost the New York
Islanders a goal Wednesday in a 3-2 loss to the Rangers. Although
the league does not allow goalies to keep a water bottle on top of
the net during the playoffs, it mandates they have one during the
regular season because of a merchandising deal with the beverage
company whose logo is on the bottles. So guess what? With the Isles
trailing the Rangers 3-1, Joe Sacco appeared to tip in a shot
midway through the third period. Live and replay views seemed to
show Rangers goalie Mike Richter catching the puck over the plane
of the goal line and pulling it back out. But the goal light never
came on, and when a replay judge was consulted, he said the only
camera angle with an otherwise clear shot had a view that was
blocked by the water bottle. ``Do you think it was a goal? How many
views do you need?'' said Isles coach Mike Milbury. His team's
second goal didn't come until five seconds remained.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Guess this trade worked out. In the first six games Keith Jones
played for Philadelphia after being acquired from Colorado, the
Flyers went 6-0 and outscored opponents 25-9. Jones is skating the
top line with Eric Lindros and John LeClair, and the three combined
for 17 goals during the streak. ... The Rangers have opened
contract extension talks with defenseman and captain Brian Leetch,
who would become an unrestricted free agents after the season. New
York is offering deals averaging $6 million per year, at least $1
million less than Leetch is seeking. His outlook: ``Hopefully it
will go smoothly. Chances are it won't but hopefully it will.'' ...
Hurricanes owner Peter Karmanos on the dreadful attendance (7,300
average) in the team's temporary home in Greensboro: ``I'm not
happy with the crowds in Greensboro. I'd be lying if I said I was.
But I'm not disappointed in the sense that I think we're in the
wrong market.'' The Hurricanes maintain their new arena in Raleigh
next season will solve their problems _ provided it's finished in
time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
