<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympics, game overtime on NHL board's agenda
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   THE AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   The league will hold its twice-a-year Board of Governors
meetings Monday and Tuesday in Scottsdale, Ariz. Nothing will be
decided but almost everything will be discussed, most notably:
</P>
<P>
   _ The NHL's participation in the Olympics. If Nagano wasn't a
complete disaster, it surely wasn't a thrilling success. It has
been assumed the NHL will return in 2002 to the Salt Lake City
Games because they are in prime time in the United States, giving
the league more exposure on NBC than it had in Japan. But officials
maintain nothing is certain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ties and overtime. The increasing number of draws and the
relative ineffectiveness of overtime have owners concerned. Two
possible alternatives: (1) End games with a shootout, as most minor
leagues do; or (2) make a victory worth three points instead of
two, giving teams more incentive in the overtime to take chances.
</P>
<P>
   _ The bankrupt Penguins. Pittsburgh's financial report will draw
the most interest of all the franchises. Ownership made last week's
payroll with the $2.5 million it received from the New York Rangers
in the Petr Nedved trade. It's worth noting that commissioner Gary
Bettman, who detests cash-for-player trades, probably would have
killed the deal if the Rangers had not included forward Alexei
Kovalev in the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   BETWEEN SHIFTS: JAROMIR JAGR
</P>
<P>
   _ Team: Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: Tied for the league scoring lead with 33 points in 22
games, but only fourth on team with seven goals.
</P>
<P>
   _ On his impact in his native Czech Republic: ``When I was
younger, we didn't hear anything about the NHL. It was illegal to
even talk about it because they thought a lot of guys would defect.
Now, all kids dream of playing in the NHL. People see games on
satellite TV and can read about the games in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the Penguins' success despite personnel losses: ``Kevin
(Constantine, head coach) has done an excellent job and we've had a
lot of underrated players come up from the farm. Everybody is
scoring goals. In Kevin's style, everybody works hard and everybody
gets chances.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his lack of goals this year: ``I've never considered myself
a goal scorer. I think of myself as more of a passer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the Penguins' acquisition of Alexei Kovalev: ``He's
probably one of the five most talented guys I've ever seen. They
put too much pressure on him in New York. I think it's going to be
a lot easier for him here.''
</P>
<P>
   THRASHERS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   With it becoming increasingly unlikely that the Thrashers will
have a permanent practice facility in place for next season, don't
be surprised if general manager Don Waddell reverses his plan to
hold training camp in Atlanta and sets up in Orlando. The IHL's
Solar Bears and NBA's Magic share one of the top athletic
facilities in the country, and Waddell helped design the hockey
side of it when he was Orlando's general manager. ... Orlando also
remains the Thrashers' probable minor-league affiliate. Waddell has
met with four teams in the IHL and AHL, as well as the
commissioners of the two leagues, to help determine where to spot
the farm team. ... Previous commitments by the Detroit Red Wings
voided Waddell's plans to bring the Stanley Cup champions to
Atlanta for an exhibition next year. ... The team ran the first of
five hockey and skating clinics for the Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs Saturday
at the World of Coke's outdoor ice rink. The next one will be
3:30-4:30 p.m. Monday with Olympic gold medalist speedskater Dan
Jansen as a guest instructor. Mostly, former Atlanta Flames are
running the clinics. Curt Bennett attended Saturday's and ex-goalie
Dan Bouchard, who runs a hockey program at Life College, will work
two of the next three Saturdays, 8:30-10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
