<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLWEST06-COX     12-05 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No yucks for Canucks
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of two things is likely to happen in the next week
or so:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Vancouver Canucks trade Pavel Bure to Los Angeles or the
New York Rangers;
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach Mike Keenan runs over general manager Brian Burke with a
Winnebago.
</P>
<P>
   Both are used to doing things their own way, and their
relationship seemed destined for failure from the time Burke took
over as GM and inherited Keenan. Neither does it help that Keenan
reportedly has a clause in his contract that states he must approve
all personnel decisions. The contract was not amended when Burke
was hired. A major irritation could be removed if Burke finally
deals Bure, the talented forward who has been holding out all
season _ not for a new contract, just a new employer.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings and Rangers seemingly are the only two teams willing
to pay Bure's $8million salary and both are star-hungry _
particularly L.A., which is struggling on the ice and at the gate
and is moving into a new arena next season. Keenan has infuriated
Burke, saying the GM is dragging his feet on a deal, and pulled an
all-timer last week in Toronto when he yanked goalie Garth Snow on
a power play while trailing 3-1 early in the third period. The
Maple Leafs scored into an empty net to clinch the win. Afterward,
Keenan claimed he was desperate for offense and made a point of
saying he would not have pulled Snow for an extra forward if Bure
were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly safe assessment to make that we need help,''
Keenan said. ``It's time for us to evaluate our personnel in terms
of who can play under pressure and who can't. That's for Brian
Burke to evaluate.'' Burke's response: ``When you lose a couple of
games in a row, everybody's seat of their pants gets a little
tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Decaf Coffey
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to find a bigger bust this season than
Chicago's cameo defenseman, Paul Coffey. The Blackhawks acquired
Coffey and his $2.5million salary from Philadelphia, knowing, at
37, he was far from the perennial All-Star who played for Edmonton.
But they expected more than this. After 24 games, Coffey has played
in only four because of back and knee injuries. His totals: 0
goals, 1 assist, $731,707.32 in collected salary.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   L.A. also is talking to the New York Islanders about unsigned
forward Ziggy Palffy, who would cost about $3 million less than
Bure but doesn't have the marquee value. ... The slow start by the
Kings, who are scraping bottom in the league with a 2.2
goals-per-game average, has worn on coach Larry Robinson. He says
he ``won't be the fall guy'' if the team continues to lose, all but
mandating that GM Dave Taylor make changes. ``There's nobody going
to the front of the net,'' he said. ... St. Louis goalie Grant
Fuhr, who started the year 3-1-2 with a 2.03 goals-against average
until suffering a torn abductor muscle four weeks ago, says he is a
few days from returning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
