</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 12/05/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 5, 1998 -- NY-VEGGIE-SINGLES, 12-5 --
William Mejia with his Northern Blue-tongued skink from Australia
named ``Krishna,'' at a Veggie Singles party. The parties which
attract hard-core animal lovers, is for folks who go beyond mere
meat avoidance to shun all animal products. No cheese, no eggs, no
honey. ``I've never had a girl not want to date me because of my
reptiles,'' says Mejia. ``They'll usually start with 'Can I touch
it?' Then they want to hold it.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MORRIS PLAINS, N.J. -- Dec. 5, 1998 --
NJ-COLUMN-BORDELLO-FURNITURE, 12-5 -- An appropriately immodest
statue belonging to the woman who became notorious last summer as
the Morristown Madam was expected to fetch up to $3,000 at an
auction. Both the auction house and Mrs. Judith Kelley Dempsey, the
Morristown Madam, whom the auction catalog discreetly identified
only as a former Playboy bunny, were hoping that publicity about
Mrs. Dempsey's case would raise prices. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NORTH HILLS, N.Y. -- Dec. 5, 1998 -- FBN-JETS-2, 12-5 --
Mo Lewis, a 6-foot-3-inch, 258-pound New York Jets linebacker, is
careful to separate his born-again aggressive football persona from
his life at home with his wife, Christalyn, and his sons, Morris
IV, 3, and Christopher Wiley, 11 months. ``I don't take my job home
to my wife,'' he says. ``You hear about some players who come home
angry. She has enough to worry about with my two boys.'' (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NORTH HILLS, N.Y. -- Dec. 5, 1998 -- FBN-JETS-1, 12-5 --
Mo Lewis, a 6-foot-3-inch, 258-pound New York Jets linebacker,
usually goes to martial-arts classes three days a week from 6:30 to
7:30 a.m. Many of Lewis' moves on the field start from a coiled
position, a style that Lewis adapted from his martial arts
training. ``I start in a coiled position because it helps me react
and attack more quickly,'' he says. However, with the Jets (8-4)
entering the crucial point of the season with four games to go,
Lewis has put the martial arts on hold, conserving his energy. (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 5, 1998 -- BBA-ARATON-COLUMN, 12-5 --
The story of Orlando Hernandez's departure from Cuba by boat has
been challenged by some of his companions as being exaggerated. Was
it really a leaky raft, tossed by waves, chased by sharks? Everyone
was guessing, until three of El Duque's companion defectors told
Sports Illustrated and then The Associated Press that some of the
previously circulated material on Hernandez was the journalistic
equivalent of an El Duque curveball, in the dirt. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NASHUA, N.H. -- Dec. 5, 1998 -- NH-PRIMARY-FRENZY, 12-5
-- Former Gov. Hugh Gregg of New Hampshire, an expert on the
state's primary, says the political courting started earlier this
year than ever before. ``The new round of courting effectively
began the day after the 1996 vote, when former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander put out bumper stickers advertising his bid for the
presidency in 2000.'' (Kirsten Elstner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 5, 1998 -- CENSUSTAKER-PROFILE, 12-5
-- Milton Kaufman, hired by the Census Bureau in 1934, remembers
the machines -- one as big as an entire room -- that tabulated
census data decades before modern computers. More than 80 percent
of the country's current population had not been born when Kaufman
was first hired by the Census Bureau. Kaufman's job advice is
simple. ``Always be good to your employees, because they may be
your boss someday,'' says Kaufman, who retired this fall after 64
years of service. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
