<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-ANNAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN REBUFFED IN BID TO GET LIBYAN SUSPECTS IN L OCKERBIE CRASH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The UN secretary general, Kofi Annan, failed
Saturday to persuade Libyan leader Moammar Khadafy to immediately
surrender two Libyan suspects in the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight
103. But Annan said Khadafy assured him during a meeting at a
desert camp that he is ready to find a solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats had held high expectations that a meeting would
produce a breakthrough. But UN officials said the unpredictable
Libyan ruler still may rebuff Annan's efforts to send the two
suspects in the terrorist bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, which
killed 270 people, to the Netherlands to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talks have been fruitful and positive. And Libya has
confirmed its seriousness and readiness to find a solution to the
Lockerbie problem,'' Annan said at a news conference in Tripoli
after meeting with the Libyan leader in his desert tent. But he
added that it ``will require some time'' to clinch a deal.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear what was holding up a final agreement. The
last major sticking point for Libya was a demand by Britain and the
United States that the two suspects be imprisoned in Scotland if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   UN diplomats were confident that a British offer to allow
outside observers to monitor their treatment and to provide Libya
with unlimited diplomatic access to the prisoners had satisfied the
Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   Khadafy has come under pressure from his allies in Africa and
the Middle East in recent months to accept an offer from the United
States and Britain to have the suspects tried in a neutral country.
US and British officials _ seeking to resolve the matter before the
10th anniversary of the bombing on Dec. 21 _ said Saturday that
Khadafy is running out of time.
</P>
<P>
   A White House foreign policy spokesman, David Leavy, warned that
Khadafy could face ``tough action'' _ most likely tighter sanctions
or an international oil embargo _ if he does not turn over the
Lockerbie suspects soon.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has been under a UN air and arms embargo since 1992 for
refusing to turn over to American or British authorities the two
Libyan citizens suspected of planting a bomb on Pan Am 103. Khadafy
said the suspects, Abdel Basset Ali Megrahi and Amin Khalifa Fhima,
could not get a fair trial in the United States or Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the Organization of African Unity endorsed a Libyan
request for a trial in a neutral country. In August, the United
States and Britain agreed to a trial in the Netherlands under
Scottish judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called his bluff,'' Leavy said. ``If he doesn't turn them
over, he would alienate himself from the people in the region and
increase their understanding for tough action.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as Thursday, British and UN officials expressed
confidence that Annan was near agreement with Libya for the
arrests. But by Friday, the Libyan leadership cast doubt over a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Libyan-controlled news agency JANA said the
decision to surrender the suspects could not be made by Khadafy,
but by the Libyan parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khadafy has a history of stringing things along,'' Richard
Murphy, an analyst at the Council on Foreign Relations, told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who has taken the lead in negotiating the terms of the
surrender of the suspects, flew Saturday from Tunisia to the Libyan
town of Sirte, some 250 miles east of Tripoli, for a meeting with
Khadafy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was received by Libyan Foreign Minister Moar
Montasser. JANA said at the time that Annan would not be able to
meet Khadafy.
</P>
<P>
   But following the Sirte meeting, Annan and several top aides
were whisked to an undisclosed desert encampment to meet with
Khadafy for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Observers suggested Khadafy, who decided to convene a
parliamentary meeting Tuesday to decide the fate of the suspects,
was seeking to drag out the crisis in order to exact greater
concessions from the West.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan insisted before traveling to the region that he was
not prepared to negotiate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
