r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-05 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS MUTINY? THERE'S A HITCH TO THAT THEORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interesting week around here.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson said no. Rafael Palmeiro said yes. Then came a
firestorm of public opinion, pro and con, over Pudge-for-Rocket
trade speculation. Good stuff, with plenty of emotion attached.
</P>
<P>
   You know it's a hot and heavy baseball topic when everything
involving the Cowboys, including Nine-Toed Deion's availability, is
shoved off into a December sports-page corner.
</P>
<P>
   This is a reminder. The Cowboys do play today in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cowboys a mere afterthought all week, a friend called
Friday to say he was expecting a ``Jones fires Gailey'' media
conference, just because Jerry was miffed over not being this
week's headline act.
</P>
<P>
   But moving right along again, the most outrageous local sports
story of the week didn't involve the Rangers or the Cowboys.
Actually, this one ended up being buried, but it's worth digging
up.
</P>
<P>
   A Phoenix newspaper, citing unnamed sources, said last week that
big trouble was right around the corner for the Stars, considered
by some to be the NHL's best team.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Arizona Republic'', one Stars player wanted
to take a swing at coach Ken Hitchcock during a recent game, and
other Stars players had privately complained to general manager Bob
Gainey that Hitchcock was being outcoached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to blow up pretty soon down there if they aren't
careful,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, a similar report appeared in a Detroit newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In total contrast, we live in one of the most competitive media
markets in the country, and the Stars, being of world championship
caliber, are closely watched by two newspapers, and a multitude of
TV and radio stations. There hasn't been even a hint of this in the
local media.
</P>
<P>
   It's best never to say never, but the opinion from here says
total fabrication is involved. Has a player ever wanted to take a
swing at the very demanding Hitchcock? Probably more than once and
more than one player. But a locker room mutiny brewing? There is
absolutely nothing to support that.
</P>
<P>
   The official stance of Hitchcock and Gainey is ignore such
foolishness. But it's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Heika has covered the Stars for this paper since day one.
In all that time, he had never heard Gainey even raise his voice.
Then last week, Heika raised the issue of the Phoenix report.
Gainey was suddenly yelling in anger at him over ``irresponsible
journalism.'' And Heika had written nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also was as angry as I've ever heard him last week,
but most of his comments were unprintable for a family publication.
</P>
<P>
   Finally cooling off, he noted, ``while there's no truth in any
of it, there are a couple of good lessons that all of us can take
from this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good teams have to deal with these kind of things.
Somebody out there will always try to create a disruption. Like in
any family, disagreements will happen. But you have to keep them in
your own room, because someone on the opposition will try to bring
you down.''
</P>
<P>
   There are Stars players, even the top names, who have
disagreements with Hitchcock. One complaint is that Hitchcock wants
perfection every game, but that's untrue. He demands perfection
every shift. Any slack off, and Hitchcock is sure to yell.
</P>
<P>
   For a fan paying the high tariff for Reunion hockey seats,
Hitchcock is their dream coach. He wants the paying customer to
always receive his money's worth in effort on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But when a player thinks he has a beef with Hitchcock, if he
tells it to a player on an opposing team, word can get around
quick. And the media in another city can end up with ``mutiny
conditions existing in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   But the same player who was mad a week ago can be Hitchcock's
most vocal supporter a week later. So it goes in any locker room in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may think you have a friend on another team, but during
the season he has to be considered the enemy,'' Hitchcock said.
``And that includes a coach on another team who is a friend of
mine. Everyone is looking for an edge against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a perfectionist, Hitchcock also loves to tinker
with his line combinations. Joe Nieuwendyk, for example, never
seems to know who his linemates will be from one game to the next.
There is locker room grumbling over this, although not from
Nieuwendyk. Again, however, it's part of the business of coaching,
and it happens everywhere. But the Stars are so good, things become
magnified, particularly if the opposition picks up on the
displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   Let me add a personal note. Hitchcock drives me crazy by
constantly making Brent Severyn a healthy scratch. See there, I've
got a complaint, too.
</P>
<P>
   But a brewing mutiny in Dallas? The first guy who said don't
believe everything you read in the newspaper had a good point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
