<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-UTEP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU'S FOWLER STEPS UP, FOIL UTEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A gimmick defense seemed like as good of a
plan as any for UT-El Paso to stop All-American Lee Nailon, thereby
stopping TCU.
</P>
<P>
   So UTEP dropped another player back to help on Nailon,
challenging TCU's guards, and Prince Fowler in particular, to beat
them.
</P>
<P>
   The guards, and Fowler in particular, answered that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a dizzying display of second-half 3-pointers, TCU
defeated UTEP, 86-79, yesterday afternoon at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was a real key in the game,'' Horned Frogs
coach Billy Tubbs said. ``We started stepping up and knocking down
threes because they were kind of challenging us to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince Fowler really got hot at the right time; he stepped up
and made some big threes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler nailed three 3-pointers in a two-minute span early in the
second half, helping to erase a UTEP lead that had grown as big as
nine points.
</P>
<P>
   TCU was 7-for-10 on 3-pointers in the second half, as Vladimir
Jaksic also chipped in three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real hard to handle the big guy around the basket,''
Miners coach Don Haskins said of Nailon. ``So we got in a gimmick
defense. It doesn't sound like it when you give as many points as
we did, but they were at least out on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miners ran a triangle-and-two, a defense where the point
guard drops down to help guard the post players.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler was the player without a defender for most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Recent history seemed to indicate that Fowler was a good player
to challenge. He had gone 2-for-15, including 1-for-11 on
3-pointers, in TCU's first game against UTEP, a 75-70 victory on
Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   He got off to an equally shaky start yesterday, 0-for-4 from the
floor in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, I didn't feel comfortable. I was rushing my
shot,'' Fowler said. ``I kind of relaxed myself coming into the
second half, and I just stepped up and shots fell down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler finished with 17 points and eight assists, and Nailon
finished with a game-high 24 points. He left the game with 17:03
remaining after rolling his right ankle, but returned less than
three minutes later. He is expected to be ready for TCU's game
against Texas Tech on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs had five players in double figures, dominated
the offensive glass, but still found themselves trailing for long
stretches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strange game,'' Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   There was the 30-second span in the first half where TCU had
four fouls called against them. There was the fact UTEP shot 59
percent from the field, and didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   There was the fact that this was the second meeting between the
two Western Athletic Conference teams this season, but neither one
counts in the conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Fowler, the guy whom the Miners were so
unconcerned with that they didn't bother to cover him, knocking
down the shots that ended up winning the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised,'' UTEP's Jarvis Mullahon said. ``The first
time their post players did all the scoring. We didn't known the
other guys could score as well as they can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
