<SLUG> BC-FBN-PRO-FOOTBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILURE OF JOHNSON'S ASSISTANTS A MAJOR MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oklahoma's dismissal of John Blake is yet another example of a
rising coach being touched by Jimmy Johnson's magic wand _ and then
watching as his career turns into a pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Shula (career record: 19-52). Dave Wannstedt (39-53). Butch
Davis (30-15). Norv Turner (29-46-1). John Blake (12-22).
</P>
<P>
   Does anybody notice a trend here?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a belief,'' Johnson says now, ``that they'll get the
job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But the stories of how each of Johnson's aides became
head coaches might be instructive in deciding why, as a whole,
they've been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wannstedt, rightly celebrated as a defensive mind,
downplays Johnson's involvement in the orchestration of his January
'93 move to Chicago. But a story he told then lends insight.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first playoff game of the 1992 season against
Philadelphia, both the Giants and Bears were elbowing their way
toward interviews with Wannstedt. But their interest was not public
knowledge. Until. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I'm in my office, watching Eagles film, and the phone
starts ringing off the hook,'' Wannstedt said. ``Everybody knew
everything. I couldn't figure it out. But what had happened was,
Jimmy had just stood up in a press conference and announced that
teams would have permission to interview me immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   And the problem with that, Dave?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, only thing was,'' Wannstedt said, ``is he forget to tell
me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1988, Don Shula's son, Dave, asked Johnson for
some career advice. Johnson told him it would be wise to leave his
father's Dolphins staff.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Johnson was the Cowboys coach. Hurried to
build a staff, he called Don to ask for permission to hire away
Wannstedt, who had departed Johnson's University of Miami staff for
a Dolphins job just a few weeks earlier. By the end of the
conversation, Johnson had hired both Daves.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of conflict, Dave Shula was issued a demotion
that would lead to his quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Shula's career took a crazy but temporary upturn a year later.
Shula was the Bengals receivers coach when head coach Sam Wyche was
fired. Shula met with Bengals general manager Mike Brown to inform
the boss of his vacation plans and desire to remain on the staff in
some capacity. But oddly, five hours later, Brown offered Wyche's
top job to Shula.
</P>
<P>
   Norv Turner's career path is a classic example of the role luck
plays. Shula got two years in Dallas and was out. Then Johnson
offered the job to old friend Gary Stevens, who accepted _ but then
relented to pressure from a miffed Don Shula and stayed with the
Dolphins. Then came calls to assistants Ted Tollner of the Chargers
and Joe Pendry of the Chiefs, both old Wannstedt pals. But their
clubs wouldn't free them. Then came an interview with Vikings aide
Bob Schnelker, which did not go well.
</P>
<P>
   And then came recommendations for a guy named Norval Turner, a
38-year-old Rams receivers coach. How well did the Cowboys know
him? After agreeing to interview him, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones
dispatched a staffer to the PR department to locate a Rams media
guide to confirm that the fella's name was really ``Norval.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch Davis was elevated to defensive coordinator after
Wannstedt's departure. Like Wannstedt, he was strong-minded in his
occasional bucking of the Johnson system _ which probably earned
him the mentor's respect. Along with staffer Joe Avezzano, Davis
got a courtesy interview for the head coaching job when Johnson
left. And he was under consideration for the Oakland Raiders' top
job. But instead, after the 1994 season, he moved to Miami to
become the Hurricanes' head coach. His allegiance to the Hurricanes
caused him to accept a football team left in shambles after the
renegade times of Johnson and successor Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is now considered a semi-success in some circles for doing
things ``the right way.'' And this year's Hurricanes are 8-3 with
the big upset of UCLA yesterday. Nevertheless, Davis' career record
is not what was once expected of a Jimmy protege.
</P>
<P>
   An aide who never won Johnson's respect, John Blake spent the
'93 season on the staff. Blake, a former Oklahoma standout, was
rescued for a time when, coincidentally, his surrogate father,
Barry Switzer, replaced Johnson in '94. Switzer relied on Blake as
a right-hand man until '96, when Blake's involvement in a Valley
Ranch racial conflict contributed to Switzer's guiding him to the
Oklahoma job.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Johnson Super Bowl Era assistants who used
that success as a career springboard is shockingly limited. Which
begs the question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Were they wildly successful as Cowboys assistants because of the
great leadership of Johnson? Were they outstanding cogs in a
machine who got exposed when put in charge of the machine? Did
Johnson's influence make them? Or did it ruin them?
</P>
<P>
   Not even Jimmy Johnson himself has the answer to that one.
NFC BUZZ There are rumors Green Bay GM Ron Wolf, thinking ahead to
when coach Mike Holmgren departs after this year, might go outside
the organization for his next coach, with Philly's Ray Rhodes on
the short list. Hiring Rhodes might be the only way the Packers
deflect criticism for not promoting Sherm Lewis. Wolf's reported
reasoning _ that hiring from within a Super Bowl-winning team
rarely results in a return to the Super Bowl _ seems lame. But at
least those who've long believed Lewis gets passed over because
he's black would be quieted by the candidacy of Rhodes. ... The
Bears are 7-21 in their past 28 games. That's the worst stretch in
Chicago since posting the same record during a 28-game stretch in
1973-74. ... Chargers at Washington: Redskins QB Trent Green has
thrown for 606 yards, seven TDs and one interception in his past
two games, and in Washington's past five games the 'Skins are
averging 29.4 points per. ... The Saints think they've done all the
right things in laying the groundwork for QB Kerry Collins to
re-sign in New Orleans. ``We've been understanding and
compassionate,'' says coach Mike Ditka, who rescued the troubled
Collins after he was dumped by Carolina. ``But if they feel there's
a better place in the NFL, I'm sure they'll take him there.'' And
then, a word of caution from Ditka: ``Go forward. Don't go
backward.'' ... No, the Packers still aren't believers in the
Vikings, despite having been blown out twice by Minnesota this
year. ``I'm not going to say they've overtaken us,'' says tight end
Mark Chmura. ``We're not folding our tents.'' ... The Vikings have
been ordered to turn down the volume on Metrodome speakers
stationed on the visitors' sideline _ speakers that resonate with
crowd noise and are aimed directly at the visitors' bench. ...
Detroit's Barry Sanders is one TD away from becoming the sixth
player in NFL history with 100. ... Minnesota cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock never had an interception in four years at North Carolina
and had just four in three seasons with the Patriots. The Vikings
acquired him for a third-round pick, and now Hitchcock has five
interceptions this year, including two returned for TDs. ... The
Cowboys are worth $413 million, according to ``Forbes'' magazine,
which makes the Cowboys' franchise the most valuable in sports. But
two points: 1) If Jerry Jones was to ever sell, $413 million would
be but a fraction of the eventual purchase price; and 2) suggesting
that a present value of $413 million means Jones got a steal in
1989 when he bought the club for $147 million is ignorant. Jones
himself is the driving force behind the increased value of the
club.
AFC BUZZ The Broncos have two unlikely stars in receiver Ed
McCaffrey and center Tom Nalen, both maybe Pro Bowl-bound _ and
both in Denver because of a rather lopsided transaction. In 1994,
the Giants traded a seventh-round pick for a Broncos receiver named
Arthur Marshall. Marshall is no longer in the NFL, but the player
taken with that Round 7 pick is. He's Nalen. And the player cut
that summer to make room on the Giants roster for Marshall is. He's
McCaffrey. ... This is when the traditionally awful Bengals usually
turn it up: Maybe it's contract runs, but Cincy has won seven of
its past eight December games. ... Look for Jon Kitna to be the
Seattle starting QB for the rest of the season, with Warren Moon as
No. 2. ... Rookie QB Peyton Manning is on pace to throw for 3,000
yards and become the first Colt to do it since Bert Jones in 1976.
... The Chargers haven't allowed a 100-yard rusher all year, and
remember, they've faced Denver and Terrell Davis twice. ... Today's
hottest name in future NFL head coaches? Pittsburgh defensive
coordinator Jim Haslett. ... Chiefs at Broncos: A rematch of the
facemask-pulling, knee-tackling,
embarrassment-to-the-citizens-of-Kansas City game of three weeks
ago. Chiefs officials are adamant in promising there will be no
cheap-shotting this week. But Kansas City QB Rich Gannon is more
realistic. ``I'm sure everyone will have their eyes wide open,''
Gannon says. ``And they should.'' ... CBS studio host Marcus Allen
swears he has no idea where cohort George Seifert will land next
year as a coach. ``It's a weekly series of George spottings,'' says
Allen of various rumors. Meanwhile, San Diego's June Jones can see
the Seifert-related handwriting on the wall. Jones replaced Kevin
Gilbride when the Chargers were 2-4. San Diego is since a more
respectable 3-3. ``I know at the end of the year they're going to
see what's available and who's out there,'' says Jones, aware that
Mike Holmgren and Seifert figure to top many teams' wish lists.
Jones apparently feels comfortable, however, with the Chargers'
organization. ``There's a possibility,'' he says, ``they might hire
somebody else and I still might stay.'' ... So who portrays Buffalo
QB Doug Flutie when the made-for-TV movie comes out? Three
candidates: Donny Osmond; Rick Springfield; Michael J. Fox.
``Definitely Michael J. Fox,'' says Dallas center Mike Kiselak,
Flutie's teammate in the CFL. ``That's what we all called him up
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
