<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON'S WORDS LOUDER THAN ACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you're old enough in America, you can say anything
you want, unless you own a team in the No Fun League. If you do,
you're probably rich enough to say anything you want but you'll pay
a high price for it, as 80-year-old Ralph Wilson learned.
</P>
<P>
   It was interesting to read Wilson's three-day whinings over how
badly he and his team were treated last week by the NFL and its
officials in a last-second loss to the Patriots since Wilson has
long been an obstructionist to the one thing that might have helped
his team avoid the whole mess. Conveniently, that seemed to slip
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson complained bitterly that a plethora of television replays
clearly showed Shawn Jefferson out of bounds on a fourth-down catch
that kept the winning New England drive alive with a minute to
play, forgetting that seven times he has voted against instant
replay, including four times since 1990, all tight votes in which
Wilson's support might well have carried the day because he is so
well respected among his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Then his team gets burned by a crew of officials who admittedly
could choose ``Three Blind Mice'' for theme music, and he's singing
the blues louder than Ruth Brown.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilson was slapped with a $50,000 fine by NFL commissioner
Paul Tagliabue for his comments, Wilson went on the offensive,
issuing a statement that read in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Society today is more enlightened. Fair comment and criticism
are rampant. The entire media as a unit is frank and the millions
watching a game are frank.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Commissioner, lecturing me as if I were a novice
instead of one who has been involved in football infinitely longer
than he has, contends that criticizing a call has `destructive and
corrosive effects on the game.' What is more destructive and
corrosive _ errant calls in front of millions of viewers or my
statements of opinion?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, to be frank, Ralph, your concern over the NFL's violation
of free speech is well taken, but where have you been? How come
you've never spoken out on the subject before, such as when some
poor sap like Bryan Cox is getting slapped with a fine for
criticizing the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   How come you never made a case for free speech when some coach
who won't make in a lifetime what you've made in a week in some of
your business ventures gets crushed by the Commissioner's Office?
How come, for example, you were silent a few years back when
Steelers coach Bill Cowher was fined for chasing down an official
and stuffing a picture of a formation in his pocket as a protest?
</P>
<P>
   It was, frankly, impressive to see Wilson finally stand up and
take a slap at what he knows has been going on for years in the
NFL, but how come it never happened until his own ox was being
gored? How come he never spoke up for Sam Wyche or Jimmy Johnson or
the hundreds of players who have been fined for speaking their
mind?
</P>
<P>
   Wilson went on to say, ``Something has to be done to make this
different in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Ralph, a lot of people have been trying to get something
done to make things different in the future. It's called instant
replay, and in case you've forgotten, you voted against it in 1985,
1987, 1988, 1990, 1991, 1992, and 1997. Conversely, the Patriots
have voted for it eight of the nine times it has been proposed.
</P>
<P>
   If Wilson really wants to make a difference, he can stop
complaining about something he helped make possible and come into
the 21st Century when the next instant replay vote comes up _ which
may not be until the 21st Century does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, there is more talk about controlling one's
destiny around the NFL than there is around an Ouija board.
</P>
<P>
   Every coach would love to be in the position of  &UR; Bill
Parcells &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who needs only to have his team win its remaining three
games from AFC East rivals Buffalo, Miami, and New England to lock
up the Jets' first division title since the divisional format began
in 1970. For the moment, the Jets need no help to return to the
playoffs for the first time since 1991, yet few teams have a more
difficult road than they, because they are in a division where four
teams are within a game of first place and every one of them seems
capable of changing the others' destiny at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and Dolphins are tied at the top at 8-4 while the
defending champion Patriots and surprising Bills lurk only one game
off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots appear to be getting healthy at just the right time
to make a stretch run, but the odds are stacked deeply against them
because they must play three of their final four games on the road
_ in Pittsburgh Sunday, in St. Louis next week, and then a classic
season-ending matchup with their old coach and running back,
Parcells and  &UR; Curtis Martin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; in the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Worse news is that despite a hot quarterback and reinforcements
arriving weekly, the Patriots have no apparent running game and
have struggled to stop the pass the last five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those pass-rush problems could be solved by the imminent
return of  &UR; Willie McGinest &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but it is unlikely that they can win
four times in winter winds if they continue to pass 45 times a
game.
</P>
<P>
   And while injuries have decimated the defense and the receiving
corps, the problems with the running game have had nothing to do
with injuries and seem fixed in stone (just like running back
 &UR; Robert Edwards's  &LR; feet).
</P>
<P>
   In the first six games of the season, Edwards rushed for 483
yards and six touchdowns, averaging 80 yards a game and 4.4 yards a
carry. But in the last six he has rushed for only 222 yards and one
touchdown, averaging 37 yards a game and 2.4 yards a carry. Worse,
he has looked tentative, perhaps tiring of getting slammed in the
backfield two or three times a game and never knowing when it might
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   While  &UR; Drew Bledsoe  &LR; is third in the NFL in pass attempts with
412, New England is 29th in the league in rushing, averaging a
dismal 78.8 yards a game. Only the lowly Carolina Panthers have
been more inept, which brings us to the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Martin was defecting to New York last March,
there was much talk in Foxborough of how a computer study revealed
that running back was the easiest position to fill. It was said
that while Martin may not be easy to replace, his production would
be, even if done by committee.
</P>
<P>
   Well, as of this morning, Martin has rushed for 1,039 yards _
334 yards more than Edwards. And you don't want to say the only
valid comparison is with Martin's rookie year, because he rushed
for 1,487 yards and 14 touchdowns that season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Patriots have enough of a running game to get to the
playoffs is debatable, but clearly the Jets do. New York also has
the best divisional record (4-1) at the moment, but it must go on
the road three straight Sundays _ at Seattle, at Miami, and at
Buffalo _ and it is only 3-3 away from the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The upside for the Jets is that they are playing their best
football of the season, and despite a franchise habit of
floundering late (6-27 this decade in December-January
regular-season games), New York is coached by a guy whose trademark
is winning with the season on the line.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason Parcells's teams are a collective 41-24 in
December and January since he became a head coach in 1983: He knows
how to prepare teams for a run to the finish line if they have any
legs under them.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, his Jets did not, which is why they went 1-3 and
blew a playoff spot after sitting at the same 8-4 mark they are
Sunday. It is also why running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell  &LR; and
quarterback  &UR; Neil O'Donnell  &LR; are gone, replaced by an apparently
injury-free Martin and  &UR; Vinny Testaverde &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde would be the comeback story of the season, were it
not for  &UR; Randall Cunningham &LR; . All but finished after losing his job
in Baltimore, Testaverde has emerged as what Parcells hopes is the
reincarnation of  &UR; Jim Plunkett &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots should already have been eliminated but they came
from behind to beat the Dolphins with 23 seconds on the clock and
did the same to Buffalo with no time left, courtesy of those calls
that had Wilson apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Bills won in New England, they would have been tied with
the Jets and Dolphins and looking at by far the easiest schedule of
the four teams. The winning percentage of the Bills' remaining
opponents is .458; they host both Oakland and the Jets at frozen
Rich Stadium while playing hapless Cincinnati and the Saints on the
road. That schedule should have been an edge, but the loss to New
England negates some of it, and Wilson knows that.
</P>
<P>
   As for Miami, the Dolphins are the polar opposite of the Bills
and not just because of the weather. They face teams with an
aggregate .771 winning percentage. Miami must go to Oakland, then
host the Jets and undefeated Broncos, before ending the season at
Atlanta against a team that could be in position to win its first
division title in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   So who really controls their own destiny in such a circumstance?
The Jets, because if they win, nobody can unseat them; and New
England, to a lesser degree, because it holds a win over wild-card
challenger Tennessee and could create the same situation with the
Steelers Sunday. In addition, it still has an opportunity to level
the field with the Jets, something it has already done with Miami
and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills have the easiest schedule but history is against them;
only three teams have begun 0-3 and ended up in the playoffs. Their
short-term future will likely be determined Dec. 19 against the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Dolphins, they have the stingiest defense in the
league, and that is always a major plus when the weather turns
foul, but they have not been able to mount much of a running game
and now have four of the five offensive linemen who opened the
season (plus tight end  &UR; Troy Drayton &LR; ) out with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   How will it play out? If you claim to know, you're kidding
yourself, but the Jets have the inside track and I like Buffalo's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave the Dolphins and Patriots? Well, if the
playoffs began Sunday, it would leave them in the playoff lineup as
well.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that four teams from one division will reach the
postseason, but unlike Pittsburgh and Oakland, at least the men
coaching those teams have one advantage this afternoon _ to some
degree, they control their destiny.
</P>
<P>
   At least until nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer  &LR; has been hot of late, and his
Cardinals are 6-6 and in the NFC playoff hunt for the first time
since 1982. Plummer believes it would never have been this way if
he'd listened to the people around him. ``You have got to set your
mind and goals and you have got to believe in yourself,'' Plummer
said. ``When everyone else is telling you you're too small, your
arm isn't strong enough, you're too skinny, you don't stay in the
pocket well enough, you can't take the hits, if I believed all
that, then I would be working somewhere else cleaning pools or
something in Arizona.'' Plummer said one reason he likes being
compared to  &UR; Joe Montana  &LR; is that, ``He was a guy who they said a
lot of the same things they said about me as far as the size and
the arm strength and little things like that. But he had the
intangibles that count.'' ... Speaking of intangibles, the
Cardinals do not play a single team with a winning record the rest
of the way, a fact that could help them reach the playoffs for the
first time in a nonstrike year since 1975. The Cardinals have never
reached the playoffs in a 16-game season ... Bledsoe has an
interesting point of view on what the two last-second wins he's
engineered have meant to his reputation: ``I think there's probably
a change in the perception of me as a quarterback. I don't think
these last two weeks will change me as a player either for the
positive or the negative, but I think that the perception of me as
a quarterback probably changes with those kind of games.'' Of
course, Bledsoe couldn't care less about how he's perceived. ``It's
not something that's necessarily important to me,'' he said. ``I
think that the ultimate goal is to win championships and when that
goal is achieved, then the perception changes. Until then, there
will be things out there that are not entirely favorable. But the
perception is not something that I care about. It's the winning
that I care about. If we can win games, then that perception can be
whatever it is and I don't really care.'' ... How bad are things
going for St. Louis coach  &UR; Dick Vermeil &LR; ? His team would have to go
on a five-game winning streak for Vermeil to have as many wins as
his predecessor,  &UR; Rich Brooks &LR; , &UR;  &LR; had on the day he got fired two
years ago. And the Rams have only three games left ... Vermeil is
not the only coach with heavy baggage to carry. In Chicago,  &UR; Dave
Wannstedt's  &LR; 7-21 record the last two years marks the worst stretch
for a Bears team since the short, unhappy tenure of  &UR; Abe Gibron  &LR; 25
years ago ... When  &UR; Koy Detmer  &LR; found  &UR; Jeff Graham  &LR; with an 18-yard
scoring pass last week against Green Bay, it was the first
touchdown pass to an Eagle wide receiver this season in 383 pass
attempts. Graham caught a second one in that game, and in
Thursday's win over the Rams,  &UR; Irving Fryar  &LR; got his first
touchdown reception since last December. Fryar is hardly part of
the problem in Philadelphia, but word from a source close to Eagle
owner  &UR; Jeff Lurie  &LR; is that the decision has already been made not
to re-sign Fryar next year when he becomes a free agent. The
Eagles' offense has been so stymied that it could become the
lowest-scoring team in the history of the 16-game schedule. To
date, Philadelphia has 109 points, which projects to break the low
of 140 set by the 1992 Seahawks ... Despite the Eagles' troubles,
remember this. Three years ago  &UR; Ray Rhodes  &LR; was the NFL's Coach of
the Year. The problem is, he can't coach some of the players the
nitwits paid to supply them have been bringing in. Rhodes could end
up as the Ravens' new head coach if  &UR; Ted Marchibroda  &LR; does not
survive or, at the worst, return to being defensive coordinator
under  &UR; George Seifert  &LR; or  &UR; Mike Holmgren  &LR; if either lands in
Seattle as a replacement for  &UR; Dennis Erickson  &LR; ... Erickson, by the
way, is all but gone in Seattle, where the Seahawks are 6-6 and
seemed to concede that they can't make the playoffs by sitting down
struggling veteran  &UR; Warren Moon  &LR; in favor of young  &UR; Jon Kitna &LR; .
Kitna came through last Sunday but Erickson concedes, ``It's not
Warren's fault by any means but in this business it's either the
quarterback or the coach.'' As Erickson well knows, sometimes it's
both soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the upside of the coaching carousel,  &UR; June Jones  &LR; has done
well enough in San Diego since replacing  &UR; Kevin Gilbride  &LR; that he
may survive his stint as interim coach. Jones is 3-3 after taking
over and benching rookie quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf  &LR; ... Star-crossed
Tennessee wide receiver  &UR; Yancey Thigpen  &LR; may be back Sunday after
missing six games with a knee injury. Thigpen's career has been one
of the oddest imaginable. Since becoming a full-time starter in
1995 in Pittsburgh, he has consistently followed a great season
with a nonexistent one. In '95, Thigpen had 85 receptions for 1,307
yards. The next year he had 12 receptions and played in only six
games because of injuries. Last year, he had 79 catches for 1,398
yards before leaving the Steelers to sign a multimillion-dollar
contract with Tennessee. This year, he's again missed half his
team's games with injury ... There are many reasons the Packers
have struggled this year, but one glaring one has been the absence
of the big plays that so characterized their recent seasons. This
time a year ago, Green Bay's offense had produced 50 plays of 20
yards or more. This year the number is 30. Worse, their running
backs had 12 such plays in 1997. They have none this season. But
director of football operations  &UR; Ron Wolf  &LR; said such statistics
tell little of the story. ``We haven't been consistent,'' Wolf
said. ``We've laid an egg every prime time appearance we've made.
Injuries have been the biggest problem for us but we're in pretty
good shape now.'' Wolf said the same applies to New England, which
at one point had seven starters in street clothes. ``To have that
many people out and still be in the playoff race is a credit to
 &UR; Pete Carroll  &LR; and his staff, or to somebody,'' Wolf said. ``You
can't operate in today's football without your players. The fact
New England is still winning with those injuries is remarkable.
Everybody has players injured but you lose seven starters and, God
almighty, it's hard to recover.'' ... Here's what the NFL will be
paid by its various TV partners during the length of it present
deal, from 1998-99 to 2005-06, according to a prospectus for the
NFL's recently derailed $600 million bond offering. ABC/ESPN: $1
billion; $1.05 billion; $1.3 billion; $1.35 billion; $1.185
billion; $1.22 billion; and $1.257 billion. CBS: $300 million, $350
million; $500 million; $400 million; $550 million; $690 million;
$715 million; $728 million. Fox: $450 million; $400 million; $450
million; $450 million; $575 million; $725 million; $765 million;
and $815 million. Escalator clauses that may kick in after five
years would make the take even bigger ... By the way, if you're
looking for a Christmas read for the football fan, consider Wolf's
recently published book, ``The Packer Way.'' It's a well-done
primer on how an organization is built ... When Bears rookie
 &UR; Curtis Enis  &LR; went down for the season with a knee injury, he
became the fourth top rookie running back in six years to suffer a
major injury. All of them _ Enis,  &UR; Garrison Hearst, Ki-Jana
Carter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Tshimanga Biakabutuka  &LR; _ had several things in
common. All were juniors coming out early and all missed
significant training camp time with holdouts. It makes you wonder
how much time is needed for a rookie to make the transition to the
NFL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
