<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4831 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      12-05 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE ON COURSE TO RENDEZVOUS WITH RUSSIAN MODULE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MARK CARREAU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Endeavour astronauts used the shuttle's robot arm
Saturday to raise and reposition the nearly 13-ton Unity module,
the first hurdle in their goal of linking components of the new
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle astronauts were on course to rendezvous with the
much-larger, $240 million Russian Zarya module tonight.(Eds.
Sunday) Astronaut Nancy Currie will use the robot arm to grab the
41-foot-long Russian module so it can be fastened to Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Working from her control panel within Endeavour's crew
compartment on Saturday, Currie commanded the 50-foot robot arm to
grasp and raise the 33-foot-long Unity module, which was stowed
horizontally in the shuttle's cargo bay for Friday's liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two hours, her commands rotated and repositioned
the raised module so that it was accurately aligned and suspended
just four inches from Endeavour's docking system. Pulses of the
shuttle's steering jets activated by Endeavour commander Bob Cabana
provided the forces necessary to shove the complementing docking
systems of the shuttle and Unity together.
</P>
<P>
   When the procedure was complete, Unity was secured vertically
and towering nearly four stories out of the cargo bay, ready for
Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Unity firmly attached to Endeavour,'' Cabana
informed mission control shortly before 6 p.m., CST. ``We're off to
a great start on building the international space station.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful sight,'' responded Chris Hadfield, the
shuttle crew's liaison in mission control, where ground teams
followed the activities by television and telemetry beamed down by
the astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Endeavour raced after Zarya, Russian for ``sunrise,''
the propulsion and electrical power generation module that was
launched from Central Asia on Nov. 20 as the cornerstone of the new
station.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, the shuttle trailed Zarya by just over 2,000
miles and was closing.
</P>
<P>
   The Endeavour crew should converge on Zarya at an altitude of
240 miles shortly before 6 p.m., CST, today. (Sunday)
</P>
<P>
   That rendezvous will set up the the most challenging phase of
the first station assembly mission.
</P>
<P>
   As the two spacecraft circle the Earth at five miles per second,
Cabana and pilot Rick Sturckow will steer Endeavour slowly toward
Zarya, rising gradually from several hundred feet below. They will
then maneuver their spacecraft about 350 feet in front of the
43,000-pound Russian module.
</P>
<P>
   As the operation continues, Endeavour will maneuver about 250
feet above Zarya, allowing Russian ground control teams to maintain
an unimpeded communications link to their module during the
upcoming shuttle capture.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the shuttle pilots will begin a slow descent
toward Zarya. With the separation within 35 feet, Currie will use
the shuttle's robot arm to grab the Russian module. With carefully
choreographed commands, Currie will position Zarya so that its
docking mechanism is aligned several inches above Unity's.
</P>
<P>
   More pulses of the shuttle's steering thrusters should drive the
two modules together, forming a single 75-foot-long, nearly
70,000-pound structural bridge between future American and Russian
segments of the new station.
</P>
<P>
   Unity is equipped with a half-dozen docking ports to join future
living quarters, research facilities, an airlock, viewing port and
an electrical power generating apparatus. The station's first crew
compartment, the Russian-built service module, should be launched
by the end of next year and joined to the opposite end of Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   At least three spacewalks by astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim
Newman are planned this week to link power and computer data cables
between the two modules and establish a communications link to
NASA's Mission Control Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the new station's 100 components will require at
least 43 more missions over the next six years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
