<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4834 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     12-05 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS BRING CLEMENS WOE UPON THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Blue Jays had just signed Jose Canseco, all this might
not be happening.
</P>
<P>
   All Roger Clemens wanted was some indication that Toronto was at
least trying to stay competitive enough to win the wild-card spot,
giving him a shot at the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also disturbed by the Blue Jays' off-season stadium
problems (they even threatened to move back to Exhibition Stadium,
for pity's sake), the declining Canadian dollar (which may not
affect him directly but certainly does indirectly) and ownership's
decision to cut payroll and hold it at the $43 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were manager Tim Johnson's fantasies about
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   A report in the ``Toronto Star'' says that Clemens has lost
faith in Johnson, brother of former Rangers assistant general
manager Sandy Johnson, after learning that the Jays manager had
lied to players and others about having served with the Marines in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' older brother is a Vietnam veteran, and Roger had
planned to have a special motorcycle helmet made for Johnson, who
was given a motorcycle as a birthday gift last July, with his
Marine company name and number on it. Clemens has since canceled
those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has apologized for having made up stories and promised
to seek counseling. ...
</P>
<P>
   If you're keeping score, there were two bona fide ace starting
pitchers on the free-agent market in Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown
(who's still there) and two at the next level who could have been
the No. 1 starter in the Rangers' rotation in Todd Stottlemyre and
Al Leiter. And how many has Rangers' general manager Doug Melvin
signed so far? Zero. ...
</P>
<P>
   One Toronto columnist, handicapping the race for Clemens, sees
it this way: (1) Astros; (2) Indians; (3) Yankees; (4) Rangers; (5)
Angels. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays were surprised and disappointed that Clemens,
despite winning consecutive Cy Young awards while in Toronto, had a
negligible affect on attendance on the days he started. In fact,
the Jays drew 2,559,563 fans the year before Clemens arrived and
2,454,283 last year. That's not likely to happen if Clemens comes
back to Texas, where fans love a power pitcher and where he's seen
as a local hero. ...
</P>
<P>
   Should Clemens come back to Texas, there would be some
similarities to Nolan Ryan's signing with the Rangers in 1989. Like
Ryan, Clemens is a pure power pitcher who is approaching some
milestones in career records. The difference is that Ryan was 42
when he arrived, six years further along than the 36-year-old
Clemens, who appears to have another two or three premier years
left in his arm. ...
</P>
<P>
   Two considerations as the Clemens saga continues: (1) He has the
right to veto a trade, which means he could turn down the Yankees
in order to force Toronto to send him to a Texas team; (2) Will he
force his new team to re-negotiate his contract, getting him into
the Randy Johnson salary range ($13 million a year)? Clemens has a
$5 million base salary for 1999, $6.35 million in 2000 and $5
million due in deferred payments. ...
</P>
<P>
   The agent for former Red Sox outfielder Mike Greenwell, who
didn't play last season, has contacted Melvin about his client
coming out of retirement. ``I might take a look at it later,''
Melvin says. ``It's not something I'm going to jump into.'' It's
not likely to happen unless the Rangers can't re-sign Lee Stevens.
...
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson's agent Dan Howits says the Rangers are among
the teams interested in his man. Melvin says that's not true. ...
</P>
<P>
   One reason Palmeiro may have been ready to get out of Baltimore:
There was talk that the Orioles might eventually move Cal Ripken
Jr. to first and ask Palmeiro to move to right field. ...
</P>
<P>
   Funny how the Rangers run from that phrase ``final piece of the
puzzle'' after Melvin trotted it out in his introduction of John
Wetteland two winters ago. ``\RPalmeiro\S can't be the final
piece,'' manager Johnny Oates says. ``He's just one of the pieces.
We all have to do our job.''. ...
</P>
<P>
   Yankees left-hander Andy Pettitte has been mentioned prominently
in the Clemens' rumors, but the Jays might be put off by reports
that he's seeking counseling to combat fear of throwing strikes.
...
</P>
<P>
   Now that Palmeiro's back in town, can Kenny Rogers be far
behind? The two are best friends, and Rogers' advice played a major
role in Raffy contacting the Rangers personally. ``I want him to be
here this year,'' Palmeiro says, ``not next year \Rwhen Rogers can
be a free agent\S. He wants to play here.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Melvin says the signing of Palmeiro won't affect the development
of last year's No. 1 draft pick, Carlos Pena. ``Carlos is also an
excellent defensive player,'' Melvin says. ``This just allows us to
take our time about bringing him along, but I could see him playing
first here in three years and Raffy moving over to DH.''
REVO'S RIMSHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   A Rangers' official on the most obvious difference between
Rafael Palmeiro and Will Clark: ``Just look at their bodies. One
works out; the other doesn't.'' Is that like saying Raffy looks
good, even in the shower?
</P>
<P>
   TCU vs. Southern Cal in the Sun Bowl? Sounds like that warning
about being careful what you pray for; you might just get it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a coin flip, maybe the NFL should have the captain of
each team just draw cards. High card gets their choice. That's
assuming, of course, that NFL officials know their cards better
than they do the rules on pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, Albert Belle promises to be more accessible to the
media, be more fan-friendly and pass out candy each and every
Halloween. ... has lightning struck Camden Yards yet?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
