<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMI-UCLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI DERAILS UCLA'S RUN FOR A NATIONAL CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As soon as Cade McNown's pass fell incomplete in the end
zone Saturday, almost certainly ending UCLA's hopes for a national
title, Paul Dee clenched his fists and began jumping in joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a game like this in 10 years,'' the Miami
athletic director shouted above the mounting din, after the
Hurricanes outlasted previously unbeaten UCLA, 49-45, before 46,819
at the Orange Bowl. ``It's wonderful. We're back.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss probably deprived UCLA (10-1) of a shot at the national
championship in the Fiesta Bowl. The Bruins entered the game second
in the Bowl Championship Series ranking, one spot ahead of Kansas
State, which was looking to remain undefeated in the Big 12
championship game against Texas A&AMP;M. If Kansas State won, UCLA
would head to the Rose Bowl, bumping Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Miami fans began spilling onto the field after the game. A
police officer wrestled down one of the first to reach the
sideline, but soon became overwhelmed. ``There's nothing you can
do,'' one officer said, as several thousand fans met at midfield,
jutting No. 1 fingers in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins trudged off the field, presumably in shock at seeing
a 38-21 late third-quarter lead disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't stop them,'' UCLA Coach Bob Toledo said.
``Our defense didn't play very well and obviously if you can't play
good defense you don't deserve to be a national champion.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Hurricanes, 8-3 and headed to the Micron PC Bowl at
nearby Pro Player Stadium, the showing provided some solace after
their 53-point beating by Syracuse the week before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was about getting our respect back,'' Miami Coach
Butch Davis said. ``We asked not one single person to surrender
until the game was over, and not one did. It took every ounce of
heart and soul we could muster to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami, four-time national champions, went a decade without
losing in the Orange Bowl, but had lost eight of its last 14 games
there after 1995 NCAA probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game says a lot about Coach Davis and this team to come
from where we were last Saturday to what we did today,'' said Scott
Covington, the Miami senior quarterback who threw for 318 yards and
three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Michael Lawson added: ``This is definitely an
out-of-body experience. I'm going to wake up tomorrow and not
believe this.''
</P>
<P>
   The game evolved into a battle between UCLA's McNown and Miami's
Covington and running back Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   McNown accounted for six touchdowns, five by passing. He
completed 26 of 35 passes for 513 yards, with his touchdowns going,
in order, for 77, 7, 14, 61 and 59 yards. He also scored on a
1-yard option run.
</P>
<P>
   James was equally as spectacular for Miami. With the backup
running back James Jackson suspended for an undisclosed team
violation, James had to do yeoman work. And he did _ rushing 39
times for a school and Big East record 299 yards. He scored three
times, on runs of 45 yards, 10 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA probably came in here thinking they were going to win
easy,'' James said. ``But they didn't understand what this program
is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   James' last score, with 50 seconds left, proved the game-winner.
It came after a disputed lost fumble by UCLA receiver Brad Melsby
at the Miami 26-yard line with 3 minutes 24 seconds remaining, with
the Bruins ready to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes then went 74 yards in eight plays to beat only
their second ranked opponent in nine tries under Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time this year we got to use the Orange Bowl
heat to our advantage,'' Covington said. ``We got to grinding them
down and I saw a lot of poise on that last drive.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA wasn't finished. It quickly moved deep into Miami
territory, as the drama thickened and the crowd's noise level
reached deafening proportions. McNown had two final chances from
the Miami 29, and both passes fell incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bennett saw McNown's last pass slip through his grasp in
the end zone as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's James had 173 yards rushing by halftime, as the
Hurricanes built a 21-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta Bowl executive director John Junker took the occasion to
hark back to a sequence that had dramatically changed the Bruins'
game against ranked Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored 21 points almost before you could blink,'' Junker
said. ``With their offense, that could happen again here, and it'll
be interesting to see if Miami can overcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Junker envisioned indeed unfolded in the second half. The
Bruins scored twice in the third quarter in five plays and added
another touchdown by quarter's end to seemingly assure a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Hurricanes on this day had more resilience than they've
shown since their championship runs of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing,'' Davis said at the end, flashing a wide
smile. ``We made 6.5 million people in Kansas happy today.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's loss opened the door for Kansas State now to play
Tennessee for the national championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
