<HEADER>
A4858 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-NYT &LR;      12-05 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS' NEW LEADER IS SEEN AS A CONTRADICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: TEAMSTERS-RDP)  
(rl) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like his famous _ many would say infamous _ father, James P.
Hoffa, the newly elected president of the International Brotherhood
of Teamsters, is a contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Hoffa is a genial, well-to-do lawyer who lives in
suburban comfort and lacks his father's powerful build. He has
become a hero to many Teamsters with his vow to clean up a union
embarrassed by a campaign-finance scandal under its previous
president, Ron Carey. Yet many of Hoffa's mentors and allies are
under investigation or have had run-ins with the law.
</P>
<P>
   The question _ the same one that swirls around his father's
reputation to this day _ is which Hoffa will emerge to lead the
Teamsters. To the new Teamsters president, the answer is clear. He
talks about how he aims to reunite a union that has been torn by a
near civil war between his supporters and those of Carey.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledges to restore the union's financial health. Under
Carey its assets plunged from $150 million to nearly zero, leaving
its strike fund depleted. He also promises to do more organizing to
regain some of the union's membership, which has fallen to 1.4
million from 2.3 million two decades ago. Hoffa wants to organize
truck drivers, hospital workers and public employees.
</P>
<P>
   But his opponents have repeatedly pointed out questions about
the younger Hoffa's links. In the late 1960s, Hoffa was an investor
in a partnership with Allen Dorfman, a friend of his father and
leading organized crime figure who funneled tens of millions of
dollars from Teamster pension funds to the Mafia. Although Dorfman
was well known as a mob figure, Hoffa denied knowing that Dorfman
was tied to organized crime, and he said he sold his investment as
soon as he found out.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Hoffa sought to run for the Teamsters presidency, but
he was told he could not because he was not working as a union
member. To qualify, he took a job as administrative assistant to
Larry Brennan, head of the Teamsters in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan played a major role in running a union welfare fund at a
time when federal Department of Labor officials found $725,000 in
improper expenses, including spending on golf outings and adult
entertainment. Federal monitors have criticized Brennan for giving
union subordinates more than $30,000 in raises that were
immediately sent to his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Similar _ if more serious _ allegations dogged Hoffa's father,
James Riddle Hoffa, who headed the union from 1957 to 1971, an era
when lawmakers termed the Teamsters a national menace. The elder
Hoffa's union was widely considered the most corrupt in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy and his brother, Attorney General Robert
Kennedy, began the pursuit of Hoffa, with more than two dozen
investigators, in what has been called the largest and longest
investigation of an individual. Hoffa was convicted of fraud and
jury tampering, and prosecutors tied him to everything from relying
on Mafia muscle in contract disputes to helping divert millions of
dollars from pension funds to his mob friends.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, after being released from jail, Hoffa disappeared in
what investigators say was a gangland rubout.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Teamsters ranging from truck drivers to vegetable packers
worshipped the elder Hoffa for turning their union into the
nation's strongest and largest, for winning them pension benefits,
and for helping double and even triple their wages. This workers'
hero was the most famous union leader of his time, and his son is
uncompromising in defending his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Hoffa denied that his father had any ties to
organized crime, insisting he was framed by the Kennedys and
overzealous prosecutors. He also angrily rejected assertions from
Carey and from his main opponent in this year's race, Tom Leedham,
that he would be like his father and let mob influence expand in
the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing,'' Hoffa said in an interview last
year, is that ``my father was, I believe, murdered by the mob. The
mob will never come back into the Teamsters union. I will see to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In several interviews over the past year, Hoffa has been eager
to discuss anything but allegations of corruption, especially those
that swirled around his father. ``The Hoffa name is revered in this
union,'' he said. ``My father's the pioneer who put this union on
the march.''
</P>
<P>
   James Phillip Hoffa was born in Detroit on May 19, 1941. He
remembers going to dozens of union meetings with his father and
standing in front of the fire barrel with him during strikes.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Cooley High School in Detroit, where he was an
all-state football player, and in 1963 he graduated from Michigan
State, where he was a starter on both the offensive and defensive
lines. He went to the University of Michigan Law School, where he
was a classmate of Dick Gephardt, the House Democratic leader. He
and his wife, Virginia, have two grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   After law school, he often represented Teamster locals that were
close to his father. Other lawyers in Detroit said he was a
talented litigator who eventually was able to drum up plenty of
business without depending on those links.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's campaign, Hoffa also seemed to be trying to carve
his own path. His forces relied on Republicans in Congress to
embarrass Carey, and now, Hoffa said, the Teamsters will no longer
be reflexively pro-Democratic, as they were under Carey. Yet while
Hoffa said the Teamsters would begin supporting some Republicans _
he mentioned Rep. Peter King of Long Island in particular _ he
described himself as a progressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to support politicians that share our vision for
America,'' he said. ``That is a working man's agenda, which is to
promote full employment, good jobs for this country, that is
against exportation of jobs and one that supports reforming the
labor laws that favor employers.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his campaign, Hoffa also promised to move power back
to union locals and regional Teamster councils. That was popular
with the many Teamster chieftains who supported him, but his
opponent, Leedham, insisted that giving local barons more power was
a recipe for them to steal more money.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Hoffa seems to be rethinking plans to send
power back to the locals. ``I'm not running for this job to give
the power back to anybody,'' he said last month. ``We're going to
provide leadership. People will rally to somebody who wants to
lead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
