<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW `PSYCHO' NOT BAD, BUT THE ORIGINAL DWARFS IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people have already made up their mind about Gus Van Sant's
remake of Alfred Hitchcock's Psycho. Their reactions range from
``Is Van Sant nuts?'' to near-apoplexy over Van Sant's nerve in
remaking a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, you just wanna tell these people to close their eyes,
breathe deeply and repeat to themselves, ``It's only a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And although the new ``Psycho'' is not an abomination, its main
problem is that it IS only a movie; it's not going to jolt the
cinematic landscape like the 1960 original. Hitchcock broke rules
regarding sex, violence and the leading lady, and left audiences
shook up; Van Sant breaks rules of remakes, changing very little,
and leaves audiences scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   As publicized, the movie is a virtual shot-for-shot remake; Van
Sant is so slavish in places, he even uses the same license-plate
numbers as the original. And although some of Van Sant's shots are
just as dazzling as Hitchcock's, it's because they are Hitchcock's.
You gotta admit, it's hard to knock this movie's direction, script
or score, because for the most part they're just as good as the
original's _ because they are the original's.
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant does make good use of some tools that Hitchcock didn't
or couldn't use, though. The primary reason to see this movie in a
theater is its use of sound; Van Sant employs an unsettling mix of
nearly inaudible whispers and boosted background noises whenever
something creepy is about to happen, and the voice-overs bounce all
over the theater, echoing and overlapping till you feel as if the
characters are sitting next to you. Van Sant also uses color well _
it's been a strength of even his lousiest movies _ flattening it
out to the point that the movie actually looks as if it was filmed
in the '60s, and dressing his stars in tones that reflect their
characters' personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The shadows of the original loom largest over the cast,
especially Vince Vaughn, trying mightily to fill Anthony Perkins'
shoes as Norman Bates. Vaughn's performance is uneven; you get the
sense that his Norman feels more guilty about all the bloodshed,
but in Norman's more ``normal'' moments, Vaughn doesn't convince
you that Anne Heche's Marion Crane could trust him enough to eat
one of his sandwiches. Heche fares better, playing Marion in a much
warmer way than Janet Leigh did, her impulsive decisions making
more sense in this context. Viggo Mortensen is too mannered as
Marion's lover, and Julianne Moore is too butch as Marion's sister,
but William H. Macy is easily Martin Balsam's equal as the private
eye who gets involved when Marion disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the original could stand some tweaking, but Van
Sant tweaks in the wrong places. Most critics agree that the
psychiatrist scene near the end is the original's weakest element,
but it remains intact here; so does Marion and Norman's dinner
conversation, which goes on far too long. Van Sant saves his
indulgences for the killings (which still look almost quaint
compared with most of today's fare), adding Van Sant-ish touches
such as quick edits of passing clouds or of a cow standing in a
road as the knife comes down. It's odd that he picked the
original's most effective parts to toy with.
</P>
<P>
   But then, his whole movie is odd. He defends it as a tribute, as
something nobody has done before, adding that people remake songs
and plays all the time, and nobody seems to get upset. But those
remakes are often best when they're reinterpretations; Van Sant may
be paying tribute here, but he's done it by reinterpreting a
classic as a curiosity piece.
</P>
<P>
   Psycho is rated R for violence, nudity and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
