<HEADLINE>
TOCCHET REBORN AS COYOTE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ A look at the standings going into the weekend showed
Phoenix and Toronto tied for the NHL lead in points with 30. Not
Philadelphia, not Detroit, not Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   What's most remarkable is the emergence of the Coyotes, who went
into the weekend with a 14-3-2 rec-ord and were 8-1-1 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's obvious to point out the seasons Keith Tkachuk and
Jeremy Roenick are having, the real surprise is the rejuvenation of
former Bruin Rick Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet, 34, played a total of 67 games with the Bruins in the
1995-96 and 1996-97 seasons, a time when the club had hit rock
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was miserable for everyone in Boston; the team was
going nowhere, and Tocchet was happy as heck to get out of Dodge in
the form of a trade to Washington that also involved Adam Oates and
Bill Ranford and brought Jason Allison, Anson Carter, and Jim
Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Now everybody is happy. The Bruins are worlds better, Tocchet
opted for free agency after 1996-97 and signed with the Coyotes,
and Washington went to the finals last season partly on the
strength of -Oates's play. Funny how it all works out.
</P>
<P>
   When Tocchet was here, he looked to be on the downside of his
career. His body had a lot of miles on it, he had a history of back
and shoulder problems, and the end appeared to be near.
</P>
<P>
   But Tocchet has been reborn in the desert climate (who wouldn't
be, when you think about it?). Going into the weekend, he was third
on the team in scoring with 19 points in 19 games. He had eight
goals, 46 penalty minutes, and was a plus-11.
</P>
<P>
   Before having back surgery four years ago, Tocchet seemed to be
finishing his career as a journeyman, going from team to team on
his way to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people said _ you can't blame them, really,''
Tocchet said. ``If you're struggling like I was, you just have to
believe in yourself. For me, the health part of it, my back, has
been pretty much everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet's offense tailed off dramatically from the time he put
up 109 points with Pittsburgh in 1992-93. In the two seasons he
spent partly with Boston, he tallied 60 points and 40 points. Last
year, in his first complete season with the Coyotes, he had 45
points, 26 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Tocchet didn't last here was that he's the
type of player who thrives in an environment where there's a great
deal of support. He doesn't have to be The Man in Phoenix. The
Coyotes have Tka-chuk, Roenick, Teppo Numminen, and Nikolai
Khabibulin for that.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in his career, Tocchet is much more comfortable in
a secondary role. In Boston, he was expected to do much more than
he did. In the pickle the Bruins were in, it wasn't going to matter
much either way, which was a frustrating situation for both player
and management.
</P>
<P>
   If you look back over his career, Tocchet's best seasons have
been on teams with an abundance of talent. The ideal time for him
to have been a Bruin would've been around the 1988-90 seasons. It
didn't happen. But now, Tocchet is in a perfect situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm proud of is I've worked very hard to get back to
where I am,'' Tocchet said. ``It's taken me a lot of summers to get
to where I can compete, where I can be a good player again. Hey, I
make a lot of money, so I'm not complaining, but I made a
commitment that if I was going down, I was going down swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet, who once looked ready for the old-age home, is now
talking about playing for several more years. His contract expires
in July and he has an option for a third year. An extension didn't
seem remotely possible a couple of years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have laughed, too,'' he said. ``I was rolling the
dice. Now I feel like the ball is in my court and I think I can
still compete. Who knows? The thing is, I think I can, and that's
not a road I was looking down a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One can't help but shudder at the comments of Tampa Bay owner
 &UR; Art Williams &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who seems the personification of the old adage
that a little knowledge is a dangerous thing. After watching his
injury-riddled club lose its eighth game in a row, Williams lashed
out. ``I can't explain it,'' he said. ``I don't know if we've got a
bunch of pansies on this team. Maybe it's a lack of confidence or
maybe some of our guys are playing just for the money. For whatever
reason, we can't seem to give a full 60 minutes of effort. I refuse
to sit there and cater to an overpriced bunch of crybabies. This
season has been a brutal lesson for me. I was told we were a few
players away from a competitive team so I willingly spent even more
money than we budgeted. So far, it's really been discouraging.''
Call me crazy, but comments like that are not going to help the
situation. Williams admits he knows nothing about hockey. His
energy would be better spent learning the game than belittling his
employees. Williams, reportedly a terrific businessman and
otherwise good guy, apparently forgot one of the oldest bits of
advice with regard to purchasing pro teams or anything else:
``Caveat emptor.'' ... Our favorite trade rumor of the week:
Colorado dealing pesky  &UR; Claude Lemieux  &LR; to Washington for
defenseman  &UR; Mark Tinordi &LR; . Imagine Lemieux,  &UR; Dale Hunter &LR; , &UR; Craig
Berube &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Chris Simon  &LR; on the same team. Now, if they could
only find a way to get  &UR; Ulf Samuelsson  &LR; and  &UR; Shayne Corson  &LR; ...
 &UR; Grant Fuhr  &LR; is something of a medical marvel. He's practicing with
the Blues barely a month after injuring his groin. Original reports
had Fuhr out as long as eight weeks. ``There's the medical schedule
and then there's my schedule,'' said Fuhr. Boston-based  &UR; Jay
Fee &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the player's agent, joked a few weeks back that Fuhr said he
expected to be out ``2-8 weeks.'' ... Word out of Florida is that
general manager  &UR; Bryan Murray  &LR; was perturbed when Buffalo goalie
 &UR; Dominik Hasek  &LR; shed his equipment last Saturday in protest of a
call. Murray thought that Hasek, as the league's MVP the last two
years, should act better. As great a goalie as Hasek is, he's the
same guy who attacked a reporter because he didn't like what the
scribe had written about him. Volatile is not too strong a word to
describe him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Doug Gilmour  &LR; said he has no regrets about signing with Chicago
as a free agent despite the club's many woes. Gilmour could've
stayed with the Devils or gone to Buffalo or any number of other
clubs who are having much better seasons than the Blackhawks, one
of the worst teams in the Western Conference. ``I'm exactly where I
want to be,'' said Gilmour, who signed a three-year, $18 million
deal last summer. ``Obviously, I didn't expect us to have the start
we've had. No one did. So it's been frustrating and disappointing
at times. But have I thought it was a mistake? No, not a chance.
That would be like quitting. That would be the biggest copout in
the whole world.'' ...  &UR; Bernie Nicholls &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 37, was cut by the
Sharks last month, but rather than try to play for another club, he
has accepted a job as assistant coach with San Jose ... Calgary
goalie  &UR; Ken Wregget  &LR; has been on a long, frustrating road to
recovery from back woes. He injured himself Nov. 3 against Detroit
and tried to come back too soon, worsening things. His condition is
said to be similar to the one that limited him to 15 appearances
with Pittsburgh last year, but Wregget said, ``It is not
career-ending. It is not season-ending. It is just taking a long
time.'' ...  &UR; Brad May &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who had nine goals in 27 games last year
after being dealt to the Canucks, has fallen off offensively, with
only one goal in 19 games. Bad luck has been a part of it, he said.
``In Philly, I had a breakaway, made the right move, and the puck
rolled off my stick,'' said May. ``In Boston, I had a great shot
that should have gone in. Another time, we got a shot on net, I was
right there for the rebound and it bounced 2 feet behind me the
other way. They have to start going in.'' ... As big as hockey is
in Phoenix, it didn't succeed in Tucson. The West Coast Hockey
League's Gila Monsters were forced to cease operations because of a
lack of fan support ... There are plenty of people out there who
would love to drop a few pounds, but we can't recommend the
 &UR; Jean-Sebastian Giguere  &LR; diet. The Flames netminder loses an
average of 10 pounds a game from excessive sweating. Last year, he
was playing for the Saint John Flames of the American Hockey League
and lost 19 pounds in one game. He became ill and had to be rushed
to the hospital because of dehydration. During training camp, team
doctors ran a battery of tests on the 21-year-old goalie. He donned
his pads and rode the stationary bike hard, trying to replicate the
sweating he would do in a game. They found out he was taking in too
much air along with the fluids he was drinking and they weren't
being absorbed properly. Now, Giguere takes nourishment through a
straw, which seems to help. ``This feels good right now,'' he said.
``I never feel bad after a game. I feel hungry. I sleep better.
Last year, I could not eat. I could not sleep after a game because
my stomach was all full from the water and the air.'' ... Former
Boston University standout  &UR; Jay Pandolfo &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who struggled under
former Devils coach  &UR; Jacques Lemaire  &LR; and bounced back and forth
from the minors, appears to be flourishing under new coach  &UR; Robbie
Ftorek &LR; . Pandolfo, who no doubt has gained some maturity in the
last couple of years, is playing on the checking line with  &UR; Bobby
Carpenter  &LR; and  &UR; Brian Rolston  &LR; but is also more involved in the
offense. He is fourth on the team in scoring with 12 points ...
Before Toronto played Sunday night against the Canadiens, goalie
 &UR; Felix Potvin  &LR; was given permission to arrive in Montreal early to
take care of family matters, but it fueled speculation that he is
about to be dealt, likely to Tampa Bay ... Speaking of Tampa Bay,
49 days to the All-Star Game.
</P>
</TEXT>
