<SLUG> BC-YALE-GERMANY-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE STUDENT FROM GERMANY FOUND STABBED TO DEATH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ A Yale University senior was found stabbed to
death Friday night a mile and a half from campus.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Suzanne Jovin, a 21-year-old political science
major from Goettingen, Germany, was stabbed more than 17 times in
the head and chest. The police found her body at Edgehill Avenue
and East Rock Road, and she was pronounced dead in the emergency
room at Yale-New Haven Hospital at 10:26 p.m. The police said they
had not determined a motive, but Michael Kuzckowski, press
secretary for Mayor John DeStefano Jr., told The Associated Press:
``Early indications show that this is not a random event.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first killing of a Yale student in New Haven since
1991, when Christian Prince, a sophomore from Chevy Chase, Md., was
found shot to death on Hillhouse Avenue at the base of the steps of
St. Mary's Church on the Yale campus. After Prince's death,
applications to Yale were down 9.5 percent for the 1991-92 school
year.
</P>
<P>
   The area where Ms. Jovin was found, a popular route for joggers,
is known as a safe area for students who venture off campus. ``It
gave me a really eerie feeling, especially when it's a place people
are encouraged to go out to get away from campus,'' said Thao Tran,
a sophomore from San Jose, Calif. `It's supposed to be really nice
and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you think it could have been you,'' added Christopher
Deutsch, a sophomore from Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Students who knew Ms. Jovin talked about her energy, enthusiasm
and kindness. An hour before she was killed, she was making pizzas
for disabled people at a New Haven church. Ms. Jovin ran a program
at Yale called Best Buddies that organizes activities between
students and disabled people. She left the church about 9 p.m. and
returned a Yale van to its campus parking lot, said Daniel Koehler,
a junior who participates in the Best Buddies program.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a tremendous person,'' Koehler said. ``She was just
really enthusiastic, and I'm going to miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is planned by Yale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
