<HEADLINE>
CHEERS FOR GORDON AT FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ Jeff Gordon's victory in the Farm Aid on CMT 300 at
New Hampshire International Speedway Aug. 30, the second of two
annual New England whistlestops on the NASCAR Winston Cup series,
was typical of the season he had in winning his third series
championship in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Lustily booed during the driver introductions at NHIS, Gordon
drove his No. 24 Dupont-sponsored Chevrolet Monte Carlo to Victory
Lane, where he was greeted by more boos and accusations from his
competitors at Roush Racing that Gordon's team tampered with tire
pressure and cheated its way to the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   That scene seemed to play itself out at almost every race he won
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen times Gordon withstood the criticism of his
competitors, endured the scrutiny of NASCAR officials, and turned a
deaf ear to the growing crescendo from a resentful faction of
anti-Gordon fans, and he got the last laugh simply by winning it
all in NASCAR's 50th anniversary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best way to fight criticism and, you know, to make
things quiet,'' Gordon said. ``To me, that's what makes us such a
great team; whether we're being criticized, or whether we've got
the pressure on us, we always find a way to step up to that
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In a year in which super teams dominated the NBA and Major
League Baseball, another emerged in NASCAR, delivering Hendrick
Motorsports its fourth consecutive Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Gordon's colleagues paid homage to that
sustained excellence at NASCAR's Awards Banquet at the
Waldorf-Astoria. Though he appeared to be the most scorned man at
the track this season, there was no disputing his talent or
begrudging him his due rewards. When he took center stage in the
grand ballroom, Gordon seemed to ascend to a new level of stardom,
especially since he had tied Richard Petty's record for wins in a
season with his 13th in the season finale at Atlanta Motor
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a year like we had this year is something that really
gets me going (for next year),'' said Gordon, 27, the youngest
driver to win three Winston Cup championships and the winner of a
record $9,306,584 this year. ``It was one of the funnest years I've
had driving a race car. It just blows me away that we're having
this kind of success as a team, at this high level of
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   To cap his championship season, Gordon was unanimously selected
by a panel of 15 media members as Driver of the Year. He joined
Mario Andretti and Darrell Waltrip as the only three-time honorees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even comprehend having my name in the same sentence as
Mario Andretti,'' said Gordon. ``Growing up in Indiana, I remember
watching him at Indy, and, in the last 6-7 years, getting to know
Darrell Waltrip. It's an honor, and to do it three times with those
guys is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   What was the highlight of his season?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the unique thing of this season, and it's that there
was never just one thing, one highlight, one thing that stuck out
in my mind,'' said Gordon. ``It was a combination of things. I
mean, I can go on and on, but you look at our first win at Michigan
... winning the Brickyard 400 for the second time ... the fourth
Southern 500 ... Atlanta ... both road courses (at Watkins Glen,
N.Y., and Sears Point, Calif.) ... I could go on and on. Those were
all the things that made it the year that it was, that made it so
special and made it so spectacular for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Motor Speedway president  &UR; Tony George  &LR; always said
it was his dream to bring Formula One racing back to American soil.
Last Wednesday, George realized that dream by landing a Formula One
race for 2000 on his 2.5-mile parcel of property at 16th and
Georgetown in Indianapolis. The fabled Brickyard, which will
undergo extensive renovations to the infield to accommodate a
1-mile, 13-turn course, would seem to be a perfect venue for F1's
first race in the US since a poorly attended event at Phoenix in
1991. But some purists fear that the US Grand Prix, combined with
the wildly successful NASCAR event at Indy, will further dilute the
prestige and spectacle of what for almost 82 years was the
Brickyard's only event: the Indy 500. Back in August, when he
presided over the Indy Racing League's final visit to NHIS, George
expressed a strong desire to land an F1 event. ``It's something
I've been interested in for quite some time to bring to
Indianapolis,'' he said then. ``I think we have a good plan and a
good venue to offer for the long term and the viability and
survivability of such a race.'' While no date has been set, George
indicated that FIA officials ``have a plan to change things the way
they schedule the season. They're thinking of scheduling the Asian
races and Australian races in the early part of the season, the
European races in the middle part of the season, and the American
races _ Canada, US, Argentina, Brazil _ towards the end of the
season. My preference would be to run sometime in late September.
It gives us plenty of time between the Brickyard 400 and our
(Senior PGA) golf tournament in early September. I think the
weather's generally good in the Midwest that time of year, it can
be very pleasant. How late could we go? I don't know, maybe late
October. It's really dependent on how the rest of the schedule
falls out.'' ... Open-wheel racing saw one great driver,  &UR; Bobby
Rahal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; retire this year and will see another,  &UR; Arie
Luyendyk &LR; , &UR;  &LR; do the same next year after the Indy 500. Luyendyk, a
two-time winner of the event, plans to call it quits after the 83d
Indy 500. Rahal, the 1986 Indy 500 winner, called it a career after
completing his ``Last Ride'' tour with an 11th-place finish in the
FedEx CART season finale at California Speedway. Rahal, who tabbed
 &UR; Max Papis  &LR; as his successor, will remain head of the two-car
operation he co-owns with late-night host  &UR; David Letterman &LR; . ``I
think the biggest thing I feel is just the enormity of turning a
page in my life,'' said Rahal, a three-time CART champion and
veteran of 285 career starts and 24 victories. ``I don't feel
melancholy or sadness or joy necessarily. What I feel is just a
long chapter in my life is over and now a new chapter has started.
Where that chapter will take me I have no idea. I'd like to be a
positive influence on open-wheel racing.'' ...  &UR; Bobby Labonte  &LR; was
all smiles at the NASCAR Awards Banquet for two reasons: He
finished sixth in points with 4,146, his career best effort, and he
finished three spots ahead of his older brother,  &UR; Terry &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was
ninth (3,759). The brothers started the 1998 season side by side on
the front row of the Daytona 500, Bobby on the pole and Terry on
the outside.
</P>
</TEXT>
