<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COWBOYS-JEFFERS-T     12-05 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COWBOYS-JEFFERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' JEFFERS LIVING OUT A BOYHOOD DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. John and Sarah Jeffers have a photo of their 5-year-old son
Patrick in a Cowboys sweatshirt. And they have one of 10-year-old
Patrick sitting in his dorm room at the Cowboys football camp.
</P>
<P>
   Now 25, Patrick Jeffers has had a few snapshots of fame in his
first three months as a receiver for the Cowboys. As he takes the
field today in New Orleans as a growing weapon in the Cowboys
offense, he has become the poster child for an entire community.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Williams' third-grade class at Fort Worth Country Day
School adorns a bulletin board with newspaper stories and pictures
of Jeffers, one of the school's now-famous graduates. Dr. John
Jeffers' office in Arlington greets callers with updates on their
favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Dr. John Jeffers. ``Nobody could have
predicted this. And people in my office think he's their son. My
nurse gets calls and the first thing they want to talk about is
Patrick, even before they say what is wrong. I have to spend five
minutes answering questions about him before I can give care to my
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before Jeffers, who was traded to the Cowboys from
Denver roughly three months ago, romped down the field with a
67-yard touchdown pass against the Minnesota Vikings on
Thanksgiving Day. That prompted a horde of phone calls to his
parents' home and had Country Day coach Joe Breedlove jumping out
of his chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were screaming and yelling in our living room, I was
thinking that every household that was affiliated with Country Day
was doing the same thing,'' Breedlove said. ``You get tickled all
the time. You find yourself looking for him on the field, looking
for his number on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jeffers' mother Sarah: ``One lady called and said, `We knew
him when he was still in diapers.' Now they have a new reason to
get excited about the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   With every catch he's made, seemingly with every practice,
Patrick Jeffers seems to get more excited about playing for his
hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big thrill,'' Jeffers said. ``I was a big Cowboys fan
my whole life. To come back and play with a star on my helmet is a
dream come true. That's what it's like every day ... it's like
living a dream.''
No doctoring for him
Jeffers fantasized about the Cowboys growing up, talking with his
roommate at the Cowboys-sponsored football camp. That happened to
be childhood friend Blake Brockermeyer, a former Arlington Heights
offensive tackle who now plays for the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers comes from a football family. Sarah is the matriarch,
who gained her intense football knowledge dates back to her days
growing up watching Auburn with her father. When Patrick played
college football at Virginia, Sarah was known to scream to coach
George Welsh from the stands to get her son the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers' older sister Allison Dooley, a doctor at Parkland
Hospital in Dallas, is married to SMU assistant football coach
Derek Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, football wasn't his favorite sport and his goal
wasn't to become a professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a doctor like my dad,'' Jeffers said. ``He
would come get me when I was little and take me to the hospital. I
would follow him around. He was my role model. I wanted to follow
in his footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, soccer topped his list of athletic endeavors. Jeffers
played soccer from the time he could walk and proved to be one of
the top talents in the area, making several select all-star teams
and playing year-round.
</P>
<P>
   There, however, was never a question about Jeffers' athletic
ability, according to his older brother Rich, who lives in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was evident early on that he was going to be a good
athlete,'' Rich said. ``He was always taller and faster than
everybody. And he just kept on growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers, who said he eventually grew tired of soccer, starred in
football, soccer and track in high school at Country Day and had
his No. 22 retired this past year. A two-time all-Southern
Preparatory Conference wide receiver, Jeffers' initial dream was to
just play major-college football.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dream that he almost didn't realize. Recruiters snubbed
him following his senior year because of a perceived ``lack of
competition'' at Country Day. A stellar student, Jeffers nearly
took an offer to play at Princeton before deciding to walk on at
the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 218-pound receiver quickly erased any doubts about
his ability to play Division I football by becoming a starter as a
redshirt freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could tell right away he was a good prospect,'' Welsh said.
``He was big, he could run, he could catch. It was hard to explain
how schools in Texas could miss on somebody like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He led the team in receptions and scored six touchdowns as a
sophomore. Only then did he begin to think playing in the NFL was
an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just started building from there,'' Jeffers said. ``Every
year the scouts came down to look at the seniors. And the coaches
told me to keep working because I was getting some notice.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished at Virginia fourth on the school's all-time receiver
list with 108 receptions for 1,785 yards and 15 touchdowns. The
Broncos took him in fifth round of the 1996 draft.
Painter steps in
Jeffers said he loved the experience of being part of last season's
Super Bowl title team with the Denver Broncos. However, nagging
injuries thwarted his growth as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Broncos said they loved his potential, he was
inactive for 28 games, played mostly on special teams and caught
only three passes for 24 yards during his first two years there.
</P>
<P>
   Another injury during training camp this season and the presence
of other quality receivers prompted Broncos coach Mike Shanahan to
make what he told Cowboys owner Jerry Jones was one of the
``toughest decisions'' he ever had in cutting Jeffers.
</P>
<P>
   However, before the Broncos made the move, Cowboys receivers
coach Dwain Painter, who coached Jeffers with the Broncos in 1997,
urged Cowboys coach Chan Gailey and Jones to intervene. The Cowboys
acquired Jeffers in a trade the week of the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you look for in a receiver is size, speed and playing
strength in addition to being able to catch,'' Painter said. ``Pat
had all that in Denver. Unfortunately, he got nicked up a bit and
got caught up in a numbers game. We're glad to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers went about his business of learning the new offense,
resulting in him being inactive for eight of the first nine games
and causing his bursting-with-pride mother to grow increasingly
antsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience is not my strong suit,'' Sarah said. ``I know
training camp was over, and they didn't have time to teach. Patrick
would kill me if I said anything.''
</P>
<P>
   What mother didn't know was that Jeffers was quietly catching
the Cowboys' attention with his play on the scout team and
improving his skills by working against All-Pro cornerback Deion
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be amazed how much we learn about a guy from what he
does on the scout team,'' Gailey said. ``We saw Pat make catch
after catch after catch. Then we started putting him in our
offense. And he continued to make plays and develop very well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jeffers finally got a chance to play against the Arizona
Cardinals on Nov. 15, he continued to impress, catching his first
pass with the Cowboys. Injuries helped expand his role the
following week, and he doubled his output with two receptions for
40 yards, including a 21-yarder to set up a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for his performance against the Vikings,
which he calls the highlight of his career. He caught three passes
for 92 yards and the first touchdown of his NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers' play has resulted in frequent comparisons to Broncos
receiver Ed McCaffrey, who is also tall at 6-5, sure-handed and
perceived to be slow. Jeffers, who learned a lot from McCaffrey
when he was in Denver, said he has long way to go before he can be
put in McCaffrey's class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some similarities, which makes it natural for people
to try to compare,'' Jeffers said. ``But in no way am I Ed
McCaffrey. A lot of what he does I can use to help my game. I hope
I can get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers said both he and McCaffrey get a raw deal in the speed
department because of their long, loping strides.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a 6-5 guy running out there and naturally he's not
going to look as quick as a smaller guy whose feet are churning,''
Jeffers said. ``But the fact is that we are covering a lot more
ground with every stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers was so fast in high school that he never lost a race in
track, breaking the school records at Country Day in the 200 and
the 400 meters. He continued the unbeaten streak against the
Vikings with the 67-yard catch running away from Vikings cornerback
Jimmy Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I hear them talk about him being slow, I think to
myself `if they only new,' Rich said. ``But if it works to his
advantage, I'm all for it. I guess Hitchcock was surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   What Jeffers appreciated most was finally getting an
opportunity. Now he wants the dream to continue one day at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing changes for me,'' Jeffers said. ``I'm going to
continue to work hard and let the rest take care of itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
