<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS VS. SAINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORYLINES
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   How will the club stop the Saints' passing game?
</P>
<P>
   On any other week, Cowboys coaches wouldn't be concerned about
the Saints offense, ranked 23rd in passing. But this isn't any
other week. Unless a miracle happens, cornerback Deion Sanders
won't play because of a sprained left big toe. The other
cornerback, Kevin Smith, is out two to four weeks with a strained
muscle in his lower back. The club is in such dire straits that it
signed Larry Brown, its Super Bowl XXX most valuable player, to
help fill the void in the secondary. Brown may not start, but look
for him to play if Charlie Williams, Kevin Mathis and Terry Billups
struggle. Without a healthy Sanders, the Cowboys have allowed 984
yards passing and nine touchdowns through the air the last three
games.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to the Cowboys' running game?
</P>
<P>
   Against the Vikings, the Cowboys fell behind early and never
went back to the run as Emmitt Smith gained just 44 yards on 18
carries. Cowboys coach Chan Gailey blamed himself for the tepid
ground game, saying, ``I just didn't stick with it.'' Gailey will
have plenty of chances to stick to the running game today as the
Saints rank 17th in rush defense and have allowed 100 or more yards
rushing in four of the last five games.
</P>
<P>
   What can we expect from Troy Aikman?
</P>
<P>
   A whole lot. Aikman has passed for 959 yards and four touchdowns
in the last three games, leading the Cowboys to 101 points. He will
take on a Saints defense that is last against the pass, but
improved of late, holding five of their past seven opponents under
200 yards passing. Injuries to Ernie Mills (abdomen) and Jeff Ogden
(shoulder) limit Aikman's options, but he still has big-play
flanker Michael Irvin, who leads the team with 62 receptions for
868 yards, a 14-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   SAINTS
</P>
<P>
   How fired up will the Saints be?
</P>
<P>
   Caustic head coach Mike Ditka chewed out the Saints following
their 30-10 loss to the Dolphins last week, calling them a bunch of
cowards, and saying that he was, ``embarrassed for myself, for the
coaching staff, for the organization.'' Publicly, at least, the
Saints players have responded. Wide receiver Andre Hastings said,
``There's no such thing as giving up in my mind. I'd knock my mama
down to win. Now, I'll help pick her up, but I'll knock her down.''
Simply put, the Saints are desparate. After beginning the season
3-0, they have dropped seven of their last nine. They remain
mathematically alive for a playoff berth, so the Cowboys can expect
an inspired bunch for at least a half or so.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cowboys secondary banged up, who among the Saints wide
receivers could be expected to have a big game?
</P>
<P>
   Sean Dawkins is the Saints' most explosive receiver, and that's
explosive compared to rest of the talent on his team. Dawkins has
just 39 receptions for 651 yards. The other receiver, Andre
Hastings, has 25 for 271. That is 64 combined receptions from the
Saints' top two pass catchers. In comparison, the Cowboys' Michael
Irvin has 62 receptions. Still, Dawkins has shown flashes of
brilliance this season. He had five receptions for 110 yards
against the Panthers on Sept. 13, six for 102 against the Panthers
on Nov. 1, and eight for 148 against the 49ers on Nov. 22. Rookie
Cameron Cleeland is a threat with 35 receptions for 498 yards and a
team-leading four receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Saints' defense do anything to stop the Cowboys'
high-powered offense?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, but they'll try. They rank 17th against the rush,
and 30th against the pass. Last week they saw their streak of
recording a sack in 60 consecutive games end in a 30-10 loss to the
Dolphins. Even with the horrific pass defense, the Saints, oddly,
lead the NFC with 18 interceptions. Safety Sammy Knight has as many
interceptions (5) as the Cowboys' Deion Sanders. Cornerback Tyronne
Drakeford and safety Chad Cota each have four. Safety Rob Kelly
returned a Dan Marino pass 79 yards for a touchdown last week. The
Saints will need more of that to stay in it against Troy Aikman and
company.
</P>
<P>
   ONES TO STOP
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Michael Irvin
</P>
<P>
   Since his streak of games with at least one reception ended at
117, Irvin has been on a tear the past two weeks. He has 18
receptions for 235 yards. He hasn't had a touchdown in a month, but
that could change as the Saints have allowed seven in the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Saints
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kerry Collins
</P>
<P>
   He is 2-0 lifetime against the Cowboys. Of course, both of those
wins came when he was with the Carolina Panthers. Since he joined
the Saints on Oct. 14, he has made three starts. He passed for 150
yards in his first start, 328 in his second, and 110 in his third.
The Cowboys will pressure him to make sure he does not continue his
roller coaster ride with a good performance today.
</P>
<P>
   THE EDGE
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys run offense vs. Saints run defense
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Despite rushing for only 58 yards against the Vikings last week,
the Cowboys' ground game has been pretty consistent. They have
rushed for at least 120 yards in six of the past seven games.
Saints linebacker Mark Fields leads the club with 85 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys pass offense vs. Saints pass defense
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman has averaged 320 yards passing in his past three
games and continues to be one of the best in the game. His passer
rating (97.2) is fifth in the league. The Saints lead the NFC with
18 interceptions. Defensive end Joe Johnson leads the club with six
sacks, though he may not increase that total against Cowboys tackle
Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys run defense vs. Saints run offense
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have allowed just three 100-yard rushers all season,
and just one in the past eight games. The Saints' leading rusher
over the past three games is quarterback Kerry Collins, who has
outgained Lamar Smith 103 yards to 53.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys pass defense vs. Saints pass offense
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Even
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were forced to sign Larry Brown because of injuries
to Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith. Meanwhile, the pass rush has
generated just three sacks in the past two games. Kerry Collins has
one touchdown and five interceptions in three starts with the
Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Saints
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries, the Cowboys signed Tyrone Hughes last week
for kick-return duties. But he is not the player he was for the
Saints, who have Andre Hastings returning punts. Hastings is third
in the NFC, averaging 14 yards per return.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey has stayed cool during this recent rash of injuries
that threaten to undermine his club's development. New Orleans'
Mike Ditka tries to motivate with angry tirades and harsh words.
</P>
</TEXT>
