<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SEEKING OFFENSIVE PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ After reviewing game film, Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock couldn't find many problems with his team's performance
during a 4-1 loss to the Vancouver Canucks on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't put the puck in the net,'' said Hitchcock, even
though his team outshot the Canucks, 37-18.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock and assistant coaches, Rick Wilson and Doug Jarvis,
dissected the film at their Edmonton hotel yesterday in preparation
for the Stars' 7 o'clock meeting tonight with the Oilers. The
verdict: The team needs to maintain its consistency of the past
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have to increase our tenacity from the red line in,
but we created plenty of good scoring chances,'' Hitchcock said.
``We simply have to be able to convert those chances and not let a
team off the hook like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who have struggled with slow starts a few times this
season, tore into the Canucks, but had nothing to show for it after
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't let a team stay in a game like that or it'll
come back to haunt you,'' said winger Pat Verbeek, who misfired on
four prime scoring opportunities. ``We should have been up two or
three to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what do the Stars do to correct the problem? They took
yesterday off from skating and did off-ice workouts, but Hitchcock
said he wasn't considering any real changes in his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With Brett Hull expected to miss another game because of a sore
groin, Hitchcock likely will use Jamie Langenbrunner on a line with
Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen. However, Hitchcock did play Verbeek
with Modano for one period Friday night when he was trying to spark
the Stars' offense.
</P>
<P>
   The second line is expected to be Verbeek, Joe Nieuwendyk and
either Dan Keczmer or rookie Jason Botterill.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hrkac will center the third line of Mike Keane and Grant
Marshall. Brian Skrudland will center Dave Reid and Guy Carbonneau
on the fourth line. Unless, of course, Hitchcock changes his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well, but we're still looking at things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the absence of Hull should not create a
significant lack of offense. The Stars played without Hull last
season and were fourth in the NHL in scoring, averaging 3.1 goals
per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can score, and we're getting plenty of great chances,''
Verbeek said. ``It starts with me. I'm not missing \Rbad\S chances,
I'm missing on great ones. ... It's frustrating the heck out of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek has one goal and two points in the past 13 games and was
one of the culprits behind the Stars having 18 shots miss the net
against the Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers are not in any better shape. They're coming off a 2-1
loss Friday against struggling Tampa Bay after edging high-flying
Phoenix, 4-3, Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to set the tempo in your own building,'' Oilers coach
Ron Low said of his team's disappointing 6-6 record at Skyreach
Centre. ``The biggest \Rproblem\S right now is our best players
aren't playing like our best players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars know that feeling. If Verbeek and Modano and
Nieuwendyk and Sergei Zubov are stopped, it's difficult for the
Stars to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say there are certain players who are struggling, and
we do expect our scorers to score more,'' Hitchcock said. ``But
this is a problem we have to react to as a team. We have to be able
to convert our chances and not keep letting teams up. We have to
find ways to beat a good goalie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
