<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGEST WINNER WILL LOSE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the LPGA Player of the Year is honored Tuesday at
a luncheon in New York, she will receive only Rookie of the Year
hardware. Which is to say that Annika Sorenstam will walk away with
what Se Ri Pak deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam had another great campaign (four wins and the money
title), one that was capped by the first-ever sub-70 season scoring
average (69.99) in LPGA Tour history, and when all the numbers from
the various categories were crunched, the Swede had finished first
based on a points system. Nice and neat, yes. Fair and accurate,
no. Pak had a better season for two very good reasons: the
McDonald's LPGA Championship and the US Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Korean won both of those majors _
unquestion-ably the most coveted championships on the tour _ and
threw in two other victories. She had a round of 61 in the Jamie
Farr Kroger Classic the week after she won the Open and finished
second on the money list. But she also made a rookie mistake and
played too much, particularly right after her draining playoff win
at the Open in July, and her major wins thrust her into a scorching
spotlight the likes of which had not been seen in women's golf
since Nancy Lopez burst upon the scene two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The attention took its toll. On a return in late October to her
native Korea, where she is a national hero, Pak collapsed with
exhaustion and spent a few days in a hospital. Two weeks later, she
concluded the LPGA season with a whimper, finishing 25th in a field
of 30 at the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But her sparkling summer had long since made its case.
Unfortunately, a numbers system is oblivious to such factors.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, easily the Tour's top rookie, will be able to hold a trophy
Tuesday, but you'll excuse her if her embrace is half-empty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk to most players who have gone through qualifying school and
they will tell you it is unbearable pressure. Then there's  &UR; Allen
Doyle &LR; , who probably wonders what the big deal is. All he did
Friday was conclude four days of sparkling play (67-70-71-67) at
Grenelefe Golf &AMP; Tennis Resort in Haines City, Fla., to take
medalist honors at the final of Senior PGA Tour Qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   His victory was no shock, considering he earned $164,918 in just
six events after turning 50 in June. But what is stunning is the
fact that he also was medalist at PGA Tour School two years ago _
when he was 48. That led to a forgettable 1997 season on the PGA
Tour, but the plan all along was to polish his game in preparation
for what is now reality: The Norwood native, one of the premier
amateur players of his generation, can challenge for a chance to
win more money in one weekend than he could earn in a year of
selling buckets of balls at his driving range in La Grange, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Lendzion &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former pro at Quechee, Vt., who won twice
on the European Senior Tour this past summer and has teed it up
just about anywhere the game is played, had a decent start at
Grenelefe, but closed 74-75 and missed out by nine shots. Another
on the outside looking in was  &UR; Gary McCord &LR; , who was three back and
earned conditional status for 1999. Which is OK because his day job
_ analyst for CBS golf coverage _ pays handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither  &UR; Ben Crenshaw  &LR; (3-8-1) nor  &UR; Mark James  &LR; (8-15-1) has a
sparkling record in Ryder Cup competition, but their passion for
the event cannot be matched. They will captain the US and European
teams in September's matches at The Country Club in Brookline, and
as part of the buildup they were in town recently to meet the
press. James talked about his first Ryder Cup experience, 1977,
``which came a few months after  &UR; Tom Watson  &LR; and  &UR; Jack Nicklaus
 &LR; took apart the field at Turnberry.'' (Watson beat Nicklaus in
arguably the greatest British Open ever.) James, paired with  &UR; Tommy
Horton &LR; , &UR;  &LR; was a bit stunned when he saw the draw that first day at
Royal Lytham &AMP; St. Annes: Watson and Nicklaus would provide the
opposition. ``I thought it was a mismatch,'' said James, ``but we
only lost, 7 and 6 (actually, 5 and 4). Had one of them broken his
leg we would have had a chance.'' ... Reporters, obviously glancing
at the current standings that include names like  &UR; Sven
Struver &LR; , &UR; Robert Karlsson &LR; , &UR; Andrew Coltart &LR; , &UR; Patrik Sjoland &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and
 &UR; Pierre Fulke &LR; , &UR;  &LR; asked James several times about the possibility of
having so many rookies on his team. James was more than polite,
though he could not have been blamed had he laughed. After all, the
standings represent a handful of events and there are nearly three
dozen tournaments to be contested before the Top 10 places will be
secured. Players such as  &UR; Bernhard Langer &LR; , &UR; Jose Maria
Olazabal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Jesper Parnevik  &LR; will no doubt move up into view
soon enough ... If you would like to listen to the Crenshaw/James
media day, it is available at www.jkgolfpro.com ... Want to warm up
for the Ryder Cup? Well, the third edition of the Presidents Cup is
here. A US team led by  &UR; Tiger Woods &LR; , &UR; Mark O'Meara &LR; , &UR; David
Duval &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Davis Love  &LR; (ranked 1-2-3-4 in the world) is at Royal
Melbourne GC in Australia to take on the International Team, and if
you can adjust your schedule to the 16-hour time difference, it
should provide for better golf viewing than what the Silly Season
has been providing. ESPN will be live Thursday (4-8:30 p.m., then 9
p.m.-2 a.m.) and Friday (4-8:30 p.m.), but the CBS coverage
Saturday (1-6 p.m.) and Sunday (4-7 p.m.) will be tape delayed. The
International Team should get a boost from a nucleus of Aussies on
native soil _  &UR; Greg Norman, Steve Elkington, Craig Parry, Stuart
Appleby  &LR; _ and the presence of  &UR; Vijay Singh, Ernie Els,  &LR; and  &UR; Nick
Price  &LR; (still the world's best ball-striker) makes this a
formidable squad. But if depth means anything, the US has to be
considered a strong favorite because the dropoff to guys like  &UR; Mark
Calcavecchia, Scott Hoch, Hal Sutton,  &LR; and  &UR; John Huston  &LR; isn't
nearly as dramatic as what the International Team faces _  &UR; Greg
Turner, Shigeki Maruyama, Naomichi Ozaki,  &LR; and  &UR; Carlos Franco. &LR; 
Then again, recalling Valderrama and a certain singles win by the
supposedly overmatched  &UR; Costantino Rocca,  &LR; perhaps you can foresee
a scenario in which Franco is the hero. He certainly makes for a
great story, a 33-year-old journeyman who grew up in poverty in
Paraguay and has played mostly on the Japanese Tour. Franco is 40th
in the world rankings, ahead of  &UR; Brad Faxon, Thomas Bjorn, Paul
Azinger, Nick Faldo,  &LR; and a bunch of other guys you have heard of.
Proof that the rankings are not to be trusted, you say? Perhaps. Or
maybe Franco will prove more than worthy, as he did last month at
the final stage of PGA Tour School when he earned his card for 1999
by finishing in a tie for the 35th and final spot. If you relish
the true spirit of the game, Franco is your man _ a golfer from a
country with just a handful of courses and fewer than three dozen
professionals, a player who, in the final round of Q School, with
his livelihood at stake, started putting with his driver. No, the
putter was not broken. He told reporters he just wanted a change.
</P>
</TEXT>
