<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX LOSE CLARK TO BALTIMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tear up all the rejection slips accumulating on Yawkey
Way, and you'll probably have enough confetti for another Yankee
victory parade down New York's Canyon of Heroes.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Will Clark became the latest free agent to say
thanks but no thanks to the Red Sox, electing to take a two-year,
$11 million deal from the Baltimore Orioles, who apparently seized
the moment while Boston general manager Dan Duquette hesitated.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles closed the deal for Clark before the Red Sox
actually tendered an offer to the man to whom they had turned as a
potential short-term replacement for Mo Vaughn. Frank Wren, the
Orioles' new GM, placed a phone call to Clark's agent, Jeff Moorad,
as Wren was flying from Baltimore to Fort Lauderdale late Friday
night, then reportedly closed the deal from an airport rental car
counter.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had talked parameters of a deal, Moorad said, but
did not make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the process we assumed Will would end up with the Red
Sox,'' Moorad said Sunday. ``The Red Sox were clearly serious about
the player. But in the end, Frank Wren and the Orioles came on like
gangbusters and put the deal together in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' interest in Clark was sufficient enough that
Duquette had manager Jimy Williams place a call to Clark last
Monday. But Clark _ who in essence flip-flopped spots with Rafael
Palmeiro, as Palmeiro signed with Clark's former team, the Rangers
_ said he was impressed by a call from Orioles manager Ray Miller
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray made it apparent that the Orioles wanted me,'' said Clark.
``When you feel wanted, it makes you feel better about yourself and
it makes you play better.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Williams didn't make him feel wanted, too, but
the Orioles followed up their phone call with an offer and the Sox
did not.
</P>
<P>
   The list of free agents courted by the Sox who decided to go
elsewhere began with Albert Belle, peaked with Bernie Williams, and
includes Palmeiro, Clark, and Robin Ventura. And that doesn't count
their own free agent defection, Mo Vaughn, whose six-year, $80
million contract still remains the high-water mark for signings
this winter, with an average annual value of $13.3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   There are slim pickings left in the free agent market, which
leaves Duquette little choice but to upgrade the team through
trades, a process that is expected to accelerate Friday, when
baseball's winter meetings begin in Nashville. Expos outfielder
Rondell White, Marlins first baseman Clifford Floyd, and Dodgers
outfielder Raul Mondesi could be among the players targeted by
Duquette, and the club also intends to explore its long shot
options in Roger Clemens trade talks with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, meanwhile, have lost All-Star Palmeiro, All-Star
second baseman Roberto Alomar, outfielder Eric Davis, and reliever
Armando Benitez, but have done a dramatic makeover of their team by
adding Belle, Clark, second baseman Delino DeShields, and reliever
Mike Timlin through free agency, while acquiring catcher Charles
Johnson in a three-way trade with the Mets and Dodgers. They also
retained outfielder B.J. Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   They've committed a projected $124 million to those six players
alone, and by all accounts, they're not done yet. The Orioles are
considered one of the leading candidates to sign righthander Kevin
Brown, the prize among this year's class of free agent pitchers.
Brown could cost as much as $14 million a year for six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to change the tide, the intensity, and the way
the guys here approach the game,'' Wren said. ``I don't think
there's a better guy in terms of the way he approaches the game
than Will Clark. And that doesn't even touch on his hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark nearly came to Baltimore five years ago, but the Orioles
chose Palmeiro and Clark signed with the Rangers. Now, as he nears
35, he gets his chance to play for the home team in Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   He received a $1 million signing bonus and will be paid $4.5
million in 1999 and $5.5 million in 2000. He can make an additional
$900,000 a year by meeting games-played clauses, and has additional
performance bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has been a terrific hitter at Fenway Park, batting .438,
his best average in any ballpark. But Sunday, he took an apparent
shot at the quality of the Fenway Park infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a place to play defense,'' he said, ``Baltimore is way
above Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
