<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE RALLIES LATE TO CORRAL WAC TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Air Force was a sleeping giant for most of
yesterday's Western Athletic Conference Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons, ranked 13th in The Associated Press poll,
awakened late in the fourth quarter, scoring two touchdowns and
defeating Brigham Young, 20-13, before a crowd of 32,745 at Sam
Boyd Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With his team trailing 13-7, Air Force senior quarterback Blane
Morgan connected with Matt Farmer on a 59-yard touchdown pass play
with 3:49 remaining in the game for what proved to be the winning
score.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer ran untouched down the left sideline for the touchdown,
and Air Force took a 14-13 lead. The Falcons added another
touchdown with 1:43 left when fullback Spanky Gilliam dashed 29
yards for a touchdow. The extra-point attempt was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force moves to 11-1 and will close the season at the Aloha
Bowl. The Falcons' only loss this year was a 35-34 setback at the
hands of TCU. BYU dropped to 9-4 and will play in the Liberty Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The WAC title was the first for Air Force, which shared the
league championship in 1985 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys never gave up,'' Falcons coach Fisher DeBerry said.
``It was a gutsy performance. Blane \RMorgan\S did a great job of
making the plays. He's a winner and a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan scored Air Force's first touchdown on a 2-yard run midway
through the third quarter, capping a five-play, 73-yard drive to
tie the game 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the fourth quarter, after BYU's Owen Pochman had kicked
two field goals to give the Cougars a 13-7 lead, Morgan connected
with Farmer for the go-ahead touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-11 from the Air Force 41, Morgan threw to Farmer,
who was standing along the line of scrimmage. After making the
catch, Farmer quickly slipped around a defender and sprinted to the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I got the ball off to Farmer, he'd be off to the
races,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown gave Air Force a 14-13 lead with 3:49 left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force stopped BYU on the next possession and took over at
the Cougars' 42. Four plays later, Gilliam dashed for the 29-yard
TD run. Brigham Young still had hope when it blocked the extra
point, leaving the score at 20-13 with 1:43 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   BYU picked up one first down, but Air Force held again and took
possession with 27 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars took a 7-0 lead with 1:01 left in the first half
when quarterback Kevin Feterik passed to Mike Rigell for a 13-yard
TD.
</P>
<P>
   BYU missed three opportunities to score in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The first came late in the first quarter when the Cougars drove
46 yards to the Air Force 20, but Pochman's 37-yard field-goal
attempt hit the left upright. The second came early in the second
quarter after the Cougars had driven 63 yards to the Air Force 25.
But Feterik's pass was tipped and intercepted by C.J. Zonotti. The
third was late in the second quarter after BYU had driven 65 yards,
where Aaron Roderick dropped a pass in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   BYU's first-half touchdown was set up when Rob Morris recovered
a fumble by Matt Rillos at the Air Force 24 with 1:44 remaining in
the second quarter. Three plays later, Feterik connected with
Ridell for a 13-yard TD pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
