<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS REHABILITATION FOR RELEASED KILLERS POSSIBLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He murdered a man in Phoenix nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like James Hamm, he paid his official debt to society, doing 13
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the man who asks to be called only Bobby _ for fear of
losing his mortgage finance job _ wonders whether he'll ever get a
break in the world beyond bars.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby took real-estate courses but was laughed at when he
inquired about a broker's license. He inquired about becoming a
licensed contractor and was told not to bother.
</P>
<P>
   He took insurance classes and scored high on tests, only to be
denied a license by the state.
</P>
<P>
   His appeal was denied also, based on ``insufficient
rehabilitation time.''
</P>
<P>
   But is rehabilitation possible _ at least in terms of anything
beyond menial, low-paying employment _ for the approximately 150
killers and 12,000 total inmates released annually from the state's
prisons?
</P>
<P>
   Have Arizonans struck a reasonable balance between the clashing
demands of social vengeance and individual redemption?
</P>
<P>
   Such questions burned up the talk-radio airwaves and the
telephone lines at Arizona State University on Thursday after it
was revealed that the School of Justice Studies had hired Hamm as
an adjunct professor to teach two law courses next spring.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the uproar, ASU officials reversed themselves
Thursday and said that Hamm would be reassigned to another area in
which he would not be teaching students.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm was paroled after serving 17 years for the murder of
Willard Morley near Tucson after a drug deal that went bad. In his
latter years of incarceration, Hamm was described as a model
inmate, and earned an undergraduate degree from Northern Arizona
University.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his release, Hamm raised another furor by being
admitted to ASU's Law School, from which he graduated. He failed
his first attempt at the state Bar, which had caused further
protests simply because he was allowed to take it.
</P>
<P>
   James Jones, a retired state purchasing agent, said Friday that
he understands the groundswell of anger directed toward Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   Society shouldn't have to worry about rehabilitation, Jones
said:
</P>
<P>
   You kill? You die.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have paid with his life,'' Jones said. ``At the
least, he should have been put to hard labor like they did at the
Yuma Territorial Prison. It just sickens me that the same law
school my boy attended admitted him, and the school turns around
later and hires him.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gallup, a former Phoenix police sergeant, also questioned
why Hamm was released from prison. Released killers should be
treated as pariahs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way a killer should be let out of prison is if they
have a terminal illness so they can die with dignity,'' Gallup
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a murderer is treated as anything more than a cancer in the
community, we've got our values at a cross purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   But rehabilitation and acceptance by the community is society's
only sane course of action, said Larry Hammond, a Phoenix defense
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond advocates a carrot-and-stick approach to ensure good
conduct on the part of parolees and to try to integrate them back
into society. The final step would be giving the inmate back all
the rights of other citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not wise to have a flat rule like the stripping of all
rights,'' Hammond said. ``It should be a system on post-release
restrictions like OK, you do well for a year or two and here's your
right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, if the progress continues, here's your passport. You
continue to do well, you have the right to run for public office.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond said ASU missed the perfect opportunity for having Hamm
become a role model for other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Sarahlyn Bristow, a Baptist minister who is chaplain at Estrella
Jail, said there are even more compelling reasons spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we confess all our sins, we are forgiven. If they do
their time and they are repentant, they should be welcomed back
into society,'' Bristow said. ``If God forgives me, how can I judge
someone else?''
</P>
<P>
   But Juanita Soto Ayers, former director of counseling at the
Arizona State Prison-Florence, said it's a pipe dream to think that
more than one in 50 prisoners can really be rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can find equally intelligent and hard-working people to
become college instructors who are not killers,'' Ayers said.
``Maybe he should write a book or make speeches about his
experience in prison. But he shouldn't be allowed to teach
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Most students interviewed on the ASU campus said they would
welcome Hamm in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Pearman, a freshman, said, ``He knows a lot about the
legal system _ a whole lot more than most people would want to
know. He served his time. He's done. He's fine. I don't have a
problem with him teaching here at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Wolf, another freshman, said she also could have learned
something from Hamm although, ``I wouldn't want to spend a lot of
time with him outside class. Office hours would be a bit of a
question.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAnza Valencia, a master's candidate in the School of Justice
Studies, said students will miss out on an unusual perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone cries about the universities being an ivory tower, so
when we finally get a chance for some real-world experience, it
gets taken away,'' Valencia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the students really thought there would be a
lot to learn from Mr. Hamm. But the university gave in. I think the
larger political context is that people really don't believe in
rehabilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   And one Valley man, who served 16 years for murder before being
released and earning a bachelor's and master's degree from ASU,
said the lack of opportunity takes its toll.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who is raising two small daughters alone and facing
bankruptcy, said he has been denied jobs at large social-service
organizations. Instead, he said, he's been relegated to low-end
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give it one more chance and go for a Ph.D. at
ASU,'' he said. ``But in the long run, I'm probably going to have
to leave America.'' &QL; 
Republic writers Martin Van Der Werf, Bill Muller and Michael
Clancy contributed to this article. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057, or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
