<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-LEHIGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS KEEPS IT GOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ After the final seconds ticked off the clock,
the throng stormed the field and approached the goalpost in the
south end zone, only to be thwarted by law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem to bother these University of Massachusetts
football fans, though. They simply ran down the field en masse,
ignoring pleas from the public address announcer, and attacked the
north goalpost like an army of ants closing in on a side of beef.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the celebration: The Minutemen had just made the
1998 season arguably the most successful in school history,
defeating unbeaten Lehigh, 27-21, to advance to the NCAA Division
1-AA semifinals for only the second time, and becoming the first
team in school history to win 10 games overall and two playoff
games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone at McGuirk Alumni Stadium wanted to be part of this
home finale. (However, junior Joshua Dubreuil got a little too
involved, as he was struck on the head when the goalpost came down.
He was taken to Cooley-Dickinson Hospital in Northampton, where he
was treated for lacerations and released.)
</P>
<P>
   The UMass players were mobbed on the field during the postgame
handshakes following the first home playoff win in school history.
Miniature cannons fired deafening blasts. The school band blared
the fight song. And a goalpost was sacrificed. Support for the
football team has returned to UMass with a vengeance. And the
season isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four teams still playing 1-AA football, and we're
one of them,'' said UMass coach Mark Whipple, who took over a
program that last year had suffered its worst season this century
(2-9) and boldly declared that in 1998 he would field a unit
capable of winning a national championship. Now he's just two wins
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great, great day for the UMass team, our seniors,
and the university,'' said Whipple, whose 10-3 team now goes on the
road to Natchitoches, La., to meet Northwestern State, a 31-20
winner over Appalachian State Saturday. UMass has already beaten
one team from Louisiana in the playoffs, McNeese State, in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big game, and big players stepped up and made the
big plays,'' said Whipple. ``You have to give credit to the kids.
They believed that they could win, and as coaches we believe in
them. We made a couple more big plays than they did today.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit running back Marcel Shipp, who had sat out the
first-round game because of a knee injury. He gained 159 yards on
36 carries, including a 1-yard touchdown run with 11:17 left that
put the Minutemen ahead, 27-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way I wasn't going to play today,'' said Shipp,
who became the first player in UMass history to rush for 2,000
yards in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Another standout on the offense was quarterback Todd Bankhead,
who completed 22 of 36 passes for 270 yards and two touchdowns, the
second of which was a 37-yarder to wide receiver Adrian Zullo with
1:34 left in the third period that turned a 14-13 halftime deficit
into a 20-14 lead. Bankhead's other scoring pass went 30 yards to
Jimmy Moore, who caught eight passes for 117 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But it was defense that secured the victory. The Minutemen were
burned badly in the first 1:01 of play, when Lehigh (12-1) scored
on Ron Jean's 8-yard run, which capped a five-play, 76-yard drive.
Lehigh struck again with 2:45 left in the half, capitalizing on a
Bankhead interception to score on a 1-yard run by Jean, capping a
five-play, 53-yard drive, to make it 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   After UMass had built its 27-14 lead, Lehigh cut the deficit to
6 with 7:11 left on a 1-yard run by quarterback Phil Stambaugh.
Then Lehigh stalled two UMass drives, getting the ball the final
time with 2:17 left.
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh, which had beaten Richmond on a field goal with three
seconds left in its first-round game last weekend, moved to the
9-yard line with 2:01 left, and things looked bleak for the
Minutemen.
</P>
<P>
   But defensive end Chris Price sacked Stambaugh on second and
goal from the 9, moving the ball back to the 16 with 1:16 left. On
third down, Stambaugh threw incomplete to Deron Braswell in the
left corner of the end zone, with defensive back Mike Smith
covering tightly.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:08 left, UMass called a timeout before the fourth-down
play. Whipple huddled up his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just told them to finish,'' he said. ```You've got one
play, and you just have to finish.'''
</P>
<P>
   That they did. Stambaugh threw to almost the same spot, to Joe
Falcone, with Smith covering again. The receiver couldn't get two
hands on the ball, and it fell to the ground incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had asked me before the game what position I would have
wanted in the fourth quarter, it would have been exactly how it
turned out,'' said Lehigh coach Kevin Higgins, whose team gave up
the most points it has allowed all season. ``We had an opportunity
to win at the end. We just didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That left the home team _ and fans _ to celebrate the final game
of the year at McGuirk Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited to be one of four,'' said Whipple. ``Anything
can happen in any game, and if we're lucky enough to play two more,
it probably will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
