<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BANKHEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKHEAD GEARED UP IN CLUTCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ There were times when he couldn't move the
team, when he couldn't complete a pass, when, it seemed, his mind
was elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the times when he took charge, when just about
every pass he threw was on target, when he was totally involved.
</P>
<P>
   When UMass needed quarterback Todd Bankhead most, however, he
was there.
</P>
<P>
   That was never more evident than on a pair of second-half
touchdown drives, when Bankhead moved the Minutemen 80 and 59 yards
to turn a 14-13 halftime deficit into a 27-14 lead. The Minutemen
then hung on for a 27-21 win over unbeaten Lehigh, keeping alive
their hopes of an NCAA Division 1-AA championship.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the final stats will show that Bankhead completed 22
of 36 passes for 270 yards and two touchdowns. Eight of those
completions, good for 117 yards, and one of those TD passes went to
wide receiver Jimmy Moore. Bankhead also had two passes
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   It was a performance that did not leave the quarterback overly
elated, but one he definitely won't discard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we can win and still have a shot at winning the
championship, I'm pleased,'' said the 6-foot-3-inch, 207-pound
junior from Escondido, Calif. ``My job is to go out there and play
as well as I can and give the team a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterback position calls for consistency and to make
things happen and to make the plays when he has to,'' said
Bankhead. ``When I do that, we move the ball; and when I don't, we
don't move the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass moved the ball sporadically in the first half and trailed
at the break, 14-13. But on back-to-back possessions _ the last of
the third quarter and first of the fourth quarter _ Bankhead drove
the Minutemen to the end zone with clocklike precision.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive that put UMass ahead, 20-14, he clicked on 4 of 5
passes, two of them on third downs, before hooking up with Adrian
Zullo on a 37-yard scoring strike. And on the drive that boosted
the lead to 27-14, he completed two big third-down passes to set up
Marcel Shipp's plunge from the 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to do my job, keep the ball on the ground
when I could, and eat up some clock at that point,'' said Bankhead.
``My first half was just so-so, but things picked up after that.''
</P>
<P>
   A big plus for the Minutemen was the return of Shipp, who had
sat out last week's first-round win over McNeese State with a knee
injury. He practiced sparingly during the week but knew that when
Saturday's gun sounded, he'd be in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Shipp responded to the challenge by gaining 159 yards on 36
carries. One of those rushes _ a 5-yard gain off right tackle in
the first quarter _ pushed him over the 2,000-yard mark for the
season, making him the first player in UMass history to accomplish
that feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was playing this game regardless,'' said Shipp. ``I
had to. You weren't going to keep me out of a game like this. The
knee held up pretty well during the game. It got a little tight on
me at the end, but it will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipp said reaching 2,000 yards meant a lot to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great achievement,'' he said. ``That's something I've
always wanted to do, and this season I accomplished it. I'm proud
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shipp will be a lot prouder, he said, if he and his
teammates can continue this storybook march.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence level on this team has built throughout the
year, and we've been playing just well enough to win,'' he said.
``I don't think we've played our best game yet. Hopefully that's
still ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
