<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT DARKENS WHITE HOUSE CHRISTMAS PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ As they al ways do this time of year, members of
Congress and their spouses will assemble at the White House on
Monday evening for the annual Christmas ball with the first family.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a season of ornate decora tions, of giving and sharing . .
. and impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In a bit of wretched timing, it seems this year's grand White
House holiday party falls the very same week as the House Judiciary
Committee's scheduled vote on whether to approve articles of im
peachment against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Some Congress members, who are accustomed to smiling through
strained social situations, say this would simply be too much to
bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone would have to con vince me that it wouldn't be too
uncomfortable, and I don't think they can,'' said Rep. John
Shadegg, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg plans to stay home, and says a small group of his GOP
colleagues will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   At least a few congressional wives are forbidding their husbands
from going. A Democratic senator, speaking on condition of
anonymity, confided that he won't attend be cause his wife said she
wouldn't shake Clinton's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it never considered canceling the ball. It
dutifully decorated its official tree, an 18-foot balsam fir from
Wisconsin. It mailed out the invita tions: ``The President and Mrs.
Clinton request the pleasure of your company at a Congressional
holiday ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And at 7 p.m., the White House will open its doors to many of
the very same members of Congress who are trying to cook the
president like a Christmas goose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypocrisy makes the world go round, and it's clearly the jet
fuel in politics,'' said Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia
political sci entist. ``I would think this particular audience
could manage to denounce the president on the floor of the Senate
or House, and 10 minutes later show up in a receiving line with the
president and first lady. There's something to be said for
separating social affairs and public affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   But this year is like few others. The rancor is high, even by
Wash ington standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington has rarely been as nasty and partisan, and hosts
and hostesses have to be much more careful about the mix at
parties,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hillary Rodham Clin ton declared, ``It's a little
hard to get into the Christmas spirit.'' She was referring to the
unusually warm weather. But she could just as well have been
talking about the atmos phere on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   This is a year when a member of the president's own party _ Sen.
Joseph Biden, D-Del., _ said Clinton showed he was ``immoral'' by
having an affair with former White House intern Monica Lewin sky
and then deceiving the nation about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were it my daughter . . . I would be looking for the man. I'd
be looking to give him a straight right,'' Biden said in a recent
speech.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly the stuff of ``Ho, Ho, Ho.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden is not planning to attend the ball, said his
communications director, Chris Madison. He said the event poses a
scheduling problem, since Biden commutes home each night to
Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the White House said it was expecting the usual amount of
attendees for the ball _ about 1,000. All 535 members of Con gress
have been invited, and each may bring a guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about Christmas this year at the White
House, as we are every year. We're doing as many events, I think,
as we have done in the past,'' White House spokesman Roger Salazar
said. The lineup includes a recep tion for journalists and their
fami lies on Dec. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Told that some invitees may stay away, Salazar replied, ``For
every one of those, we could come up with examples of folks who are
seeking the invitations. We don't have attendance problems
tradition ally, and I don't think we will this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the partygoers, espe cially the Republicans, are quick
to note that their attendance won't be an endorsement of the chief
execu tive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still admire the office of the president,'' said Rep. Matt
Salmon, R-Ariz. ``I may have some prob lems with the traits of this
president, but I still admire the office, and I still believe that
the White House is the people's house. You bet I'm going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Salmon has already taken some flak for his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spouse of a member of Congress gave me a really hard time
because I am going,'' he said. ``She said, `How in the world could
you stand in the same room with that man?' '' &QL; 
 &UR; Jeff Barker can be reached at (202)
 &UR; 662-7264 or jeff.barker &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
