<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-KANSAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BEATS COLD-SHOOTING PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ When Pepperdine arrived home it could have wandered
off campus, headed toward the beach and somehow wound up in Asia
without getting wet _ all without hitting the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of shooting day.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, searching for any kind of national recognition, was
an anemic 1 of 14 from 3-point range. That, more than anything,
allowed No.7 Kansas to escape the Wooden Classic with a 62-55 win
Saturday at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Senior point guard Jelani Gardner scored a game-high 16 points,
but joined the Waves' outside ineptitude by missing both of his
3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Tommie Prince, the Waves' top long-range shooter
entering the game, was held scoreless for only the second time in
his Pepperdine career. He missed six shots and was 0 of 5 from
3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit some of those (3-point) shots, we probably win,''
Gardner said. ``We played hard but basically we're not good enough
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The outside struggles are the opposite of what the Waves
experienced during the exhibition season, but they mirror what has
taken place since.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine hit 50 percent of its 3-pointers in two exhibition
games, and coach Lorenzo Romar said the shots charted during
practice were the same. However, the Waves are 29 of 107 on
3-pointers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed a big opportunity to get recognized and to show
people we can beat the big-name teams,'' Prince said. ``But 1 for
14, man, that's something. If we could have hit a few we could have
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas (5-1) did very little to distinguish itself as one of the
nation's elite teams, other than keep alive a streak of not losing
back-to-back games that dates back nearly five years. The Jayhawks
were coming off an 18-point loss to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Gregory led the Jayhawks with 13 points. Ryan Robertson
added 12 and Eric Chenowith chipped in 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Oklahoma State coach) Eddie Sutton said it best when he
grabbed me and I said how ugly it was and how hard both teams
played,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams said. ``He said forget all
about it. It's a `W.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The one problem we had is we haven't lost very often. It's a
good problem to have, but when you do lose then I think the kids
get a little more tentative and think something's wrong. The
tentativeness showed up on the court, especially in the first
half.''
</P>
<P>
   What was certain to bother the Waves as they fought their way
through the evening traffic on their way back to Malibu was the
missed opportunity for a program starving for attention outside Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas may be in the top 10, but the Jayhawks are still fumbling
around offensively and committing way too many turnovers. Couple
that with a spirited defensive effort from Pepperdine and the
seven-point loss becomes unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves held Kansas scoreless for a span of 7:01, bridging the
halves, but scored only nine points and had a 28-26 lead with 18
minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got good shots, shots we talk about in practice and that we
want, and at times weren't able to knock them down,'' Romar said.
``If we made a couple shots there we could have spread the gap and
been up. I told our guys at halftime that we were three or four
made shots from being in control of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team had a double-digit lead, and it wasn't until a 7-0
spurt late, keyed by strong inside play, gave Kansas a 56-47 lead
with 4:45 to play. The Waves closed within 56-53 with two minutes
remaining, but Chenowith hit a six-footer along the baseline to
extend Kansas' lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's effort to pull within a possession failed when
Prince, who had an in-grown toenail removed earlier in the day,
symbolized the afternoon by missing two uncontested 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not getting shots then we're going to do something
about that,'' Romar said. ``But we're just not making wide-open
shots. All we can do is go back and shoot as many as we can
shoot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
