<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-WYOMING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL PROBLEMS NEARLY DERAIL UA  
 BUT WILDCATS RALLY TO BEAT WYOMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The good news for 13th-ranked Arizona is that three
players had career scoring highs Saturday in a 94-84 dash past
Wyoming at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is they had to.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th ranked Wildcats (4-0), who have four non-conference
games left to straighten out their youthful woes before opening
defense of their Pac-10 title, had all of their shortcomings
exposed in a strong effort by the Cowboys (3-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to continue to be a struggle, I'm afraid, for a
while,'' said UA Coach Lute Olson. ``But the ability is there.''
</P>
<P>
   In transition, the Wildcats didn't get back and were burned for
easy layups.
</P>
<P>
   In half-court defense, UA didn't find Wyoming's outside shooters
quickly enough, allowing the Cowboys to open a quick nine-point
lead with torrid three-point shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, with three true freshmen in the lineup, was
discombobulated offensively, the youngsters firing away and hitting
little. Very little. The two freshman shooting guards, starter
Traves Wilson and backup Ruben Douglas , shot a combined 0 for 9
and had six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   That's likely going to cause yet another freshman, Richard
Jefferson, a Moon Valley High product, to be moved to shooting
guard with Justin Wessel stepping into Jefferson's small forward
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me like we have to take a look at whether those
are the two guys we are going to go with,'' Olson said. ``We've
been waiting for one of our shooting guards to surface, and neither
has. Richard and Justin are the ones making things happen. They
deserve the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona was bailed out by senior point guard Jason Terry's
career-high 29 points (plus seven assists and four steals), senior
center A.J. Bramlett's career- high 24 points (plus 17 rebounds,
four steals, and two blocked shots), and Wessel's career-high 15
points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson made only three of 11 shots for 7 points but he added
six rebounds and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-2 tear by the Wildcats midway through the closing half,
sparked by Bramlett's outlets to Terry, who pulled up for three
pointers or found Wessel running on the wing, took UA from nine
points down to 13 up in 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Wildcats survived seven missed free throws in the
closing 4:54.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we proved to ourselves a little bit that we can play
with anybody in the country,'' said Cowboys first-year Coach Steve
McClain.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys made the point a little too clearly for the
Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scouting report said they were good shooters,'' Terry
said. ``The whole thing with this team is defense. If we don't play
it in the first half, it's going to be close. The older guys know
that, but maybe the young guys have to experience it to know it.
That's what these non-conference games are about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bramlett, at 6-10 the tallest man on the floor, acknowledged
that as big as his numbers were, they could have been even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to try to get every rebound because that's what
sparks runs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bramlett, who missed several shots from point-blank, said the
unexpected emergence of Wessel, a sophomore who has been in the
program for three years, has been critical to the Wildcats' early
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin really came up big,'' Bramlett said. ``He's got the
skills. Defense is the only thing that has kept him out of big-time
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wessel, who made six of seven shots, played 29 minutes, in part
because starting power forward Eugene Edgerson was suspended for
the game for throwing a flagrant elbow in the Brigham Young game
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene wasn't there, and if he had been the start might have
been different because he is a physical, intense player ,'' Wessel
said. ``We feed off him. Without him, it was like we were playing
in slow-motion at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have freshman starters, but I've been in the program longer
and I'm more comfortable at this point. The coaches told me that
I'd have a lot of chances like this to come in, and to be ready to
step up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
