<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTHOMES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX AREA HOMEOWNERS SAVOR SOARING MARKET
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR 
 and RYAN KONIG 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Valley's hot home market hit inferno status this year, as
buyers snatched up houses at scorching speed even as prices roared
upward.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers smiled, buyers paced, and real estate analysts gasped as
the frenzy was documented in hard, cold facts:
</P>
<P>
   More than 90,000 new and existing homes in metro Phoenix will
sell this year, setting an all-time record.
</P>
<P>
   The average time a home is listed before being snared by an
eager buyer has fallen to just 21 days in some areas, a record low
for the 1990s. In some popular areas, bids are being offered
minutes after a house is put up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   There is little or no difference between what sellers are asking
and what buyers are willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The value of more than half the homes in the Valley has
increased by at least 25 percent since 1994, making many homes that
were worth $100,000 five years ago worth at least $125,000 now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times are good,'' said Scott Jarson, a agent with Realty Execu
tives. ``Homes are being snatched up hours or even minutes after a
sign goes up or they get listed on the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi Contana found out just how good times are when she and her
husband recently offered their north-central Phoenix home for sale.
Competing bids by prospective buy ers pushed the sale price $8,000
above their list price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea how in demand our home was,'' she said. ``If we
had the time, we probably could have gotten even more.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Contanas had it easy selling their home, the Lillises
found it tough buying a home in the area they wanted when they
moved back to Phoenix from Chicago earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   They knew exactly where they wanted to buy _ the Arcadia
district with its close-knit neighbor hoods, sprawling ranch homes,
good schools and lovely stands of orange trees. But what they
didn't know was what it would cost them. Big.
</P>
<P>
   The Lillises and their three daughters had lived in Arcadia in
east Phoenix for six years before moving to the Midwest in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In those six years, the increase in the value of their home was
some thing every homeowner dreams of: The Lillises sold theirs for
$150,000 more than they had paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   But just a year later they had to pay $50,000 more than they
sold their former Arcadia home for to get back into the
neighborhood _ in a smaller home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were bowled over by how much more it cost us to move back
into the neighborhood _ and for less space,'' Lynn Lillis said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Arcadia area is so desirable that they felt lucky to
get into the house. And that happened only because a friend tipped
them that someone was selling; they were able to put an offer on
the home before it was officially on the market.
</P>
<P>
   That tells the story of the Valley's real estate market. It will
cost you to get a prime home, and you'll have to hustle. And if you
already own one, you can move it fast and make a hefty profit if
it's priced right.
</P>
<P>
   Like any fire, though, the Valley's home market won't burn
forever. Analysts already are predicting a slowdown for next year.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, sellers are still basking in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, the value of most existing homes has
bal looned in value, jumping more than 50 percent in areas such as
Arcadia, Paradise Valley, downtown Phoe nix's historic districts,
north-central Phoenix, southwest Phoenix, east Scottsdale and
Apache Junc tion/Gold Canyon, an emerging area.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many new homes in growing suburbs like
Ahwatukee in the southeast Valley and Arrowhead Ranch in Glendale
are being pounced upon almost before the paint dries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just won't seem to quit,`` said R.L. Brown, a local home
building analyst. ``The Phoenix housing market has exceeded all
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, homes are selling days or even hours after they
hit the market, and prices often trump sellers' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The Contanas had seen some of their north-central Phoenix neigh
bors selling. They thought it might be a good time to make some
money on their three-bedroom house so they could move into a bigger
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to sell it fast so we listed it at $190,000,'' Bobbi
Con tana said. ``Our Realtor thought we might be able to get a
little more, but we had already found another house we wanted.``
</P>
<P>
   The Contanas scheduled an open house for the next day. More than
a dozen people were waiting in their driveway before they opened
their front door.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of selling for $190,000, they got $198,000 be cause
buyers started outbidding each other for the home near Squaw Peak.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder. The Contanas' former home is in the 85016 ZIP
code, where home prices have increased nearly 44 percent since
1994. Add to that the fact that more than 2,200 of the houses in
the ZIP code have changed hands at least once since 1994, and you
have one sizzling area.
</P>
<P>
   The speed their home sold also was not unusual in this market.
</P>
<P>
   The average time that priced-right homes stay on the market has
fallen to three weeks in some popular Valley communities, a
fraction of the time it took to sell houses in the early 1990s,
when ``For sale'' signs languished for an average of nine months in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
   On average, the homes that are spending the least time on the
market are in northeast Scottsdale, central Phoenix historic
districts, Arcadia, Paradise Valley, Ahwatukee and Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, Ray Levin, a real estate agent with Keller
Williams, was putting up a sign for a Sunday open house in
northeast Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The home near Frank Lloyd Wright Boulevard and the Thomp son
Peak Parkway had gone on the market the day before. It was priced
at $215,000 in an area where more than 45 percent of the area's
homes have sold at least once since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Levin barely got the sign up before he had to add ``Sold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple followed me into the house and made an offer less
than an hour later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a testament to the vibrancy of the market, this year new and
existing home sales will break all records with a total of at least
90,000 transactions across the Val ley.
</P>
<P>
   And the average spread between what sellers want and buyers are
willing to pay has closed to less than 1 percent, agents say.
</P>
<P>
   Resale numbers skyrocketed in some Valley communities like east
Mesa, Apache Junction, Arrowhead, Arcadia, northeast Scottsdale,
Para dise Valley, central Phoenix and historic neighborhoods like
Encanto and Willo, all of which could be considered among top hot
spots for home values and number of sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the 85018 ZIP code where Arcadia is located and the Lillises
bought, nearly 30 percent of the homes have changed hands in the
past five years. And these days it doesn't take long to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good home in Arcadia is typically on the market about six
minutes before it gets snatched up,'' said Bruce Wiskirchen, an
agent with Realty Executives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Valley homes are hot because thousands of home-hungry people
are rushing to Arizona to live in metropolitan Phoenix. Maricopa
County led the nation for population growth last year, and from
1990 to 1997, almost 600,000 people poured into the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a robust job market is gushing the cash that home buyers
need to bid up prices.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, interest rates have plunged to mouth-watering
lows well below 7 percent, offering buyers some of the best
mortgage deals they've seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix isn't alone in the trend. Other cities such as Atlanta,
Las Vegas, San Diego and Los Angeles are all brimming with buyers
will ing to pay more because they have money to spend and wanting
more house because of low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now and the next several years will be looked upon as the
golden years,'' National Association of Re altors economist John
Tuccillo said. ``Mortgage rates and unemployment are low, consumer
confidence and spending are high.''
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix is a striking example of a place offering attractive
lairs that are still relatively affordable for people on the move.
</P>
<P>
   The area's median existing home price is $115,000, far below
most of those other cities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Atlanta is the closest, at just above $115,000. But the typical
price for an existing home is $125,000 in Las Vegas, $176,000 in
Los Angeles and $192,000 for San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the Phoenix home market is broad-based. Since
1993, more than half the ZIP codes in the Valley have shown jumps
in home prices of more than 25 percent. That's not bad, since
inflation rose only 13 percent during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some Valley homes are more appealing than others,
either because they are in top-ranked school districts or come with
the most square footage and ameni ties for the lowest price. Those
are the two top priorities for the average metro Phoenix home
shopper, real estate agents say.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Valley's prime homes can be found in neighbor hoods
offering easy access to free ways and nestled up against bustling
business corridors and thriving shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   But the the mix of attractions may vary from hot spot to hot
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Ambience, a whiff of class and mansions with breathtaking views
draw buyers to Paradise Valley. Northeast Scottsdale and the Arca
dia district pull home seekers with their good schools, big lots
and upscale lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Central Phoenix's historical dis tricts attract people who work
down town and have grown tired of long commutes and cookie-cutter
homes. Tempe boasts solid schools, big yards and quick freeway
access.
</P>
<P>
   Some west Valley areas beckon because you can still get a big
home there for less than $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; One west Valley couple, Jim and Theresa Norman, recently consid
ered selling their 2,000-square-foot home on Palm Valley's golf
course, near Litchfield Park.
</P>
<P>
   But even though they could get more than $150,000 for their
home, which they bought four years ago for less than $115,000, they
found they'd have had to pay at least an additional $100,000 to buy
a similar house in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   While the market is hot, sellers shouldn't expect the heat to
drive buyers completely crazy. Good area or no, a house is likely
to languish on the market if the seller gets too greedy, pegging
his price too high over the appraised value.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a home is overpriced, it doesn't matter where it's located.
It won't move as quickly, no matter how great the market is right
now,'' said Chuck Fraas, an agent with Century 21 Alliance and
Investment Group.
</P>
<P>
   But reasonably priced homes aren't going to go begging for quite
a while, Valley real estate observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brown and other analysts like David Thikoll of the Meyers
Group are predicting a slight slow down in construction of new
homes next year, they say the area's resale market isn't going to
waver for a while.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Even if the Valley's home market slows next year as we
expect, it will continue to be a hot market for resales and
appreciation, as long as jobs keep bringing people here,'' Thikoll
said. ``And there's no forecast for job growth to stop anytime
soon.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Catherine Reagor can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8040, or at catherine.reagor &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
