<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGE OPTIONS HELP HOME BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The traditional 30-year mortgage with a hefty down payment isn't
the only way to buy a home anymore.
</P>
<P>
   There are a plethora of mortgages available that make buying a
house easier than ever, whether you're a first-time home buyer who
doesn't have enough cash for a down payment, someone with bad
credit, or a high-end buyer who wants a big tax write-off right
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mortgages have changed dramatically from 20 years ago. Now
there are a whole bunch of types of loans on the market that make
it simpler for people to buy homes,'' said Jay Luber, a vice
president with North American Mortgage, one of the biggest mortgage
lenders in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The many ways to finance a house, coupled with low interest
rates, have helped more people buy homes and others buy bigger
houses, thus helping fuel the boom in sales of both new and resale
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell the story:
</P>
<P>
   Someone purchasing a $150,000 house with 10 percent down and an
8 percent interest rate _ where 30-year loans were hovering a few
years ago _ would pay $990 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The same loan with a 7 percent rate _ which the market averages
now for conventional loans with no points _ only costs $898 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low interest rates have definitely helped the home market.
People can now afford much more house and get different options for
financing it,'' said Phil Mercurio of Century 21 Alliance and
Investment Group.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest help has probably come for first-time buyers. These
eager home shoppers no longer have to scrape together 20 percent,
or even 10 percent, of a home's value to get into their first
house.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Housing Administration, or FHA, now backs these
loans, which lets first-time buyers put less than 5 percent down _
even less if they get bond money from a city or state trying to aid
home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Also Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the top loan buyers in the
country, have beefed up their low down payment programs for
first-time buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The groups recently began allowing borrowers to obtain a 3
percent down payment from gifts or loans from family, friends,
employers or a non-profit agency.
</P>
<P>
   That is a big change from the past, when borrowers had to bend
over backward to show that their down payments came from their own
checking accounts and that the cost of getting into a home would
not leave them strapped to make the monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   For home buyers who are not sure how long they will stay in
their house, there are new hybrid loans, said Terry Turk, president
of Sun American Mortgage in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   These loans have low fixed interest rates for five, seven or 10
years and then rise in cost. That way, people who know they're only
going to be in a city for a few years can buy a bigger house.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the top mortgage companies also have developed programs
for people who have a rocky credit background or have been through
a bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   These mortgages carry higher interest rates at first, but if the
borrower doesn't miss payments for the first year or so, the lender
will either refinance or drop the rate.
</P>
<P>
   At the high end of the market are mortgages that allow buyers to
pay all interest and no principal for a period, so the home buyer
can get the best tax bang for the buck.
</P>
<P>
   And there are balloon mortgages for people whose income is based
on a large annual bonus. These loans require only interest payments
until a certain time and then a large ballon payment of principle.
</P>
<P>
   All mortgage bankers agree that getting a mortgage has become
easier for those who have a steady income. But it could get even
better.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae is looking at customizing loans. For example, if
someone plans to work eight more years before retiring, his or her
mortgage could last that long.
</P>
<P>
   Or if a borrower will have big education costs for children at
some point, a long-term mortgage could be configured so the person
has smaller payments then.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt among economists that more people buy when
barriers to the loan process like steep down payments and high
interest rates are taken away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low interest rates gave the Valley's already strong housing
market a shot in the arm,'' said Jay Butler, director of the Real
Estate Center at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   As a testimony to that, the rate of home ownership in the Valley
has steadily climbed during the past several years, recently
hitting a high of 75 percent of all households. Nationally, home
ownership hit a record 68 percent last month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
