<HEADLINE>
JARVIS FEELS AT HOME AS ST. JOHN'S RIPS BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With his 80-year-old mother, Dorothy, and his wife,
Connie, seated next to each other behind the visitor's bench and
his son, Mike 2d, seated alongside him as one of his assistants,
St. John's basketball coach Mike Jarvis, the former coach at
Cambridge Rindge &AMP; Latin and Boston University, enjoyed a
triumphant homecoming Saturdayafter his 25th-ranked Red Storm
pinned Boston College with a 74-55 loss in the Big East opener
before 4,438 at Conte Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Who ever said you can't go home again?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it didn't apply to Jarvis, who considered leaving
George Washington two years ago to take the BC job before removing
himself from consideration after deciding ``the timing wasn't
right,'' he said. Jarvis, though, wound up in the Big East after
leaving in June to take over at St. John's, which won its first
conference road game of the season in its coach's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always special to come back home; it's with capital
letters,'' said Jarvis, 53, who spent a lot of time at The Heights,
scouting basketball games and once even picking the brains of BC's
football staff when he was a high school football coach. ``How
often does a guy get an opportunity to do that in front of your
wife and your mother and your family and friends _ in your own
backyard?
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston College has been very, very good for me for a long
time,'' he added. ``I don't think we ever lost a game here in high
school and it's kinda nice to know we can win a few in college as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   After suffering a 75-70 loss to Fairfield a week ago, the Eagles
(2-4, 0-1), who were led by Kenny Walls's career-high 18 points,
surged to a 9-point lead (24-15) on a 3-pointer by Clinton Sims
with 7:56 to go before intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing aggressively then we had a couple of missed
shots, a couple of calls, and then we got passive and started to
look away from the basket,'' said BC coach Al Skinner, whose team
went without a field goal in eight attempts and managed just 2
points in the final 7:56 of the half, shooting 19 for 57 overall.
``But the real difference was our shooting percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm (6-2, 1-0), who got double-figure scoring from
three starters, including a team-high 15 by Tyrone Grant, responded
by capitalizing on a five-minute BC scoring drought to go on a 12-0
run to build a 27-24 lead. They extended the run to 17-2 to take a
32-26 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just went into the locker room (at the half) and got a
little more focused,'' said St. John's Lavor Postell. ``They had a
little run in the first half, and then it was our turn to run.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's opened the second half by going on a 17-4 run,
scoring the last 12 points unanswered, to build a whopping 49-30
lead on Postell's 3-point dagger with 12:56 to go. The Eagles,
however, went on a 3-point binge, with Kenny Harley sandwiching two
of his own around a Walls trey to help BC pull within 10, 53-43,
with 7:10 to go. But it was as close as the Eagles got to ruining
Jarvis's homecoming when freshman guard Erick Barkley drilled a
clutch trey and followed with a pair of free throws to spark a
decisive 14-4 run that gave the Red Storm an insurmountable 67-47
lead that grew to as much as 24, 72-48.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that were happening then mostly were our fault,''
said Jarvis. ``We weren't carrying through with the defensive
assignments, we weren't finishing inside like we wanted to, we were
shooting too many jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the road, then you get scared, because then anything can
happen. And that's all I kept reminding the kids is that we're on
the road,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about their record. Forget about the fact that they're
rebuilding their program and forget about the fact we're in the Top
25. We're on the road, and they're not going to quit at home. So
we're just going to have to dig in and play the way we're supposed
to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
