<SLUG> BC-NEXT-HOT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR NEIGBORHOOD MAY BE NEXT TO ENJOY BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 and RYAN KONIG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be discouraged if home values in your neighborhood haven't
risen as sharply as in some areas of the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Your time may be coming.
</P>
<P>
   In some spots in metro Phoenix, home sales have been slow to
reach the boiling point, but it's heating up nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that most of the homes in the Valley increased in value
by 20 to 35 percent between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be as jaw-dropping as the numbers in the hottest
spots, which saw more than a 50 percent increase in value, but it's
not shabby. Compare the Phoenix area's increase to other U.S. home
markets; the average appreciation nationwide over that time was
under 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Much attention has focused on the sizzling home trade in such
areas as Arcadia and north-central Phoenix, where the landscape is
lush and neighborhoods are long-established.
</P>
<P>
   But real prosperity is on the way for some areas that haven't
had time to mature and appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's next home market hot spots are likely to be housing
hubs in Ahwatukee and Chandler in the East Valley, Goodyear in the
west Valley, Arrowhead on the Peoria/Glendale border and far north
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The number of home sales in those areas, and the short-term
rises in house prices, make it likely that these areas and a few
others will be coming into their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along the Valley's peripheries, there are areas that will
continue to grow and thrive and possibly become the Arcadia or
central Phoenix of tomorrow,'' said Jay Butler, director of the
Real Estate Center at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   He said there's definitely a symbiotic relationship between new
and older homes _ each helps pull up the value of the other.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of new homes have been built across the Valley in recent
years _ 150,000 since 1994 _ to create dozens of new housing hubs
and revitalize older neighbhorhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In the northwest Valley, the Arrowhead area is beginning to
boom, partly because of its new freeway access.
</P>
<P>
   The large housing area really started to evolve as Loop 101 was
completed, linking it to the rest of the Valley, according to
housing analyst R.L. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The area's relatively affordable upscale homes, shopping and
restaurants also have played a part in its growing attractiveness
for home shoppers. The typical price for a home in Arrowhead is
$144,000. Values in the area that includes ZIP codes 85308, 85381
and 85382 have been slow to grow. But the number of sales is high.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of the 17,500 single-family houses in
Arrowhead's main ZIP code (85308) have changed hands during the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
   In west Phoenix, a housing area reaching into Goodyear and
Litchfield Park and south to Avondale also is up-and-coming,
because of its affordable homes adjacent to such amenities as golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the homes in that area are new, so home building
analysts are forecasting values there won't start to take off for a
few years. The median price for a home in Goodyear's 85340 ZIP code
is $136,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these people have recently woken up and realized the west
Valley has great amenities, transportation and is affordable,''
said Carl Giordano, a realtor with Remax Sunset Valley.
</P>
<P>
   On the west side, ZIP code 85340 encompasses the community of
Palm Valley and several other growing developments. Its values are
flat, growing only about 10 percent since 1994. But sales there are
brisk; more than 40 percent of the 1,555 new and existing houses
there have sold since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   If some of the more popular home sales spots in the Valley
continue to grow and draw buyers, communities like Ahwatukee
Foothills could post 50 percent gains in value in the next five
years the way that Paradise Valley has done the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahwatukee, particularly the Foothills, is the Scottsdale of
the East Valley,'' said Mike Mendoza, a Realtor with Keller
Williams. ``There's no other spot with the upscale homes, good
schools and beautiful terrain in that part of the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Home values in the newest Ahwatukee area (ZIP code 85045) have
increased at a heady pace, though the area is still young. Homes
there have jumped in price nearly 30 percent since 1994 to reach a
median of $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The rest of Ahwatukee didn't do as well. But the area is still
a magnet for buyers. Most of the houses in the area spanning ZIP
codes 85044, 85045 and 85048 have sold at least once since being
built. Nearly 90 percent of the single-family houses in 85045 have
sold as either as new homes or resales during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the future of values in Ahwatukee depends on whether more
roadways are built to connect the homes to other parts of the
Valley, said Mendoza, who lives and specializes in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jams for commuters leaving and entering Ahwatukee have
deterred some buyers.
</P>
<P>
   But others have been lured by its acclaimed Kyrene school
district.
</P>
<P>
   In northeast Phoenix, both home sales and home prices are
growing steadily, and analysts expect that to continue.
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, homes north of the under-construction Pima
Freeway are likely to jump in value and sell like hotcakes during
the next five years as the roadway is completed.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell Mountain Ranch is part of the area and was the No.
2-selling master-planned community in the state last year after Sun
City Grand last year.
</P>
<P>
   Grayhawk is a popular golf community in the area, and DC Ranch
just recently started to sell homes but already has a long waiting
list of potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers are flocking to the area for the great lifestyle,
schools and family-friendly neighborhoods,'' said Yvonne Chrysokos
of Remax Achievers.
</P>
<P>
   Many homes in this part of north Scottsdale are upscale but not
as expensive as homes in Paradise Valley or northeast Scottsdale.
The price for a home in north Scottsdale runs about $195,000 in the
85331 ZIP code. In the part of Scottsdale adjacent Paradise Valley,
the median home price is $245,000. And in Paradise Valley, the
typical home sells for $565,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the newer home areas in the East Valley, such as
Chandler, Gilbert, East Mesa and Gold Canyon, have drawn scads of
buyers who want big new homes but don't want to pay huge prices.
</P>
<P>
   An average house costs $163,500 in the Chandler area around
Ocotillo. Gilbert is less; a typical home sells for $143,000. East
Mesa prices are comparable at $140,000 in the 85215 ZIP code. Homes
in the Gold Canyon and Apache Junction are the lowest price right
now, averaging about $97,000, but that likely will change because
of several upscale communities opening in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the prices across the East Valley have steadily risen
as the area's &UR; planned communities have filled up.
</P>
<P>
   ``New-home prices may have gone up in areas like Chandler, but
it still draws many people whose first pick for a house is the East
Valley,'' said Meg Shultz of Russ Lyon Realty. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
