<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLDSPOTS-AZR &LR;      12-05 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLDSPOTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW SPOTS EXPERIENCE PRICE DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 and RYAN KONIG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's tough to find a place in Phoenix or outlying areas where
home values haven't posted double-digit increases in the past five
years and sales aren't sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a few.
</P>
<P>
   The mostly farming communities of Gila Bend, Avondale and
Wittman were the only areas to post declines in home values from
1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The median price for homes in the 85337 ZIP code that includes
Gila Bend have dropped 8 percent since 1994 to $41,400. In
Avondale, which is ZIP code 85323, homes depreciated 6.8 percent,
to $115,000, and prices in Wittman (85361) decreased in value by 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale is the most likely of those areas to see values turn
around in the next few years. That's because the West Valley, south
of Interstate 10 and Goodyear, offers affordable new homes for
around $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The area around Sky Harbor International Airport, a place where
many homes vibrate from the strident thrumming of airline engines
overhead, had the fewest home sales in the five-year period. But
prices didn't suffer because it's an emerging commercial
real-estate hot spot.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 5 percent of homes, just 71 out of 1,433, in that area
(ZIP code 85034) have changed hands during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Connell, who inherited his 1,500-square-foot block home near
the airport from an uncle three years ago, isn't surprised by that
figure.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to the Valley from Seattle to live rent-free in the
house and work on a master's degree at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplanes are so loud, they kept me awake at night for the
first year after I moved in,'' Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's considered selling, but found that there are
few buyers for homes there.
</P>
<P>
   Although the airport area is waning in popularity for home
sales, it is a growing hub for office buildings and industrial
projects because of its prime location next to the airport and
several major freeways.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some homes there have been bought by commercial
developers who want the land for office space. As a result, the
median sales price for homes in the 85034 ZIP code has shot up 29
percent during the past five years, to $50,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
