<SLUG> BC-DATA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(SIDEBAR TO HOTHOMES) 
 METHODOLOGY FOR HOME PRICE STORIES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
For this package of stories and the accompanying maps and graphics,
The Arizona Republic used a computer analysis of median prices and
sales of new and existing homes throughout the Valley.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We used home-price data from Marketron Services Inc., a
Phoenix-based company, and Maricopa County Assessor records. We
also interviewed dozens of home-sale experts, including economists
and Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Through the computer analysis, we identified the Phoenix
metropolitan ZIP codes that showed the highest price increases
during the past five years for new and resale homes. We also were
able to calculate the percentage of homes that sold from 1994 to
1998. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-05-98 2309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981205.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5114 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      12-05 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S WHITE-COLLAR LYNCH
 ING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was an angry mob outside calling for blood, so the men in
suits (with patches on the elbows) dragged out convicted murderer
James Hamm and hanged him from their ivory tower.
</P>
<P>
   Only a day after Hamm had been hired to teach criminal justice
courses at Arizona State, officials at the school decided that
``reassigning Mr. Hamm to non-teaching duties is in the best
interest of the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you were one of the people who called ASU, demanding
Hamm's head on a platter. Maybe you're a truck driver or an electri
cian, a small businessman or secre tary or construction worker.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you didn't notice, but at the same time ASU's elite were
lynching Hamm, they were spitting in your face.
</P>
<P>
   And mine.
</P>
<P>
   James Hamm wasn't run out of the university for being a killer.
He was run out for being uppity.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to become a ``profes sional,'' and the suits would
have none of it. A guy like Hamm, they say, should only work in a
``non-teaching'' position.
</P>
<P>
   My father and grandfathers were in non-teaching positions. They
were steelworkers. All my uncles worked in the mills. So did I, the
summers I was in college.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching at a university is no more honorable than working in a
mill.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching has no more dignity.
</P>
<P>
   If it's OK for a one-time killer to work in a mill, or cut
grass, or fix a pipe, it should be OK to teach at a university. If
not, you insult every working stiff out there. `QUESTION OF
PREJUDICE'
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there is a class question here,'' Hamm told me
Friday. ``But there's also a question of prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   James Hamm admits his crime. He expresses remorse. He served 17
years in the state prison, and has graduated from college and the
ASU Law School. He is both a convicted murderer and an educated
man. Now that he's served his time, he wants to work.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are willing to let him have a job, it seems, but only
as long as he doesn't get to wear a suit.
</P>
<P>
   There's no other reason.
</P>
<P>
   We exclude ex-cons from some jobs for safety reasons. That isn't
a problem here. ASU officials admit it. The students Hamm would
have taught are older, more savvy, more able to challenge him.
Besides, he's never tried to hide his past. He couldn't if he
wanted to, and he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   All he wants to do is work, and we're saying no. At least, we're
saying he can't work in an area where he has some ability. We'd
prefer he did ``unskilled'' work.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning less desirable. Meaning less valuable. Meaning less
dignified. Meaning this isn't an ethics problem or morality
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pedigree problem.
</P>
<P>
   Either a man with a background like James Hamm deserves to work
or he doesn't. If we limit the types of jobs he can get for reasons
other than qualifications of safety concerns, it isn't the ex-con
who's being put down.
</P>
<P>
   It's us. HE ACCEPTS IT
</P>
<P>
   Hamm told me he understands and expects people to become emotion
ally involved in anything he tries to do. He accepts it.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``I still would like to be a professor. And I'm still
disappointed and still hurt at what they've done. But there is a
sense in which you say, let's take what we've got and let's make
something meaningful to other people. I want to come out of this
feeling like this wasn't a lose-lose situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids in the classes Hamm was to teach have learned more
about jus tice from the way Hamm was treated than from anything he
could have taught them.
</P>
<P>
   They've also learned that running a university is a highly
specialized profession, requiring advanced de grees in both
scaredy-cat and back sliding.
</P>
<P>
   And they've learned that ``class'' is something into which
students are divided. And something into which professions are
divided. And some thing which the people who do the dividing don't
often possess.
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
