<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENCY CHANGES HOT STOVE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some will say the Hot Stove League is back and better than ever,
with players jumping from club, trades taking place almost on a
daily basis and baseball talk dominating the cold winter months
from every point between Boston to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Others will argue, believing all these players hopping around
leads to fans becoming disinterested with their clubs. The makeup
of today's clubs changes every off-season to the point where it's
difficult to follow even your favorite club.
</P>
<P>
   It's a difficult line to walk if you're inside the inner circle
of baseball, where owners definitely want to please their fans and
shaking up the roster seems to be the best way to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The winter meetings begin later this week in Nashville. There
was a time when the winter meetings were cause to stop the sports
world. It was a time when nearly every trade that was going to
occur took place.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials have promised this year's winter meetings
will resemble those from days gone by, when fans across the country
scurried for their morning papers to see what transactions had
taken place. But with the flurry of activity that's taken place in
the last month, is there really anything left to do?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, free agency has changed the landscape of the game. It
wasn't really that long ago when, for example, the Detroit Tigers
would pretty much look the same from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Cash, Dick McAuliffe, Ray Oyler and Don Wert rounded out
the infield. The outfield had Willie Horton, Mickey Stanley, Al
Kaline as the primary starters with Jim Northrup serving as a
backup. Bill Freehan was always behind the plate and Denny McLain,
Mickey Lolich and Earl Wilson anchored the rotation for years.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a club and it was pretty much the same thing. Across the
country just about every club had its regulars. You knew they would
be back every year, as long as they produced. Players were the
property of their clubs, and that was that. If Horton's contract
was up and he wanted to look elsewhere, too bad. He couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Everything began changing when Curt Flood challenged baseball's
reserve clause in 1970. Flood wondered why, after playing 12
seasons for the St. Louis Cardinals, he couldn't switch clubs on
his own. After all, the guy working at Allied Signal is not
obligated to stay there his entire life. If Insight wants to hire
him for more money, they simply offer more money to lure the worker
away.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Flood wound up losing that court battle with the
Cardinals, one which went all the way to the Supreme Court, the
stage had been set for the inevitable. Within a few years free
agency was here to stay. The game has not been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   But before the purists start blaming Flood, who recently passed
away, for all the game's problems _ stop. It was inevitable that
the game's owners would have to allow players the freedom to work
elsewhere. Anyone who believes a player should be the property of
his club for life is simply living in the dark ages.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fallout from free agency was the advent of the
multiyear contract. It really didn't exist in the game before free
agency because there was no need for it. This is where those old
stories about a player walking into the owner's office asking for
more money came from.
</P>
<P>
   Before free agency a club had no need to offer more than a
one-year contract. In essence, the player's salary was truly
determined by what he did the previous season. Bad year, bad
contract. Good year, good contract.
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple theory that every player had to follow, even the
game's superstars, all the way from Babe Ruth to Willie Mays.
Everyone else had no choice but to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Once players were allowed to jump around, clubs naturally looked
to lock those players up for more than one season.
</P>
<P>
   It soon turned to the absurd, though. The most obvious example
was the $10 million, 10-year contract the Cleveland Indians gave
pitcher Wayne Garland after the 1976 season. Garland, a 20-game
winner the season before for Baltimore, went 28-48 while being
plagued by arm injuries in the next five seasons. He was forced to
retire just five years after signing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   There were other foolish examples, like the time Atlanta signed
catcher Biff Pocoroba to a seven-year deal. In all, several owners
started getting carried away with the newness of free agency, and
this is where the irony with today's signings takes place.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams just received a seven-year deal to remain with
the Yankees. Pitcher Kevin Brown wants a seven-year deal of his
own. First baseman Mo Vaughn just signed with Anaheim for six
years.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the players receiving the longest-term deals now can be
classified as superstars. Still, this is exactly how baseball's
problems in the late 1970s and early '80s began. Owners, indeed,
need to show a bit of restraint, which was the primary topic at
Thursday's owners meeting in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's the other side to the argument: If owners
couldn't afford these contracts they simply would not present them
to the players. It's a difficult argument to make when you see so
many owners coughing up unheard of amounts of money for the
services of a single player. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
