<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSTATE-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M BEATS KANSAS STATE, 36-33  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was a slant pass in the second overtime, from a
second-string quarterback to a second-team running back working at
flanker, that shuffled the rankings in the Bowl Championship
Series, not a computer program designed by a Ph.D. It was a
stiff-arm at the 1-yard line that will keep Kansas State out of the
national title game at the Fiesta Bowl, not penalty points for
strength of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When Branndon Stewart, a senior quarterback whose football
odyssey has taken him from the backup role behind Peyton Manning at
Tennessee to a benching earlier this season at Texas A&AMP;M, hit Sirr
Parker on the 28-yard line in double overtime of the Big 12
championship game, college football justice was carried to the end
zone on swift legs.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Aggie zigged inside cornerback Jerametrius Butler,
then zagged out to the corner and saved one punishing push to the
face of the Wildcats' Lamar Chapman that propelled him over the
goal line. The football barely brushed the flag. The Aggies had
barely beaten the Wildcats, 36-33, in a heart-stopping finish on a
heart-stopping final day of a memorable football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only 5-11, but I was 6 feet on that one,'' said Parker,
who caught a pass on the same pattern to bring the Aggies within
27-25 in regulation, then caught the 2-point conversion to send the
game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   What it means is this. When the BCS ranking comes out Sunday,
Florida State will join Tennessee in the national title game at the
Fiesta Bowl _ if the Volunteers won the Southeastern Conference
title game against Mississippi State Saturday night. UCLA, which
like Kansas State started the day unbeaten only to be upended by
Miami, 49-45, will go to the Rose Bowl against Wisconsin in a
suddenly traditional matchup of Pacific 10 and Big Ten champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East winner, Syracuse, will be in the Orange, maybe
against Florida, maybe against Kansas State. And the Aggies are in
the Sugar Bowl, perhaps against Ohio State. It also means that
Kansas State learned that the adage ``it ain't over until it's
over'' can be especially painful.
</P>
<P>
   They were ahead by 14 points with 10 minutes 37 seconds left in
the first half when the public-address announcer informed the more
than 60,000 people _ most of them dressed in the purple of Kansas
State _ at the Trans World Dome that UCLA had lost. It came seconds
after quarterback Michael Bishop had heaved a 66-yard bomb to
Darnell McDonald. The crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas State players beamed smiles and slapped high fives.
They had come into this game ranked third in the BCS and needed
either Tennessee or the Bruins to lose. They got it. They
celebrated, and the Aggies across the field steamed. But neither
states of mind lasted long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very evident that we are tremendously disappointed. This
is a big hurt for our coaches, players and fans. I have so much
pride in the players and fans,'' Kansas State Coach Bill Snyder
began after the game. Then his voice cracked, and he cried. With
him was Bishop, running back Eric Hickson and linebacker Jeff
Kelly. They cried, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so much pride in these players,'' Snyder continued.
``This may be the most difficult thing to happen in their young
lives that they have been forced to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats essentially collapsed on themselves. They outgained
Texas A&AMP;M, 519 yards to 452, but racked up 110 yards on penalties
and turned the ball over three times. The biggest was on third down
with 2:22 left in the game. Bishop, who threw for 341 yards and 2
touchdowns and ran for another, appeared to pick up the first down
that would have allowed the Wildcats to run out the clock, but
linebacker Warrick Holdman knocked the ball loose and Cornelius
Anthony recovered on the 35-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sick feeling,'' a devastated Bishop said after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was replacing an injured Randy McCown after losing
his job to him after the fifth game, slung a sidearm pass down the
field to a streaking Matt Bumgardner. He lunged for the ball and
caught it on the 14-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Twice earlier in the game, the Aggies had to settle for field
goals after having the ball inside the 10-yard line. On third-and-9
from the 9-yard line, Stewart this time found Parker, who cut in
front of strong safety Jarrod Cooper at the goal line and caught
the touchdown pass to bring the Aggies within 27-25. Stewart again
went to Parker for the 2-point conversion, this time on a
play-action rollout that left Parker alone in the end zone to tie
the score at 27-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was going to play ever again,'' said the
senior quarterback, who was 15 of 31 for 324 yards and 3
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Randy was doing a great job. But when I knew I'd get
the start I couldn't wait to get out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
