<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE WASTES A CHANCE FOR PROMINENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Opportunity No. 1 is gone. Wasted would be an
appropriate way of putting it. Three more chances exist this month
for the Waves to gain prominence. That's what they've been talking
about since October.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's 62-55 loss to No.7 Kansas on Saturday in the Wooden
Classic was its best chance for stardom, but Wisconsin offers
visibility next Saturday. Michigan State does the same Dec.21.
Ditto for Rhode Island on Dec.29.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game we were looking forward to playing for a long
time,'' Pepperdine guard David Lalazarian said. ``We knew what it
meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine has talked about being a Top 25 team this season, and
the Waves also mentioned that anything short of a West Coast
Conference title and an NCAA berth would be unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to become a force on a higher level, Pepperdine
must beat a high-profile, top echelon team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we were a team that could beat Kansas and we feel
like we're a team that could beat Wisconsin and a team that can
beat Michigan State,'' Pepperdine point guard Jelani Gardner said.
``(The loss) lets us know we have to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice to see you: Before, during and after the game, Waves center
Nick Sheppard and Jayhawks forward Lester Earl chatted.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a while since they've seen each other. Both played at
Louisiana State during the 1996-97 season before transferring to
their current schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got his phone number before I left after the game,''
Sheppard said. ``We were friends. We hung out together. It was just
good to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl, bothered recently by a sore knee, scored four points in 14
minutes. Sheppard had two points and eight rebounds but missed all
six of his shots from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Foul shots: Forward Marc McDowell led Pepperdine in scoring, but
was held 10 points beneath his average with two points.... The
Waves had only six assists.... Pepperdine is yet to play outside
California.... Kansas center Eric Chenowith, from nearby Villa
Park, had 10 points but played only seven minutes in the second
half because of foul trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
