A5126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-CHAMPS-COX     12-05 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-CHAMPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols roll in the fourth to win title
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee won its second consecutive conference championship and
in the process may have scheduled a date with Destiny as the
Volunteers stormed from behind in the final seven minutes to defeat
Mississippi State 24-14 in the 1998 SEC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (12-0), ranked No. 1 in the Associated Press poll,
will receive an invitation from the Fiesta Bowl today where the
Volunteers will get the opportunity to play for their first
national championship since 1951. Tennessee will not know its
opponent until the official Bowl Championship Series pairings are
released at 3:30 p.m. today on ABC. With No. 2 UCLA and No. 3
Kansas State both losing on Saturday, the Volunteers will likely
face Forida State (11-1) on Jan. 4 in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's hopes and dreams for an entire season seemed to be
on the ropes with 8:43 left in the game when Mississippi State's
Kevin Prentiss returned a punt 83 yards for a touchdown. That gave
the Bulldogs a 14-10 lead against a Tennessee team had had
struggled on offense for most of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee struck back with cold-blooded precision as
quarterback Tee Martin found Peerless Price open for a perfect
41-yard touchdown strike that gave the Volunteers a 17-14 lead with
less than six mintues remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then , on Mississippi State's very next possession, the Bulldogs
fumbled and Tennesee recovered at the 26. The Volunteers did not
hesitate as Martin hit Cedrick Wilson for a touchdown on the very
first play giving UT control of the game and consecutive SEC titles
for the first time since 1989-90.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's offense played it close to the vest all night as
Martin found himself under constant pressure by Mississippi State's
constantly blitzing defense. But as the Volunteers had done all
season, beginning with the last-second victory over Syracuse, the
Volunteers found a way to win when the game was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are just one victory away from the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   With Tennessee leading 10-7, both teams continued to play it
close to the vest going into the fourth quarter, waiting for the
other team to make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee used a 20-yard run by Travis Henry to move out to its
44-yard line. But facing a third and eight at that point,
Mississippi State blitzed quarterback Tee Martin, who threw wide
and Tennessee had to kick.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Mississippi State's Kevin Prentiss gathered in the
punt at his own 12-yard line and sprinted down his own sideline for
a touchdown, giving the Bulldogs a14-10 lead and cranking up the
noise at the Georgia Dome to yet another level.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 10-7 at halftime, Tennessee had an apparent touchdown
midway through the third quarter when linebacker Al Wilson
intercepted a pass and returned it 33 yards. But the Volunteers
were called for a block in the back and took possession at the
Mississippi State 33.
</P>
<P>
   On the second play from scrimmage Tennessee's Travis Henry
fumbled and Mississippi State recovered, killing the scoring
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   That play was the only thing resembling any kind of offense and
both teams slugged out defensively the rest of the way and
Tennessee was clinging to its three-point lead as the final period
began.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
